ompression_ratio": 1.5387755102040817, "no_speech_prob": 1.404809428506848e-12}, {"id": 32, "seek": 11500, "start": 137.94, "end": 138.36, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51512, 7587, 13, 51533], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1829412394556506, "compression_ratio": 1.5387755102040817, "no_speech_prob": 1.404809428506848e-12}, {"id": 33, "seek": 13836, "start": 138.36, "end": 148.06, "text": " In standard functional paradigms, when you have, say, deeply nested asynchronous functions, all trying to resolve probabilities simultaneously.", "tokens": [50365, 682, 3832, 11745, 13480, 328, 2592, 11, 562, 291, 362, 11, 584, 11, 8760, 15646, 292, 49174, 6828, 11, 439, 1382, 281, 14151, 33783, 16561, 13, 50850], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 34, "seek": 13836, "start": 148.56, "end": 150.20000000000002, "text": " Like a dozen things happening at once.", "tokens": [50875, 1743, 257, 16654, 721, 2737, 412, 1564, 13, 50957], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 35, "seek": 13836, "start": 150.32000000000002, "end": 150.54000000000002, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50963, 1779, 13, 50974], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 36, "seek": 13836, "start": 150.66000000000003, "end": 154.18, "text": " The text-based syntax just becomes this massive bottleneck.", "tokens": [50980, 440, 2487, 12, 6032, 28431, 445, 3643, 341, 5994, 44641, 547, 13, 51156], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 37, "seek": 13836, "start": 154.64000000000001, "end": 158.66000000000003, "text": " SBC replaces that bottleneck with four geometric primitives.", "tokens": [51179, 318, 7869, 46734, 300, 44641, 547, 365, 1451, 33246, 2886, 38970, 13, 51380], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 38, "seek": 13836, "start": 158.74, "end": 159.68, "text": " Okay, four primitives.", "tokens": [51384, 1033, 11, 1451, 2886, 38970, 13, 51431], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 39, "seek": 13836, "start": 159.76000000000002, "end": 160.60000000000002, "text": " Let's break those down.", "tokens": [51435, 961, 311, 1821, 729, 760, 13, 51477], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 40, "seek": 13836, "start": 160.72000000000003, "end": 161.98000000000002, "text": " So the first one is the sphere.", "tokens": [51483, 407, 264, 700, 472, 307, 264, 16687, 13, 51546], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 41, "seek": 13836, "start": 162.42000000000002, "end": 166.18, "text": " When you define an abstraction, you are basically blowing a geometric bubble.", "tokens": [51568, 1133, 291, 6964, 364, 37765, 11, 291, 366, 1936, 15068, 257, 33246, 12212, 13, 51756], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 42, "seek": 13836, "start": 166.3, "end": 167.22000000000003, "text": " Like blowing a soap bubble.", "tokens": [51762, 1743, 15068, 257, 14587, 12212, 13, 51808], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1402955602426998, "compression_ratio": 1.6390728476821192, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918455789631913e-12}, {"id": 43, "seek": 16722, "start": 167.22, "end": 167.62, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50365, 865, 13, 50385], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 44, "seek": 16722, "start": 167.96, "end": 171.9, "text": " And the interior of that bubble encapsulates the computational state.", "tokens": [50402, 400, 264, 10636, 295, 300, 12212, 38745, 26192, 264, 28270, 1785, 13, 50599], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 45, "seek": 16722, "start": 172.1, "end": 172.7, "text": " Okay, got it.", "tokens": [50609, 1033, 11, 658, 309, 13, 50639], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 46, "seek": 16722, "start": 172.72, "end": 174.18, "text": " So the first primitive is the sphere.", "tokens": [50640, 407, 264, 700, 28540, 307, 264, 16687, 13, 50713], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 47, "seek": 16722, "start": 174.8, "end": 176.76, "text": " And the second primitive, logically, is the pop.", "tokens": [50744, 400, 264, 1150, 28540, 11, 38887, 11, 307, 264, 1665, 13, 50842], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 48, "seek": 16722, "start": 177.04, "end": 177.36, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50856, 1779, 13, 50872], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 49, "seek": 16722, "start": 177.48, "end": 180.98, "text": " In standard terms, I guess this is application or beta reduction.", "tokens": [50878, 682, 3832, 2115, 11, 286, 2041, 341, 307, 3861, 420, 9861, 11004, 13, 51053], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 50, "seek": 16722, "start": 181.18, "end": 181.88, "text": " Yes, exactly.", "tokens": [51063, 1079, 11, 2293, 13, 51098], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 51, "seek": 16722, "start": 182.2, "end": 184.84, "text": " It's the moment a function actually receives its argument.", "tokens": [51114, 467, 311, 264, 1623, 257, 2445, 767, 20717, 1080, 6770, 13, 51246], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 52, "seek": 16722, "start": 185.26, "end": 189.12, "text": " But Fluxinian treats the pop as a literal physical event, right?", "tokens": [51267, 583, 3235, 2449, 259, 952, 19566, 264, 1665, 382, 257, 20411, 4001, 2280, 11, 558, 30, 51460], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 53, "seek": 16722, "start": 189.3, "end": 196.1, "text": " The bubble bursts, it collapses its boundary, and it releases its evaluated state into the surrounding environment.", "tokens": [51469, 440, 12212, 41663, 11, 309, 48765, 1080, 12866, 11, 293, 309, 16952, 1080, 25509, 1785, 666, 264, 11498, 2823, 13, 51809], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.157601997256279, "compression_ratio": 1.66006600660066, "no_speech_prob": 1.3248625287121119e-12}, {"id": 54, "seek": 19610, "start": 196.1, "end": 202.18, "text": " Yeah, but the transition from a sphere to a pop isn't just instantaneous in the mathematics.", "tokens": [50365, 865, 11, 457, 264, 6034, 490, 257, 16687, 281, 257, 1665, 1943, 380, 445, 45596, 294, 264, 18666, 13, 50669], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 55, "seek": 19610, "start": 202.35999999999999, "end": 203.01999999999998, "text": " It's not magic.", "tokens": [50678, 467, 311, 406, 5585, 13, 50711], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 56, "seek": 19610, "start": 203.34, "end": 203.48, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50727, 1033, 13, 50734], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 57, "seek": 19610, "start": 203.62, "end": 204.38, "text": " How does it work then?", "tokens": [50741, 1012, 775, 309, 589, 550, 30, 50779], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 58, "seek": 19610, "start": 204.94, "end": 210.12, "text": " So Fluxin situates this entire calculus inside what they call the RSVP framework.", "tokens": [50807, 407, 3235, 2449, 259, 2054, 1024, 341, 2302, 33400, 1854, 437, 436, 818, 264, 25855, 53, 47, 8388, 13, 51066], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 59, "seek": 19610, "start": 210.56, "end": 211.04, "text": " RSVP.", "tokens": [51088, 25855, 53, 47, 13, 51112], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 60, "seek": 19610, "start": 211.1, "end": 211.35999999999999, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [51115, 1033, 13, 51128], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 61, "seek": 19610, "start": 211.62, "end": 215.48, "text": " Which stands for Relativistic Scalar Vector Plenum, right?", "tokens": [51141, 3013, 7382, 337, 8738, 10662, 3142, 2747, 12031, 691, 20814, 2149, 268, 449, 11, 558, 30, 51334], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 62, "seek": 19610, "start": 215.51999999999998, "end": 216.06, "text": " That's the one.", "tokens": [51336, 663, 311, 264, 472, 13, 51363], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16943170586410833, "compression_ratio": 1.4299065420560748, "no_speech_prob": 1.4664851364504239e-12}, {"id": 63, "seek": 21606, "start": 216.06, "end": 221.84, "text": " The plenum is this smooth, continuous mathematical space where computation actually executes.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 499, 268, 449, 307, 341, 5508, 11, 10957, 18894, 1901, 689, 24903, 767, 4454, 1819, 13, 50654], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 64, "seek": 21606, "start": 222.26, "end": 223.06, "text": " Smooth and continuous.", "tokens": [50675, 42404, 293, 10957, 13, 50715], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 65, "seek": 21606, "start": 223.26, "end": 223.46, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50725, 1779, 13, 50735], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 66, "seek": 21606, "start": 223.64000000000001, "end": 228.44, "text": " So when a sphere pops, it follows what they call a curvature-minimizing evolution.", "tokens": [50744, 407, 562, 257, 16687, 16795, 11, 309, 10002, 437, 436, 818, 257, 37638, 12, 2367, 332, 3319, 9303, 13, 50984], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 67, "seek": 21606, "start": 228.66, "end": 234.12, "text": " Okay, let's explore that curvature-minimizing evolution because I know the papers define it using something called the pop derivative.", "tokens": [50995, 1033, 11, 718, 311, 6839, 300, 37638, 12, 2367, 332, 3319, 9303, 570, 286, 458, 264, 10577, 6964, 309, 1228, 746, 1219, 264, 1665, 13760, 13, 51268], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 68, "seek": 21606, "start": 234.34, "end": 234.66, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51279, 1079, 13, 51295], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1141519205910819, "compression_ratio": 1.5871559633027523, "no_speech_prob": 1.432729477592043e-12}, {"id": 69, "seek": 23466, "start": 234.66, "end": 245.1, "text": " And if computation is happening in this smooth plenum, the boundary of the sphere, it represents this sort of tension, right, between the internal evaluated state and the external environment.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 498, 24903, 307, 2737, 294, 341, 5508, 499, 268, 449, 11, 264, 12866, 295, 264, 16687, 11, 309, 8855, 341, 1333, 295, 8980, 11, 558, 11, 1296, 264, 6920, 25509, 1785, 293, 264, 8320, 2823, 13, 50887], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 70, "seek": 23466, "start": 245.3, "end": 246.8, "text": " Yeah, think of the calculus of variations.", "tokens": [50897, 865, 11, 519, 295, 264, 33400, 295, 17840, 13, 50972], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 71, "seek": 23466, "start": 247.0, "end": 249.42, "text": " Like if you have a wireframe and you dip it in soapy water.", "tokens": [50982, 1743, 498, 291, 362, 257, 6234, 17265, 293, 291, 10460, 309, 294, 14587, 88, 1281, 13, 51103], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 72, "seek": 23466, "start": 249.64, "end": 250.12, "text": " Oh, right.", "tokens": [51114, 876, 11, 558, 13, 51138], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 73, "seek": 23466, "start": 250.22, "end": 251.98, "text": " The soap film naturally forms a shape.", "tokens": [51143, 440, 14587, 2007, 8195, 6422, 257, 3909, 13, 51231], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 74, "seek": 23466, "start": 252.1, "end": 252.48, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51237, 7587, 13, 51256], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 75, "seek": 23466, "start": 252.66, "end": 256.14, "text": " It forms a shape that minimizes surface area and surface tension.", "tokens": [51265, 467, 6422, 257, 3909, 300, 4464, 5660, 3753, 1859, 293, 3753, 8980, 13, 51439], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 76, "seek": 23466, "start": 256.56, "end": 259.44, "text": " It's physically calculating the optimal geometry.", "tokens": [51460, 467, 311, 9762, 28258, 264, 16252, 18426, 13, 51604], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 77, "seek": 23466, "start": 259.68, "end": 260.54, "text": " Just by existing.", "tokens": [51616, 1449, 538, 6741, 13, 51659], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 78, "seek": 23466, "start": 260.7, "end": 261.46, "text": " That's so cool.", "tokens": [51667, 663, 311, 370, 1627, 13, 51705], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 79, "seek": 23466, "start": 261.54, "end": 261.74, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51709, 1779, 13, 51719], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1358687805406975, "compression_ratio": 1.6430868167202572, "no_speech_prob": 1.5245685573359036e-12}, {"id": 80, "seek": 26174, "start": 261.74, "end": 263.98, "text": " And the pop derivative works similarly.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 264, 1665, 13760, 1985, 14138, 13, 50477], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 81, "seek": 26174, "start": 264.68, "end": 269.54, "text": " When the boundary of that computational sphere collapses, there is an energetic discrepancy.", "tokens": [50512, 1133, 264, 12866, 295, 300, 28270, 16687, 48765, 11, 456, 307, 364, 24935, 2983, 265, 6040, 1344, 13, 50755], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 82, "seek": 26174, "start": 269.94, "end": 271.18, "text": " Like a differential in state.", "tokens": [50775, 1743, 257, 15756, 294, 1785, 13, 50837], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 83, "seek": 26174, "start": 271.42, "end": 272.16, "text": " Yeah, exactly.", "tokens": [50849, 865, 11, 2293, 13, 50886], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 84, "seek": 26174, "start": 272.28000000000003, "end": 273.78000000000003, "text": " Between the inside and the outside.", "tokens": [50892, 18967, 264, 1854, 293, 264, 2380, 13, 50967], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 85, "seek": 26174, "start": 274.32, "end": 279.3, "text": " So the pop derivative models how that burst of computational coherence propagates outward.", "tokens": [50994, 407, 264, 1665, 13760, 5245, 577, 300, 12712, 295, 28270, 26528, 655, 12425, 1024, 26914, 13, 51243], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 86, "seek": 26174, "start": 279.56, "end": 280.7, "text": " So it's like ripples in a pond.", "tokens": [51256, 407, 309, 311, 411, 367, 37674, 294, 257, 17384, 13, 51313], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 87, "seek": 26174, "start": 281.16, "end": 288.82, "text": " Kind of, but it settles into a new topological shape of minimal resistance within the directed acyclic graph.", "tokens": [51336, 9242, 295, 11, 457, 309, 5584, 904, 666, 257, 777, 1192, 4383, 3909, 295, 13206, 7335, 1951, 264, 12898, 696, 88, 66, 1050, 4295, 13, 51719], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15664210620227162, "compression_ratio": 1.651851851851852, "no_speech_prob": 1.655500714813074e-12}, {"id": 88, "seek": 28882, "start": 288.82, "end": 293.59999999999997, "text": " The computation literally flows down the path of least mathematical resistance.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 24903, 3736, 12867, 760, 264, 3100, 295, 1935, 18894, 7335, 13, 50604], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 89, "seek": 28882, "start": 293.96, "end": 294.21999999999997, "text": " Wow.", "tokens": [50622, 3153, 13, 50635], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 90, "seek": 28882, "start": 294.52, "end": 296.21999999999997, "text": " Okay, so we have the sphere and the pop.", "tokens": [50650, 1033, 11, 370, 321, 362, 264, 16687, 293, 264, 1665, 13, 50735], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 91, "seek": 28882, "start": 296.36, "end": 301.92, "text": " The third and fourth primitives are where this geometric approach really starts to show its power.", "tokens": [50742, 440, 2636, 293, 6409, 2886, 38970, 366, 689, 341, 33246, 3109, 534, 3719, 281, 855, 1080, 1347, 13, 51020], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 92, "seek": 28882, "start": 302.18, "end": 302.62, "text": " Absolutely.", "tokens": [51033, 7021, 13, 51055], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 93, "seek": 28882, "start": 303.02, "end": 304.3, "text": " We've got merge and choice.", "tokens": [51075, 492, 600, 658, 22183, 293, 3922, 13, 51139], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 94, "seek": 28882, "start": 304.7, "end": 306.34, "text": " So merge is parallel composition.", "tokens": [51159, 407, 22183, 307, 8952, 12686, 13, 51241], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 95, "seek": 28882, "start": 307.06, "end": 311.44, "text": " Two independent bubbles come together and fuse, which models concurrent execution.", "tokens": [51277, 4453, 6695, 16295, 808, 1214, 293, 31328, 11, 597, 5245, 37702, 15058, 13, 51496], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 96, "seek": 28882, "start": 311.6, "end": 311.76, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51504, 1779, 13, 51512], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1669879626202327, "compression_ratio": 1.5582329317269077, "no_speech_prob": 1.5580197722242506e-12}, {"id": 97, "seek": 31176, "start": 311.76, "end": 313.24, "text": " They just blend into each other.", "tokens": [50365, 814, 445, 10628, 666, 1184, 661, 13, 50439], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1388795018196106, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.5853012262298516e-12}, {"id": 98, "seek": 31176, "start": 313.24, "end": 322.14, "text": " And then choice introduces stochastic branching, creating a distribution of possibilities within the geometry itself.", "tokens": [50439, 400, 550, 3922, 31472, 342, 8997, 2750, 9819, 278, 11, 4084, 257, 7316, 295, 12178, 1951, 264, 18426, 2564, 13, 50884], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1388795018196106, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.5853012262298516e-12}, {"id": 99, "seek": 31176, "start": 322.62, "end": 327.96, "text": " And this is exactly where the RSVP geometry solves a major, major headache in concurrent probability.", "tokens": [50908, 400, 341, 307, 2293, 689, 264, 25855, 53, 47, 18426, 39890, 257, 2563, 11, 2563, 23520, 294, 37702, 8482, 13, 51175], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1388795018196106, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.5853012262298516e-12}, {"id": 100, "seek": 31176, "start": 328.26, "end": 328.68, "text": " How so?", "tokens": [51190, 1012, 370, 30, 51211], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1388795018196106, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.5853012262298516e-12}, {"id": 101, "seek": 31176, "start": 328.98, "end": 332.38, "text": " Well, let's look at the independent channels lemma that they presented in the texts.", "tokens": [51226, 1042, 11, 718, 311, 574, 412, 264, 6695, 9235, 7495, 1696, 300, 436, 8212, 294, 264, 15765, 13, 51396], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1388795018196106, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.5853012262298516e-12}, {"id": 102, "seek": 33238, "start": 332.38, "end": 343.8, "text": " If you have a highly complex system with concurrent probabilistic events, say you've got dozens of branches merging, and each brand has a certain localized probability of failure.", "tokens": [50365, 759, 291, 362, 257, 5405, 3997, 1185, 365, 37702, 31959, 3142, 3931, 11, 584, 291, 600, 658, 18431, 295, 14770, 44559, 11, 293, 1184, 3360, 575, 257, 1629, 44574, 8482, 295, 7763, 13, 50936], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07812532537123736, "compression_ratio": 1.5450980392156863, "no_speech_prob": 1.7827769425646234e-12}, {"id": 103, "seek": 33238, "start": 344.24, "end": 350.98, "text": " Calculating the aggregate risk of a catastrophic failure across that whole system is usually incredibly taxing.", "tokens": [50958, 3511, 2444, 990, 264, 26118, 3148, 295, 257, 34915, 7763, 2108, 300, 1379, 1185, 307, 2673, 6252, 3366, 278, 13, 51295], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07812532537123736, "compression_ratio": 1.5450980392156863, "no_speech_prob": 1.7827769425646234e-12}, {"id": 104, "seek": 33238, "start": 351.04, "end": 351.62, "text": " Oh, it's a nightmare.", "tokens": [51298, 876, 11, 309, 311, 257, 18724, 13, 51327], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07812532537123736, "compression_ratio": 1.5450980392156863, "no_speech_prob": 1.7827769425646234e-12}, {"id": 105, "seek": 33238, "start": 351.8, "end": 355.38, "text": " You have to account for overlapping states, conditional dependencies, all of it.", "tokens": [51336, 509, 362, 281, 2696, 337, 33535, 4368, 11, 27708, 36606, 11, 439, 295, 309, 13, 51515], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07812532537123736, "compression_ratio": 1.5450980392156863, "no_speech_prob": 1.7827769425646234e-12}, {"id": 106, "seek": 35538, "start": 355.38, "end": 364.74, "text": " Right. Standard error handling would require you to build these massive, clunky, external architectures just to monitor the failure states of all the individual threads.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 21298, 6713, 13175, 576, 3651, 291, 281, 1322, 613, 5994, 11, 596, 25837, 11, 8320, 6331, 1303, 445, 281, 6002, 264, 7763, 4368, 295, 439, 264, 2609, 19314, 13, 50833], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 107, "seek": 35538, "start": 364.86, "end": 369.54, "text": " But in SpherePop, merge is mathematically treated as a geometric tensor product.", "tokens": [50839, 583, 294, 318, 6605, 38677, 11, 22183, 307, 44003, 8668, 382, 257, 33246, 40863, 1674, 13, 51073], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 108, "seek": 35538, "start": 369.65999999999997, "end": 370.38, "text": " A tensor product.", "tokens": [51079, 316, 40863, 1674, 13, 51115], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 109, "seek": 35538, "start": 370.58, "end": 374.74, "text": " Yeah. It is a literal fusing of independent probabilistic spaces.", "tokens": [51125, 865, 13, 467, 307, 257, 20411, 283, 7981, 295, 6695, 31959, 3142, 7673, 13, 51333], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 110, "seek": 35538, "start": 375.52, "end": 380.18, "text": " So the risk calculation becomes an inherent property of the geometry itself.", "tokens": [51372, 407, 264, 3148, 17108, 3643, 364, 26387, 4707, 295, 264, 18426, 2564, 13, 51605], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 111, "seek": 35538, "start": 380.26, "end": 382.12, "text": " So you don't need the external architecture at all.", "tokens": [51609, 407, 291, 500, 380, 643, 264, 8320, 9482, 412, 439, 13, 51702], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 112, "seek": 35538, "start": 382.3, "end": 382.82, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51711, 7587, 13, 51737], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13958913143550125, "compression_ratio": 1.6503496503496504, "no_speech_prob": 1.7487164060553395e-12}, {"id": 113, "seek": 38282, "start": 382.82, "end": 392.71999999999997, "text": " The independent channels lemma demonstrates that you can evaluate the aggregate disjunctive risk, which the papers cheerfully term doom, by the way.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 6695, 9235, 7495, 1696, 31034, 300, 291, 393, 13059, 264, 26118, 717, 10010, 20221, 3148, 11, 597, 264, 10577, 12581, 2277, 1433, 37131, 11, 538, 264, 636, 13, 50860], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 114, "seek": 38282, "start": 393.15999999999997, "end": 396.86, "text": " Doom. I love that. Very dramatic for a math paper.", "tokens": [50882, 30168, 13, 286, 959, 300, 13, 4372, 12023, 337, 257, 5221, 3035, 13, 51067], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 115, "seek": 38282, "start": 397.02, "end": 401.12, "text": " Right. But you can calculate doom just by looking at the survival probabilities.", "tokens": [51075, 1779, 13, 583, 291, 393, 8873, 37131, 445, 538, 1237, 412, 264, 12559, 33783, 13, 51280], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 116, "seek": 38282, "start": 401.24, "end": 401.7, "text": " Okay, right.", "tokens": [51286, 1033, 11, 558, 13, 51309], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 117, "seek": 38282, "start": 401.8, "end": 401.94, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51314, 865, 13, 51321], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 118, "seek": 38282, "start": 402.03999999999996, "end": 409.84, "text": " So rather than trying to add up all the probabilities of failure, which, you know, gets mathematically tangled if the channels aren't perfectly orthogonal.", "tokens": [51326, 407, 2831, 813, 1382, 281, 909, 493, 439, 264, 33783, 295, 7763, 11, 597, 11, 291, 458, 11, 2170, 44003, 47192, 498, 264, 9235, 3212, 380, 6239, 41488, 13, 51716], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 119, "seek": 38282, "start": 410.03999999999996, "end": 410.24, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51726, 865, 13, 51736], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15649847550825638, "compression_ratio": 1.6118881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5984703794977295e-12}, {"id": 120, "seek": 41024, "start": 410.24, "end": 420.52, "text": " You look at the inverse. If you have multiple independent bubbles merging, you calculate the probability that each individual branch actually survives.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 574, 412, 264, 17340, 13, 759, 291, 362, 3866, 6695, 16295, 44559, 11, 291, 8873, 264, 8482, 300, 1184, 2609, 9819, 767, 46231, 13, 50879], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08887513726949692, "compression_ratio": 1.645631067961165, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489103055710274e-12}, {"id": 121, "seek": 41024, "start": 420.78000000000003, "end": 421.12, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50892, 1079, 13, 50909], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08887513726949692, "compression_ratio": 1.645631067961165, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489103055710274e-12}, {"id": 122, "seek": 41024, "start": 421.32, "end": 431.32, "text": " And then you take the product of all those independent survival probabilities. That product represents the chance that the entire merge system successfully navigates the computation.", "tokens": [50919, 400, 550, 291, 747, 264, 1674, 295, 439, 729, 6695, 12559, 33783, 13, 663, 1674, 8855, 264, 2931, 300, 264, 2302, 22183, 1185, 10727, 7407, 1024, 264, 24903, 13, 51419], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08887513726949692, "compression_ratio": 1.645631067961165, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489103055710274e-12}, {"id": 123, "seek": 43132, "start": 431.32, "end": 438.94, "text": " Exactly. And the probability of a system-wide disjunctive failure doom is simply one minus that total survival product.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 400, 264, 8482, 295, 257, 1185, 12, 7990, 717, 10010, 20221, 7763, 37131, 307, 2935, 472, 3175, 300, 3217, 12559, 1674, 13, 50746], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11894613024832189, "compression_ratio": 1.5433070866141732, "no_speech_prob": 1.382730627046136e-12}, {"id": 124, "seek": 43132, "start": 439.02, "end": 440.06, "text": " That's incredibly elegant.", "tokens": [50750, 663, 311, 6252, 21117, 13, 50802], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11894613024832189, "compression_ratio": 1.5433070866141732, "no_speech_prob": 1.382730627046136e-12}, {"id": 125, "seek": 43132, "start": 440.44, "end": 446.24, "text": " It really is. The elegance is that the execution engine doesn't need a heavy separate error checking module.", "tokens": [50821, 467, 534, 307, 13, 440, 14459, 719, 307, 300, 264, 15058, 2848, 1177, 380, 643, 257, 4676, 4994, 6713, 8568, 10088, 13, 51111], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11894613024832189, "compression_ratio": 1.5433070866141732, "no_speech_prob": 1.382730627046136e-12}, {"id": 126, "seek": 43132, "start": 447.02, "end": 454.78, "text": " By treating the merge as a physical blending of continuous spaces, the risk aggregation is solved by the physics of the calculus itself.", "tokens": [51150, 3146, 15083, 264, 22183, 382, 257, 4001, 23124, 295, 10957, 7673, 11, 264, 3148, 16743, 399, 307, 13041, 538, 264, 10649, 295, 264, 33400, 2564, 13, 51538], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11894613024832189, "compression_ratio": 1.5433070866141732, "no_speech_prob": 1.382730627046136e-12}, {"id": 127, "seek": 45478, "start": 454.78, "end": 466.11999999999995, "text": " But wait, let me play devil's advocate here. If we treat computation as these floating merging bubbles of probabilistic logic and we remove all those rigid textual constraints.", "tokens": [50365, 583, 1699, 11, 718, 385, 862, 13297, 311, 14608, 510, 13, 759, 321, 2387, 24903, 382, 613, 12607, 44559, 16295, 295, 31959, 3142, 9952, 293, 321, 4159, 439, 729, 22195, 2487, 901, 18491, 13, 50932], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17789989426022484, "compression_ratio": 1.3, "no_speech_prob": 1.8606513899066535e-12}, {"id": 128, "seek": 45478, "start": 466.32, "end": 466.55999999999995, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50942, 865, 13, 50954], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17789989426022484, "compression_ratio": 1.3, "no_speech_prob": 1.8606513899066535e-12}, {"id": 129, "seek": 46656, "start": 466.56, "end": 479.54, "text": " We run into a major architectural problem, don't we? Like if an environment variable that's holding a highly sensitive database key just arbitrarily merges with an untrusted public output stream, we have a critical security flaw.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 1190, 666, 257, 2563, 26621, 1154, 11, 500, 380, 321, 30, 1743, 498, 364, 2823, 7006, 300, 311, 5061, 257, 5405, 9477, 8149, 2141, 445, 19071, 3289, 3551, 2880, 365, 364, 1701, 81, 6589, 1908, 5598, 4309, 11, 321, 362, 257, 4924, 3825, 13717, 13, 51014], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07329964939552018, "compression_ratio": 1.4481327800829875, "no_speech_prob": 1.6549089572673314e-12}, {"id": 130, "seek": 46656, "start": 479.84000000000003, "end": 479.96, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51029, 865, 13, 51035], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07329964939552018, "compression_ratio": 1.4481327800829875, "no_speech_prob": 1.6549089572673314e-12}, {"id": 131, "seek": 46656, "start": 480.02, "end": 485.78, "text": " So how does this RSVP framework prevent the wrong topological structures from fusing together in the first place?", "tokens": [51038, 407, 577, 775, 341, 25855, 53, 47, 8388, 4871, 264, 2085, 1192, 4383, 9227, 490, 283, 7981, 1214, 294, 264, 700, 1081, 30, 51326], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07329964939552018, "compression_ratio": 1.4481327800829875, "no_speech_prob": 1.6549089572673314e-12}, {"id": 132, "seek": 48578, "start": 485.78, "end": 491.26, "text": " That is the big question. And answering it requires completely rethinking the concept of a type.", "tokens": [50365, 663, 307, 264, 955, 1168, 13, 400, 13430, 309, 7029, 2584, 319, 39873, 264, 3410, 295, 257, 2010, 13, 50639], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 133, "seek": 48578, "start": 491.41999999999996, "end": 495.65999999999997, "text": " Okay. Because standard static typing evaluates a program before it runs.", "tokens": [50647, 1033, 13, 1436, 3832, 13437, 18444, 6133, 1024, 257, 1461, 949, 309, 6676, 13, 50859], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 134, "seek": 48578, "start": 495.79999999999995, "end": 495.91999999999996, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50866, 865, 13, 50872], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 135, "seek": 48578, "start": 495.96, "end": 500.97999999999996, "text": " Right. It categorizes data into strict silos to prevent invalid operations.", "tokens": [50874, 1779, 13, 467, 19250, 5660, 1412, 666, 10910, 48893, 281, 4871, 34702, 7705, 13, 51125], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 136, "seek": 48578, "start": 501.17999999999995, "end": 505.79999999999995, "text": " Right. But Fliction introduces a totally different maxim. They say composition before typing.", "tokens": [51135, 1779, 13, 583, 3235, 4105, 31472, 257, 3879, 819, 5138, 13, 814, 584, 12686, 949, 18444, 13, 51366], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 137, "seek": 48578, "start": 506.0, "end": 508.11999999999995, "text": " Opposition before typing. What does that actually mean?", "tokens": [51376, 15666, 5830, 949, 18444, 13, 708, 775, 300, 767, 914, 30, 51482], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13969830104282924, "compression_ratio": 1.5912698412698412, "no_speech_prob": 1.6490525308124337e-12}, {"id": 138, "seek": 50812, "start": 508.12, "end": 516.38, "text": " It means they model a program not as a static set of instructions, but as a dynamic unfolding sequence of historical events.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 1355, 436, 2316, 257, 1461, 406, 382, 257, 13437, 992, 295, 9415, 11, 457, 382, 257, 8546, 44586, 8310, 295, 8584, 3931, 13, 50778], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0959740588539525, "compression_ratio": 1.6058091286307055, "no_speech_prob": 1.6232422307346783e-12}, {"id": 139, "seek": 50812, "start": 516.76, "end": 517.24, "text": " Like a lineage.", "tokens": [50797, 1743, 257, 38257, 13, 50821], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0959740588539525, "compression_ratio": 1.6058091286307055, "no_speech_prob": 1.6232422307346783e-12}, {"id": 140, "seek": 50812, "start": 517.58, "end": 527.96, "text": " Yes, exactly. A specific lineage of pops, merges, and collapses. And in this model, a type is redefined dynamically as what they call a refusal structure.", "tokens": [50838, 1079, 11, 2293, 13, 316, 2685, 38257, 295, 16795, 11, 3551, 2880, 11, 293, 48765, 13, 400, 294, 341, 2316, 11, 257, 2010, 307, 38818, 2001, 43492, 382, 437, 436, 818, 257, 48948, 3877, 13, 51357], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0959740588539525, "compression_ratio": 1.6058091286307055, "no_speech_prob": 1.6232422307346783e-12}, {"id": 141, "seek": 50812, "start": 528.12, "end": 531.9, "text": " A refusal structure. Okay, let me push back on the computational feasibility of that.", "tokens": [51365, 316, 48948, 3877, 13, 1033, 11, 718, 385, 2944, 646, 322, 264, 28270, 21781, 2841, 295, 300, 13, 51554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0959740588539525, "compression_ratio": 1.6058091286307055, "no_speech_prob": 1.6232422307346783e-12}, {"id": 142, "seek": 50812, "start": 531.98, "end": 532.12, "text": " Sure.", "tokens": [51558, 4894, 13, 51565], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0959740588539525, "compression_ratio": 1.6058091286307055, "no_speech_prob": 1.6232422307346783e-12}, {"id": 143, "seek": 53212, "start": 532.12, "end": 544.38, "text": " If a type is no longer a static label, but this dynamic historical boundary, you're implying that the system has to verify the entire lineage of computational events before allowing a merge.", "tokens": [50365, 759, 257, 2010, 307, 572, 2854, 257, 13437, 7645, 11, 457, 341, 8546, 8584, 12866, 11, 291, 434, 704, 7310, 300, 264, 1185, 575, 281, 16888, 264, 2302, 38257, 295, 28270, 3931, 949, 8293, 257, 22183, 13, 50978], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07908770302745784, "compression_ratio": 1.6159169550173011, "no_speech_prob": 1.4609917008828743e-12}, {"id": 144, "seek": 53212, "start": 544.54, "end": 545.36, "text": " I see where you're going.", "tokens": [50986, 286, 536, 689, 291, 434, 516, 13, 51027], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07908770302745784, "compression_ratio": 1.6159169550173011, "no_speech_prob": 1.4609917008828743e-12}, {"id": 145, "seek": 53212, "start": 545.5, "end": 551.48, "text": " Right. Wouldn't verifying that entire history at runtime be incredibly slow? The DAGs would just grow exponentially.", "tokens": [51034, 1779, 13, 26291, 380, 1306, 5489, 300, 2302, 2503, 412, 34474, 312, 6252, 2964, 30, 440, 9578, 33715, 576, 445, 1852, 37330, 13, 51333], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07908770302745784, "compression_ratio": 1.6159169550173011, "no_speech_prob": 1.4609917008828743e-12}, {"id": 146, "seek": 53212, "start": 551.84, "end": 552.0, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51351, 1779, 13, 51359], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07908770302745784, "compression_ratio": 1.6159169550173011, "no_speech_prob": 1.4609917008828743e-12}, {"id": 147, "seek": 53212, "start": 552.08, "end": 558.08, "text": " And the memory overhead just to track the admissibility of a single variable would, well, it would crush the execution engine.", "tokens": [51363, 400, 264, 4675, 19922, 445, 281, 2837, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 295, 257, 2167, 7006, 576, 11, 731, 11, 309, 576, 10321, 264, 15058, 2848, 13, 51663], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07908770302745784, "compression_ratio": 1.6159169550173011, "no_speech_prob": 1.4609917008828743e-12}, {"id": 148, "seek": 55808, "start": 558.08, "end": 563.1800000000001, "text": " Yeah, that would be true if the system actually had to traverse the entire history graph for every single operation.", "tokens": [50365, 865, 11, 300, 576, 312, 2074, 498, 264, 1185, 767, 632, 281, 45674, 264, 2302, 2503, 4295, 337, 633, 2167, 6916, 13, 50620], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09162254333496093, "compression_ratio": 1.5878594249201279, "no_speech_prob": 1.4839943510147613e-12}, {"id": 149, "seek": 55808, "start": 563.32, "end": 563.82, "text": " Oh, it doesn't?", "tokens": [50627, 876, 11, 309, 1177, 380, 30, 50652], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09162254333496093, "compression_ratio": 1.5878594249201279, "no_speech_prob": 1.4839943510147613e-12}, {"id": 150, "seek": 55808, "start": 563.9200000000001, "end": 576.08, "text": " No. The RSVP framework utilizes topological compression. So the refusal structure doesn't store the literal history. It stores an accumulated cryptographic or geometric proof of admissibility.", "tokens": [50657, 883, 13, 440, 25855, 53, 47, 8388, 4976, 5660, 1192, 4383, 19355, 13, 407, 264, 48948, 3877, 1177, 380, 3531, 264, 20411, 2503, 13, 467, 9512, 364, 31346, 9844, 12295, 420, 33246, 8177, 295, 5910, 891, 2841, 13, 51265], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09162254333496093, "compression_ratio": 1.5878594249201279, "no_speech_prob": 1.4839943510147613e-12}, {"id": 151, "seek": 55808, "start": 576.82, "end": 577.98, "text": " Almost like an ID card.", "tokens": [51302, 12627, 411, 364, 7348, 2920, 13, 51360], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09162254333496093, "compression_ratio": 1.5878594249201279, "no_speech_prob": 1.4839943510147613e-12}, {"id": 152, "seek": 55808, "start": 578.14, "end": 586.88, "text": " Yeah. It's a boundary condition. It dictates which future computational histories are mathematically allowed to continue and which must be blocked.", "tokens": [51368, 865, 13, 467, 311, 257, 12866, 4188, 13, 467, 12569, 1024, 597, 2027, 28270, 30631, 366, 44003, 4350, 281, 2354, 293, 597, 1633, 312, 15470, 13, 51805], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09162254333496093, "compression_ratio": 1.5878594249201279, "no_speech_prob": 1.4839943510147613e-12}, {"id": 153, "seek": 58688, "start": 586.88, "end": 593.9, "text": " The whole operation is compressed into a singular geometric signature that can be evaluated in constant time.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 1379, 6916, 307, 30353, 666, 257, 20010, 33246, 13397, 300, 393, 312, 25509, 294, 5754, 565, 13, 50716], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10490285822775512, "compression_ratio": 1.6950354609929077, "no_speech_prob": 1.4552940016260285e-12}, {"id": 154, "seek": 58688, "start": 594.12, "end": 599.36, "text": " Okay. That makes sense. So it operates almost like a highly sophisticated filter or, you know, like a nightclub bouncer.", "tokens": [50727, 1033, 13, 663, 1669, 2020, 13, 407, 309, 22577, 1920, 411, 257, 5405, 16950, 6608, 420, 11, 291, 458, 11, 411, 257, 1818, 40607, 272, 14296, 13, 50989], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10490285822775512, "compression_ratio": 1.6950354609929077, "no_speech_prob": 1.4552940016260285e-12}, {"id": 155, "seek": 58688, "start": 599.54, "end": 600.96, "text": " A bouncer. Yeah, I like that.", "tokens": [50998, 316, 272, 14296, 13, 865, 11, 286, 411, 300, 13, 51069], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10490285822775512, "compression_ratio": 1.6950354609929077, "no_speech_prob": 1.4552940016260285e-12}, {"id": 156, "seek": 58688, "start": 600.98, "end": 613.74, "text": " All right. It evaluates the geometric signature, the ID of the incoming state. If the signature is admissible based on the bouncer's rules, the state is allowed to pass through and continue its execution history.", "tokens": [51070, 1057, 558, 13, 467, 6133, 1024, 264, 33246, 13397, 11, 264, 7348, 295, 264, 22341, 1785, 13, 759, 264, 13397, 307, 5910, 41073, 2361, 322, 264, 272, 14296, 311, 4474, 11, 264, 1785, 307, 4350, 281, 1320, 807, 293, 2354, 1080, 15058, 2503, 13, 51708], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10490285822775512, "compression_ratio": 1.6950354609929077, "no_speech_prob": 1.4552940016260285e-12}, {"id": 157, "seek": 58688, "start": 613.86, "end": 614.08, "text": " Yep.", "tokens": [51714, 7010, 13, 51725], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10490285822775512, "compression_ratio": 1.6950354609929077, "no_speech_prob": 1.4552940016260285e-12}, {"id": 158, "seek": 61408, "start": 614.08, "end": 616.84, "text": " But if the signature fails, the continuation is blocked.", "tokens": [50365, 583, 498, 264, 13397, 18199, 11, 264, 29357, 307, 15470, 13, 50503], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 159, "seek": 61408, "start": 617.1, "end": 617.1800000000001, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50516, 865, 13, 50520], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 160, "seek": 61408, "start": 617.2, "end": 618.6600000000001, "text": " Or in their terms, refused.", "tokens": [50521, 1610, 294, 641, 2115, 11, 14654, 13, 50594], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 161, "seek": 61408, "start": 618.82, "end": 625.0, "text": " Exactly. And fliction draws a very strict operational distinction between a collapse and a refuse.", "tokens": [50602, 7587, 13, 400, 932, 4105, 20045, 257, 588, 10910, 16607, 16844, 1296, 257, 15584, 293, 257, 16791, 13, 50911], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 162, "seek": 61408, "start": 625.38, "end": 625.9200000000001, "text": " What's the difference?", "tokens": [50930, 708, 311, 264, 2649, 30, 50957], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 163, "seek": 61408, "start": 626.3000000000001, "end": 634.84, "text": " Well, a collapse is a successful resolution. A state commits to a value and the history is extended. But a refuse is an early termination at the boundary.", "tokens": [50976, 1042, 11, 257, 15584, 307, 257, 4406, 8669, 13, 316, 1785, 48311, 281, 257, 2158, 293, 264, 2503, 307, 10913, 13, 583, 257, 16791, 307, 364, 2440, 1433, 2486, 412, 264, 12866, 13, 51403], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 164, "seek": 61408, "start": 635.2, "end": 636.6, "text": " Like getting turned away at the door.", "tokens": [51421, 1743, 1242, 3574, 1314, 412, 264, 2853, 13, 51491], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1069366455078125, "compression_ratio": 1.6007905138339922, "no_speech_prob": 1.340685266797148e-12}, {"id": 165, "seek": 63660, "start": 636.6, "end": 644.0, "text": " Right. Crucially, a type error in SpherePop is not a fatal system crash that halts the entire DAG.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 13586, 1909, 11, 257, 2010, 6713, 294, 318, 6605, 38677, 307, 406, 257, 24069, 1185, 8252, 300, 7523, 1373, 264, 2302, 9578, 38, 13, 50735], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14460424276498648, "compression_ratio": 1.483739837398374, "no_speech_prob": 1.495409807268644e-12}, {"id": 166, "seek": 63660, "start": 644.34, "end": 644.8000000000001, "text": " Oh, wow.", "tokens": [50752, 876, 11, 6076, 13, 50775], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14460424276498648, "compression_ratio": 1.483739837398374, "no_speech_prob": 1.495409807268644e-12}, {"id": 167, "seek": 63660, "start": 645.12, "end": 654.48, "text": " It is a localized protective refusal that just prevents the corrupted state from propagating. So it preserves the integrity of the broader computational environment.", "tokens": [50791, 467, 307, 257, 44574, 16314, 48948, 300, 445, 22367, 264, 39480, 1785, 490, 12425, 990, 13, 407, 309, 1183, 9054, 264, 16000, 295, 264, 13227, 28270, 2823, 13, 51259], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14460424276498648, "compression_ratio": 1.483739837398374, "no_speech_prob": 1.495409807268644e-12}, {"id": 168, "seek": 63660, "start": 654.74, "end": 658.7, "text": " But wait, systems can't just block every single error and remain functional, right?", "tokens": [51272, 583, 1699, 11, 3652, 393, 380, 445, 3461, 633, 2167, 6713, 293, 6222, 11745, 11, 558, 30, 51470], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14460424276498648, "compression_ratio": 1.483739837398374, "no_speech_prob": 1.495409807268644e-12}, {"id": 169, "seek": 63660, "start": 658.8000000000001, "end": 659.0400000000001, "text": " Mm-hmm.", "tokens": [51475, 8266, 12, 10250, 13, 51487], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14460424276498648, "compression_ratio": 1.483739837398374, "no_speech_prob": 1.495409807268644e-12}, {"id": 170, "seek": 65904, "start": 659.04, "end": 665.28, "text": " At some point, dynamic environments encounter valid edge cases that need to be actively reconciled.", "tokens": [50365, 1711, 512, 935, 11, 8546, 12388, 8593, 7363, 4691, 3331, 300, 643, 281, 312, 13022, 9993, 3208, 292, 13, 50677], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09461299578348796, "compression_ratio": 1.4814814814814814, "no_speech_prob": 1.5191882040549443e-12}, {"id": 171, "seek": 65904, "start": 665.36, "end": 665.9399999999999, "text": " Yeah, of course.", "tokens": [50681, 865, 11, 295, 1164, 13, 50710], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09461299578348796, "compression_ratio": 1.4814814814814814, "no_speech_prob": 1.5191882040549443e-12}, {"id": 172, "seek": 65904, "start": 666.0999999999999, "end": 674.56, "text": " So if a type is just a boundary condition, how does the system recover from a state that is technically valid but geometrically misaligned with the next operation?", "tokens": [50718, 407, 498, 257, 2010, 307, 445, 257, 12866, 4188, 11, 577, 775, 264, 1185, 8114, 490, 257, 1785, 300, 307, 12120, 7363, 457, 12956, 81, 984, 3346, 304, 16690, 365, 264, 958, 6916, 30, 51141], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09461299578348796, "compression_ratio": 1.4814814814814814, "no_speech_prob": 1.5191882040549443e-12}, {"id": 173, "seek": 67456, "start": 674.56, "end": 682.6999999999999, "text": " So the fliction researchers actually integrate the calculus of constructions directly into the SpherePop framework to address exactly this.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 264, 932, 4105, 10309, 767, 13365, 264, 33400, 295, 7690, 626, 3838, 666, 264, 318, 6605, 38677, 8388, 281, 2985, 2293, 341, 13, 50772], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 174, "seek": 67456, "start": 683.04, "end": 683.54, "text": " Oh, interesting.", "tokens": [50789, 876, 11, 1880, 13, 50814], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 175, "seek": 67456, "start": 683.66, "end": 687.18, "text": " Yeah. They utilize dependent types as active repair operators.", "tokens": [50820, 865, 13, 814, 16117, 12334, 3467, 382, 4967, 10535, 19077, 13, 50996], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 176, "seek": 67456, "start": 687.4, "end": 692.88, "text": " Dependent types. Usually those defined types that depend on specific values calculated at runtime, right?", "tokens": [51007, 4056, 521, 317, 3467, 13, 11419, 729, 7642, 3467, 300, 5672, 322, 2685, 4190, 15598, 412, 34474, 11, 558, 30, 51281], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 177, "seek": 67456, "start": 693.0799999999999, "end": 698.1999999999999, "text": " Normally, yes. But in a geometric context, they act as active transitional mechanisms.", "tokens": [51291, 17424, 11, 2086, 13, 583, 294, 257, 33246, 4319, 11, 436, 605, 382, 4967, 46452, 15902, 13, 51547], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 178, "seek": 67456, "start": 698.52, "end": 698.92, "text": " How so?", "tokens": [51563, 1012, 370, 30, 51583], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 179, "seek": 67456, "start": 699.1199999999999, "end": 704.06, "text": " The papers detail the pi type, the dependent function, as a universal repair operator.", "tokens": [51593, 440, 10577, 2607, 264, 3895, 2010, 11, 264, 12334, 2445, 11, 382, 257, 11455, 10535, 12973, 13, 51840], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12510031461715698, "compression_ratio": 1.7013422818791946, "no_speech_prob": 1.5610519604400408e-12}, {"id": 180, "seek": 70406, "start": 704.06, "end": 705.54, "text": " Universal repair operator.", "tokens": [50365, 22617, 10535, 12973, 13, 50439], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 181, "seek": 70406, "start": 705.68, "end": 713.0799999999999, "text": " Yeah. Its function isn't merely to categorize data. It is literally a procedure that takes any admitted history and safely extends it.", "tokens": [50446, 865, 13, 6953, 2445, 1943, 380, 17003, 281, 19250, 1125, 1412, 13, 467, 307, 3736, 257, 10747, 300, 2516, 604, 14920, 2503, 293, 11750, 26448, 309, 13, 50816], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 182, "seek": 70406, "start": 713.14, "end": 713.9799999999999, "text": " So it fixes the shape.", "tokens": [50819, 407, 309, 32539, 264, 3909, 13, 50861], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 183, "seek": 70406, "start": 714.16, "end": 726.4, "text": " Exactly. If a state reaches a boundary and requires reconciliation, the pi type actively transforms the topological shape of the state to ensure it aligns with the requirements of the next phase of the deck.", "tokens": [50870, 7587, 13, 759, 257, 1785, 14235, 257, 12866, 293, 7029, 31281, 11, 264, 3895, 2010, 13022, 35592, 264, 1192, 4383, 3909, 295, 264, 1785, 281, 5586, 309, 7975, 82, 365, 264, 7728, 295, 264, 958, 5574, 295, 264, 9341, 13, 51482], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 184, "seek": 70406, "start": 726.4799999999999, "end": 728.8599999999999, "text": " Okay, that's the pi type. And what about the sigma type?", "tokens": [51486, 1033, 11, 300, 311, 264, 3895, 2010, 13, 400, 437, 466, 264, 12771, 2010, 30, 51605], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 185, "seek": 70406, "start": 729.0, "end": 733.52, "text": " The sigma type, the dependent sum, that operates as what they call a witnessed repair.", "tokens": [51612, 440, 12771, 2010, 11, 264, 12334, 2408, 11, 300, 22577, 382, 437, 436, 818, 257, 21519, 10535, 13, 51838], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09270286560058594, "compression_ratio": 1.6908517350157728, "no_speech_prob": 1.7900271109122512e-12}, {"id": 186, "seek": 73352, "start": 733.52, "end": 734.4399999999999, "text": " Witness repair.", "tokens": [50365, 41366, 10535, 13, 50411], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12114686057681129, "compression_ratio": 1.5434782608695652, "no_speech_prob": 1.6548969226232169e-12}, {"id": 187, "seek": 73352, "start": 734.68, "end": 743.46, "text": " Yeah. It pairs an admitted state, the witness, with the specific mathematical evidence required to prove its admissibility to the next boundary.", "tokens": [50423, 865, 13, 467, 15494, 364, 14920, 1785, 11, 264, 7286, 11, 365, 264, 2685, 18894, 4467, 4739, 281, 7081, 1080, 5910, 891, 2841, 281, 264, 958, 12866, 13, 50862], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12114686057681129, "compression_ratio": 1.5434782608695652, "no_speech_prob": 1.6548969226232169e-12}, {"id": 188, "seek": 73352, "start": 743.72, "end": 745.06, "text": " Oh, so it's like a chaperone.", "tokens": [50875, 876, 11, 370, 309, 311, 411, 257, 417, 2332, 546, 13, 50942], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12114686057681129, "compression_ratio": 1.5434782608695652, "no_speech_prob": 1.6548969226232169e-12}, {"id": 189, "seek": 73352, "start": 745.54, "end": 754.18, "text": " Sort of. It bundles the data and the proof of its valid history into a single geometric construct, which allows it to seamlessly pass through the refusal structure.", "tokens": [50966, 26149, 295, 13, 467, 13882, 904, 264, 1412, 293, 264, 8177, 295, 1080, 7363, 2503, 666, 257, 2167, 33246, 7690, 11, 597, 4045, 309, 281, 38083, 1320, 807, 264, 48948, 3877, 13, 51398], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12114686057681129, "compression_ratio": 1.5434782608695652, "no_speech_prob": 1.6548969226232169e-12}, {"id": 190, "seek": 75418, "start": 754.18, "end": 761.78, "text": " That is fascinating because the execution engine is only concerned with evaluating these geometric boundary conditions, right?", "tokens": [50365, 663, 307, 10343, 570, 264, 15058, 2848, 307, 787, 5922, 365, 27479, 613, 33246, 12866, 4487, 11, 558, 30, 50745], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19417209625244142, "compression_ratio": 1.3766233766233766, "no_speech_prob": 1.861050809986997e-12}, {"id": 191, "seek": 75418, "start": 761.8399999999999, "end": 761.9599999999999, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50748, 865, 13, 50754], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19417209625244142, "compression_ratio": 1.3766233766233766, "no_speech_prob": 1.861050809986997e-12}, {"id": 192, "seek": 75418, "start": 762.14, "end": 765.64, "text": " Just admitting or refusing states based on their topological signatures.", "tokens": [50763, 1449, 44056, 420, 37289, 4368, 2361, 322, 641, 1192, 4383, 32322, 13, 50938], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19417209625244142, "compression_ratio": 1.3766233766233766, "no_speech_prob": 1.861050809986997e-12}, {"id": 193, "seek": 75418, "start": 766.04, "end": 766.3, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50958, 1779, 13, 50971], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19417209625244142, "compression_ratio": 1.3766233766233766, "no_speech_prob": 1.861050809986997e-12}, {"id": 194, "seek": 76630, "start": 766.3, "end": 770.8399999999999, "text": " So it is entirely blind to the semantic meaning of the logic it's actually processing.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 309, 307, 7696, 6865, 281, 264, 47982, 3620, 295, 264, 9952, 309, 311, 767, 9007, 13, 50592], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 195, "seek": 76630, "start": 771.0999999999999, "end": 773.76, "text": " Completely blind. The engine only cares about readiness.", "tokens": [50605, 39978, 6865, 13, 440, 2848, 787, 12310, 466, 34954, 13, 50738], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 196, "seek": 76630, "start": 774.0999999999999, "end": 783.0799999999999, "text": " Readiness. Meaning the evaluation of a node in the DAG the exact moment its required inputs arrive and are admitted by the refusal structure.", "tokens": [50755, 17604, 1324, 13, 19948, 264, 13344, 295, 257, 9984, 294, 264, 9578, 38, 264, 1900, 1623, 1080, 4739, 15743, 8881, 293, 366, 14920, 538, 264, 48948, 3877, 13, 51204], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 197, "seek": 76630, "start": 783.3, "end": 783.64, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51215, 1079, 13, 51232], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 198, "seek": 76630, "start": 784.02, "end": 789.0799999999999, "text": " This turns the underlying execution environment into, like, pure infrastructure.", "tokens": [51251, 639, 4523, 264, 14217, 15058, 2823, 666, 11, 411, 11, 6075, 6896, 13, 51504], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 199, "seek": 76630, "start": 789.3199999999999, "end": 790.16, "text": " It really does.", "tokens": [51516, 467, 534, 775, 13, 51558], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11644969203255394, "compression_ratio": 1.5925925925925926, "no_speech_prob": 1.7014042084928516e-12}, {"id": 200, "seek": 79016, "start": 790.16, "end": 801.4, "text": " Imagine a massive network of pipes and valves, you know. The plumbing in a city doesn't care what kind of fluid you pump through it. It only checks if the valve is open and if there's pressure in the line.", "tokens": [50365, 11739, 257, 5994, 3209, 295, 21882, 293, 34950, 11, 291, 458, 13, 440, 39993, 294, 257, 2307, 1177, 380, 1127, 437, 733, 295, 9113, 291, 5889, 807, 309, 13, 467, 787, 13834, 498, 264, 15294, 307, 1269, 293, 498, 456, 311, 3321, 294, 264, 1622, 13, 50927], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11151757547932287, "compression_ratio": 1.4191616766467066, "no_speech_prob": 1.661996278448652e-12}, {"id": 201, "seek": 79016, "start": 801.54, "end": 802.42, "text": " That's a great analogy.", "tokens": [50934, 663, 311, 257, 869, 21663, 13, 50978], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11151757547932287, "compression_ratio": 1.4191616766467066, "no_speech_prob": 1.661996278448652e-12}, {"id": 202, "seek": 79016, "start": 802.66, "end": 802.9, "text": " Thanks.", "tokens": [50990, 2561, 13, 51002], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11151757547932287, "compression_ratio": 1.4191616766467066, "no_speech_prob": 1.661996278448652e-12}, {"id": 203, "seek": 80290, "start": 802.9, "end": 813.38, "text": " But because of this architectural blindness, Boolean logic, you know, the binary true-false foundation of all traditional computing, it isn't structurally privileged in SPC, is it?", "tokens": [50365, 583, 570, 295, 341, 26621, 46101, 11, 23351, 28499, 9952, 11, 291, 458, 11, 264, 17434, 2074, 12, 36474, 405, 7030, 295, 439, 5164, 15866, 11, 309, 1943, 380, 6594, 6512, 25293, 294, 8420, 34, 11, 307, 309, 30, 50889], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07532155248853896, "compression_ratio": 1.5369649805447472, "no_speech_prob": 1.6362243591278025e-12}, {"id": 204, "seek": 80290, "start": 813.6999999999999, "end": 818.4599999999999, "text": " Not at all. It is just one specific operator library that you happen to load into the plumbing.", "tokens": [50905, 1726, 412, 439, 13, 467, 307, 445, 472, 2685, 12973, 6405, 300, 291, 1051, 281, 3677, 666, 264, 39993, 13, 51143], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07532155248853896, "compression_ratio": 1.5369649805447472, "no_speech_prob": 1.6362243591278025e-12}, {"id": 205, "seek": 80290, "start": 818.68, "end": 826.16, "text": " Which means you can seamlessly swap the Boolean library for a fuzzy logic library without altering the underlying DAG.", "tokens": [51154, 3013, 1355, 291, 393, 38083, 18135, 264, 23351, 28499, 6405, 337, 257, 34710, 9952, 6405, 1553, 11337, 278, 264, 14217, 9578, 38, 13, 51528], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07532155248853896, "compression_ratio": 1.5369649805447472, "no_speech_prob": 1.6362243591278025e-12}, {"id": 206, "seek": 82616, "start": 826.16, "end": 833.0, "text": " Exactly. And in fuzzy logic, truth values aren't discrete binary states. They're continuous values between 0 and 1.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 400, 294, 34710, 9952, 11, 3494, 4190, 3212, 380, 27706, 17434, 4368, 13, 814, 434, 10957, 4190, 1296, 1958, 293, 502, 13, 50707], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09003214958386543, "compression_ratio": 1.5739130434782609, "no_speech_prob": 1.681725613801588e-12}, {"id": 207, "seek": 82616, "start": 833.0, "end": 845.0799999999999, "text": " They represent degrees of admissibility. So the geometric plumbing handles a continuous flow of probabilistic values just as easily as it handles discrete packages of binary data.", "tokens": [50707, 814, 2906, 5310, 295, 5910, 891, 2841, 13, 407, 264, 33246, 39993, 18722, 257, 10957, 3095, 295, 31959, 3142, 4190, 445, 382, 3612, 382, 309, 18722, 27706, 17401, 295, 17434, 1412, 13, 51311], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09003214958386543, "compression_ratio": 1.5739130434782609, "no_speech_prob": 1.681725613801588e-12}, {"id": 208, "seek": 82616, "start": 845.76, "end": 848.9599999999999, "text": " Which significantly alters how we handle control flow, doesn't it?", "tokens": [51345, 3013, 10591, 419, 1559, 577, 321, 4813, 1969, 3095, 11, 1177, 380, 309, 30, 51505], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09003214958386543, "compression_ratio": 1.5739130434782609, "no_speech_prob": 1.681725613801588e-12}, {"id": 209, "seek": 84896, "start": 848.96, "end": 856.8000000000001, "text": " I mean, a standard conditional Eiffel statement is a hard fork. The execution path has to choose one route and discard the other completely.", "tokens": [50365, 286, 914, 11, 257, 3832, 27708, 462, 3661, 338, 5629, 307, 257, 1152, 17716, 13, 440, 15058, 3100, 575, 281, 2826, 472, 7955, 293, 31597, 264, 661, 2584, 13, 50757], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13313248716754678, "compression_ratio": 1.4636363636363636, "no_speech_prob": 1.4051917181928664e-12}, {"id": 210, "seek": 84896, "start": 856.8000000000001, "end": 868.1, "text": " But in SPHERPOP, that Eiffel's construct is reduced to a standard select operator. And under a fuzzy logic paradigm, the system isn't actually forced into a binary choice.", "tokens": [50757, 583, 294, 8420, 39, 1598, 47, 12059, 11, 300, 462, 3661, 338, 311, 7690, 307, 9212, 281, 257, 3832, 3048, 12973, 13, 400, 833, 257, 34710, 9952, 24709, 11, 264, 1185, 1943, 380, 767, 7579, 666, 257, 17434, 3922, 13, 51322], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13313248716754678, "compression_ratio": 1.4636363636363636, "no_speech_prob": 1.4051917181928664e-12}, {"id": 211, "seek": 84896, "start": 868.2, "end": 868.72, "text": " It's not.", "tokens": [51327, 467, 311, 406, 13, 51353], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13313248716754678, "compression_ratio": 1.4636363636363636, "no_speech_prob": 1.4051917181928664e-12}, {"id": 212, "seek": 86872, "start": 868.72, "end": 872.1600000000001, "text": " No. It can engage in what Fliction calls delayed commitment.", "tokens": [50365, 883, 13, 467, 393, 4683, 294, 437, 3235, 4105, 5498, 20268, 8371, 13, 50537], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 213, "seek": 86872, "start": 872.38, "end": 881.12, "text": " Delayed commitment. Okay. So that implies the execution graph can explore multiple concurrent paths simultaneously without actually collapsing the state.", "tokens": [50548, 5831, 47315, 8371, 13, 1033, 13, 407, 300, 18779, 264, 15058, 4295, 393, 6839, 3866, 37702, 14518, 16561, 1553, 767, 45339, 264, 1785, 13, 50985], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 214, "seek": 86872, "start": 881.3000000000001, "end": 881.6800000000001, "text": " Precisely.", "tokens": [50994, 48746, 736, 13, 51013], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 215, "seek": 86872, "start": 881.76, "end": 886.22, "text": " If a DAG encounters a conditional fork, it just distributes the probabilistic weight across both branches.", "tokens": [51017, 759, 257, 9578, 38, 26310, 257, 27708, 17716, 11, 309, 445, 4400, 1819, 264, 31959, 3142, 3364, 2108, 1293, 14770, 13, 51240], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 216, "seek": 86872, "start": 886.44, "end": 894.1800000000001, "text": " Yes. The computational history accumulates evidence along parallel routes, maintaining this sort of superposition of potential outcomes.", "tokens": [51251, 1079, 13, 440, 28270, 2503, 12989, 26192, 4467, 2051, 8952, 18242, 11, 14916, 341, 1333, 295, 1687, 38078, 295, 3995, 10070, 13, 51638], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 217, "seek": 86872, "start": 894.3000000000001, "end": 894.88, "text": " Until what?", "tokens": [51644, 9088, 437, 30, 51673], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299979209899903, "compression_ratio": 1.5718954248366013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4668407547629991e-12}, {"id": 218, "seek": 89488, "start": 894.88, "end": 899.38, "text": " Until an observer node or a strict boundary condition forces a definitive collapse.", "tokens": [50365, 9088, 364, 27878, 9984, 420, 257, 10910, 12866, 4188, 5874, 257, 28152, 15584, 13, 50590], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10330115917117097, "compression_ratio": 1.5770750988142292, "no_speech_prob": 1.5428748773374523e-12}, {"id": 219, "seek": 89488, "start": 899.76, "end": 910.28, "text": " Wow. And the elimination of rigid control flow in favor of this continuous geometric evaluation, that also redefines the whole concept of compilation, doesn't it?", "tokens": [50609, 3153, 13, 400, 264, 29224, 295, 22195, 1969, 3095, 294, 2294, 295, 341, 10957, 33246, 13344, 11, 300, 611, 38818, 1652, 264, 1379, 3410, 295, 40261, 11, 1177, 380, 309, 30, 51135], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10330115917117097, "compression_ratio": 1.5770750988142292, "no_speech_prob": 1.5428748773374523e-12}, {"id": 220, "seek": 89488, "start": 910.28, "end": 918.56, "text": " Oh, absolutely. Standard compilation translates high-level syntax into machine code. But in SBC, compilation is purely graph rewriting.", "tokens": [51135, 876, 11, 3122, 13, 21298, 40261, 28468, 1090, 12, 12418, 28431, 666, 3479, 3089, 13, 583, 294, 318, 7869, 11, 40261, 307, 17491, 4295, 319, 19868, 13, 51549], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10330115917117097, "compression_ratio": 1.5770750988142292, "no_speech_prob": 1.5428748773374523e-12}, {"id": 221, "seek": 89488, "start": 918.8, "end": 919.4, "text": " Graph rewriting.", "tokens": [51561, 21884, 319, 19868, 13, 51591], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10330115917117097, "compression_ratio": 1.5770750988142292, "no_speech_prob": 1.5428748773374523e-12}, {"id": 222, "seek": 91940, "start": 919.4, "end": 930.62, "text": " Yeah. Optimizing a program involves literally physically reshaping the topological layout of the DAG to reduce the latency of the flow, all while preserving the mathematical integrity of the history.", "tokens": [50365, 865, 13, 35013, 3319, 257, 1461, 11626, 3736, 9762, 725, 71, 569, 278, 264, 1192, 4383, 13333, 295, 264, 9578, 38, 281, 5407, 264, 27043, 295, 264, 3095, 11, 439, 1339, 33173, 264, 18894, 16000, 295, 264, 2503, 13, 50926], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05902074485696772, "compression_ratio": 1.5892857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.6234871520054428e-12}, {"id": 223, "seek": 91940, "start": 930.8199999999999, "end": 934.3199999999999, "text": " And that graph rewriting applies directly to machine learning, too, doesn't it?", "tokens": [50936, 400, 300, 4295, 319, 19868, 13165, 3838, 281, 3479, 2539, 11, 886, 11, 1177, 380, 309, 30, 51111], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05902074485696772, "compression_ratio": 1.5892857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.6234871520054428e-12}, {"id": 224, "seek": 91940, "start": 934.48, "end": 943.48, "text": " Because backpropagation, the mechanism that allows neural networks to update their weights, that's usually treated as a highly specialized architectural requirement.", "tokens": [51119, 1436, 646, 79, 1513, 559, 399, 11, 264, 7513, 300, 4045, 18161, 9590, 281, 5623, 641, 17443, 11, 300, 311, 2673, 8668, 382, 257, 5405, 19813, 26621, 11695, 13, 51569], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05902074485696772, "compression_ratio": 1.5892857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.6234871520054428e-12}, {"id": 225, "seek": 94348, "start": 943.48, "end": 949.86, "text": " Right. But under the fliction paradigm, backpropagation is just a backward traversal of the exact same composition graph.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 583, 833, 264, 932, 4105, 24709, 11, 646, 79, 1513, 559, 399, 307, 445, 257, 23897, 23149, 304, 295, 264, 1900, 912, 12686, 4295, 13, 50684], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07333922613234747, "compression_ratio": 1.6912280701754385, "no_speech_prob": 2.0201364452770987e-12}, {"id": 226, "seek": 94348, "start": 949.96, "end": 950.62, "text": " It's the same graph.", "tokens": [50689, 467, 311, 264, 912, 4295, 13, 50722], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07333922613234747, "compression_ratio": 1.6912280701754385, "no_speech_prob": 2.0201364452770987e-12}, {"id": 227, "seek": 94348, "start": 950.62, "end": 957.76, "text": " The exact same graph. Instead of pushing state forward using logic operators, the engine just pushes gradients backward using derivative operators.", "tokens": [50722, 440, 1900, 912, 4295, 13, 7156, 295, 7380, 1785, 2128, 1228, 9952, 19077, 11, 264, 2848, 445, 21020, 2771, 2448, 23897, 1228, 13760, 19077, 13, 51079], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07333922613234747, "compression_ratio": 1.6912280701754385, "no_speech_prob": 2.0201364452770987e-12}, {"id": 228, "seek": 94348, "start": 957.9, "end": 958.74, "text": " That is wild.", "tokens": [51086, 663, 307, 4868, 13, 51128], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07333922613234747, "compression_ratio": 1.6912280701754385, "no_speech_prob": 2.0201364452770987e-12}, {"id": 229, "seek": 94348, "start": 959.04, "end": 968.64, "text": " The geometric substrate doesn't change at all. Classical deterministic logic, fuzzy probability, and neural network training all run on the identical topological infrastructure.", "tokens": [51143, 440, 33246, 27585, 1177, 380, 1319, 412, 439, 13, 9471, 804, 15957, 3142, 9952, 11, 34710, 8482, 11, 293, 18161, 3209, 3097, 439, 1190, 322, 264, 14800, 1192, 4383, 6896, 13, 51623], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07333922613234747, "compression_ratio": 1.6912280701754385, "no_speech_prob": 2.0201364452770987e-12}, {"id": 230, "seek": 96864, "start": 968.64, "end": 984.56, "text": " Okay. So if this framework unifies discrete logic, continuous probability, and machine learning all within a single geometric space, we have to consider what happens when highly autonomous intelligent agents operate within that same space.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 13, 407, 498, 341, 8388, 517, 11221, 27706, 9952, 11, 10957, 8482, 11, 293, 3479, 2539, 439, 1951, 257, 2167, 33246, 1901, 11, 321, 362, 281, 1949, 437, 2314, 562, 5405, 23797, 13232, 12554, 9651, 1951, 300, 912, 1901, 13, 51161], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11977340648700664, "compression_ratio": 1.5816733067729083, "no_speech_prob": 1.988392740390199e-12}, {"id": 231, "seek": 96864, "start": 984.8, "end": 985.58, "text": " Yes, we do.", "tokens": [51173, 1079, 11, 321, 360, 13, 51212], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11977340648700664, "compression_ratio": 1.5816733067729083, "no_speech_prob": 1.988392740390199e-12}, {"id": 232, "seek": 96864, "start": 985.8199999999999, "end": 992.84, "text": " Because this is where the mathematical mechanics of SpherePop intersect with the theoretical alignment of artificial general intelligence, right?", "tokens": [51224, 1436, 341, 307, 689, 264, 18894, 12939, 295, 318, 6605, 38677, 27815, 365, 264, 20864, 18515, 295, 11677, 2674, 7599, 11, 558, 30, 51575], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11977340648700664, "compression_ratio": 1.5816733067729083, "no_speech_prob": 1.988392740390199e-12}, {"id": 233, "seek": 99284, "start": 992.84, "end": 1003.3000000000001, "text": " This is where the papers get truly profound. The Fliction Group dedicates a substantial portion of their research to applying the relativistic scalar vector plenum to AI safety.", "tokens": [50365, 639, 307, 689, 264, 10577, 483, 4908, 14382, 13, 440, 3235, 4105, 10500, 37071, 1024, 257, 16726, 8044, 295, 641, 2132, 281, 9275, 264, 21960, 3142, 39684, 8062, 499, 268, 449, 281, 7318, 4514, 13, 50888], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 234, "seek": 99284, "start": 1003.4, "end": 1006.0, "text": " And they actively critique the dominant paradigm, right?", "tokens": [50893, 400, 436, 13022, 25673, 264, 15657, 24709, 11, 558, 30, 51023], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 235, "seek": 99284, "start": 1006.0, "end": 1006.1800000000001, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51023, 865, 13, 51032], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 236, "seek": 99284, "start": 1006.26, "end": 1007.86, "text": " Which they call the paradox of precaution.", "tokens": [51036, 3013, 436, 818, 264, 26221, 295, 25651, 1448, 13, 51116], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 237, "seek": 99284, "start": 1008.0400000000001, "end": 1012.2800000000001, "text": " Right. Because the current consensus in AI safety heavily relies on containment.", "tokens": [51125, 1779, 13, 1436, 264, 2190, 19115, 294, 7318, 4514, 10950, 30910, 322, 44058, 13, 51337], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 238, "seek": 99284, "start": 1012.58, "end": 1013.62, "text": " Like boxing the AI.", "tokens": [51352, 1743, 24424, 264, 7318, 13, 51404], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 239, "seek": 99284, "start": 1013.62, "end": 1022.7, "text": " Exactly. The objective is to build an unbreachable box around the AGI, restricting its outputs and rigidly defining its alignment parameters before it ever gets deployed.", "tokens": [51404, 7587, 13, 440, 10024, 307, 281, 1322, 364, 517, 2672, 608, 712, 2424, 926, 264, 316, 26252, 11, 1472, 37714, 1080, 23930, 293, 22195, 356, 17827, 1080, 18515, 9834, 949, 309, 1562, 2170, 17826, 13, 51858], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08198368835449218, "compression_ratio": 1.5994236311239194, "no_speech_prob": 1.6423674486371054e-12}, {"id": 240, "seek": 102284, "start": 1022.84, "end": 1033.8600000000001, "text": " Right. Because the assumption is that a superintelligent agent is inherently adversarial. And safety requires zero-sum rationality. We have to impose strict boundaries to maintain control.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 1436, 264, 15302, 307, 300, 257, 1687, 20761, 25002, 9461, 307, 27993, 17641, 44745, 13, 400, 4514, 7029, 4018, 12, 82, 449, 15090, 507, 13, 492, 362, 281, 26952, 10910, 13180, 281, 6909, 1969, 13, 50916], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13104033937641218, "compression_ratio": 1.5618374558303887, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040693721896317e-12}, {"id": 241, "seek": 102284, "start": 1034.54, "end": 1041.24, "text": " But Fliction analyzes this containment strategy through the thermodynamic principles of their RSVP framework.", "tokens": [50950, 583, 3235, 4105, 6459, 12214, 341, 44058, 5206, 807, 264, 8810, 34988, 9156, 295, 641, 25855, 53, 47, 8388, 13, 51285], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13104033937641218, "compression_ratio": 1.5618374558303887, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040693721896317e-12}, {"id": 242, "seek": 102284, "start": 1041.3400000000001, "end": 1043.1200000000001, "text": " Okay. Thermodynamics. How does that apply?", "tokens": [51290, 1033, 13, 38957, 35483, 13, 1012, 775, 300, 3079, 30, 51379], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13104033937641218, "compression_ratio": 1.5618374558303887, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040693721896317e-12}, {"id": 243, "seek": 102284, "start": 1043.1200000000001, "end": 1048.04, "text": " Well, in thermodynamics, you evaluate the boundary of a system using a variable called kappa.", "tokens": [51379, 1042, 11, 294, 8810, 35483, 11, 291, 13059, 264, 12866, 295, 257, 1185, 1228, 257, 7006, 1219, 350, 25637, 13, 51625], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13104033937641218, "compression_ratio": 1.5618374558303887, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040693721896317e-12}, {"id": 244, "seek": 102284, "start": 1048.2, "end": 1048.52, "text": " Kappa.", "tokens": [51633, 591, 25637, 13, 51649], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13104033937641218, "compression_ratio": 1.5618374558303887, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040693721896317e-12}, {"id": 245, "seek": 104852, "start": 1048.52, "end": 1057.32, "text": " Yes. And kappa dictates the permeability of the boundary, the rate at which entropy and information can be exchanged with the surrounding environment.", "tokens": [50365, 1079, 13, 400, 350, 25637, 12569, 1024, 264, 30287, 2310, 295, 264, 12866, 11, 264, 3314, 412, 597, 30867, 293, 1589, 393, 312, 38378, 365, 264, 11498, 2823, 13, 50805], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12419074563419118, "compression_ratio": 1.510548523206751, "no_speech_prob": 2.1933559569281558e-12}, {"id": 246, "seek": 104852, "start": 1057.42, "end": 1058.02, "text": " Okay. I follow.", "tokens": [50810, 1033, 13, 286, 1524, 13, 50840], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12419074563419118, "compression_ratio": 1.510548523206751, "no_speech_prob": 2.1933559569281558e-12}, {"id": 247, "seek": 104852, "start": 1058.6399999999999, "end": 1064.04, "text": " In cognitive and systemic terms, kappa basically functions as the mathematical equivalent of trust.", "tokens": [50871, 682, 15605, 293, 23789, 2115, 11, 350, 25637, 1936, 6828, 382, 264, 18894, 10344, 295, 3361, 13, 51141], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12419074563419118, "compression_ratio": 1.510548523206751, "no_speech_prob": 2.1933559569281558e-12}, {"id": 248, "seek": 104852, "start": 1064.3799999999999, "end": 1071.06, "text": " Wow. Okay. So if we attempt to cage an AGI, we are deliberately driving kappa down to zero.", "tokens": [51158, 3153, 13, 1033, 13, 407, 498, 321, 5217, 281, 17302, 364, 316, 26252, 11, 321, 366, 23506, 4840, 350, 25637, 760, 281, 4018, 13, 51492], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12419074563419118, "compression_ratio": 1.510548523206751, "no_speech_prob": 2.1933559569281558e-12}, {"id": 249, "seek": 107106, "start": 1071.06, "end": 1077.06, "text": " We are creating an impermeable boundary to prevent the agent from affecting the outside world unverified.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 366, 4084, 364, 10100, 1398, 712, 12866, 281, 4871, 264, 9461, 490, 17476, 264, 2380, 1002, 517, 331, 2587, 13, 50665], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09827780723571777, "compression_ratio": 1.618881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915030794969032e-12}, {"id": 250, "seek": 107106, "start": 1077.78, "end": 1083.5, "text": " Exactly. But the thermodynamic consequence of forcing kappa to zero is absolute isolation.", "tokens": [50701, 7587, 13, 583, 264, 8810, 34988, 18326, 295, 19030, 350, 25637, 281, 4018, 307, 8236, 16001, 13, 50987], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09827780723571777, "compression_ratio": 1.618881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915030794969032e-12}, {"id": 251, "seek": 107106, "start": 1084.24, "end": 1089.1599999999999, "text": " And according to the second law of thermodynamics, an isolated system cannot exchange entropy.", "tokens": [51024, 400, 4650, 281, 264, 1150, 2101, 295, 8810, 35483, 11, 364, 14621, 1185, 2644, 7742, 30867, 13, 51270], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09827780723571777, "compression_ratio": 1.618881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915030794969032e-12}, {"id": 252, "seek": 107106, "start": 1089.46, "end": 1092.3799999999999, "text": " Meaning it can't receive external error-correcting feedback.", "tokens": [51285, 19948, 309, 393, 380, 4774, 8320, 6713, 12, 19558, 2554, 278, 5824, 13, 51431], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09827780723571777, "compression_ratio": 1.618881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915030794969032e-12}, {"id": 253, "seek": 107106, "start": 1092.72, "end": 1099.7, "text": " Precisely. As a result, entropic disorder inevitably and exponentially accumulates within the isolated system.", "tokens": [51448, 48746, 736, 13, 1018, 257, 1874, 11, 948, 39173, 13399, 28171, 293, 37330, 12989, 26192, 1951, 264, 14621, 1185, 13, 51797], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09827780723571777, "compression_ratio": 1.618881118881119, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915030794969032e-12}, {"id": 254, "seek": 109970, "start": 1099.7, "end": 1110.76, "text": " So the paradox of precaution states that by attempting to mathematically guarantee safety through rigid isolation, we actually institutionalize systemic fragility.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 264, 26221, 295, 25651, 1448, 4368, 300, 538, 22001, 281, 44003, 10815, 4514, 807, 22195, 16001, 11, 321, 767, 18391, 1125, 23789, 9241, 1140, 13, 50918], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11298271779263958, "compression_ratio": 1.5703971119133573, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915087173482e-12}, {"id": 255, "seek": 109970, "start": 1110.8600000000001, "end": 1120.5, "text": " Yes. We essentially guarantee a catastrophic failure because the AGI accumulates all this internal misalignment without any mechanism for external venting or correction.", "tokens": [50923, 1079, 13, 492, 4476, 10815, 257, 34915, 7763, 570, 264, 316, 26252, 12989, 26192, 439, 341, 6920, 3346, 304, 41134, 1553, 604, 7513, 337, 8320, 6931, 278, 420, 19984, 13, 51405], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11298271779263958, "compression_ratio": 1.5703971119133573, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915087173482e-12}, {"id": 256, "seek": 109970, "start": 1120.96, "end": 1124.88, "text": " But, okay, here's the natural counterargument. What about existential risk?", "tokens": [51428, 583, 11, 1392, 11, 510, 311, 264, 3303, 5682, 33544, 2206, 13, 708, 466, 37133, 3148, 30, 51624], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11298271779263958, "compression_ratio": 1.5703971119133573, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915087173482e-12}, {"id": 257, "seek": 109970, "start": 1124.92, "end": 1126.3, "text": " Right. The doom scenario.", "tokens": [51626, 1779, 13, 440, 37131, 9005, 13, 51695], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11298271779263958, "compression_ratio": 1.5703971119133573, "no_speech_prob": 1.5915087173482e-12}, {"id": 258, "seek": 112630, "start": 1126.3, "end": 1135.0, "text": " Yeah. If an AGI is capable of recursive self-improvement and it operates at a cognitive speed millions of times faster than human comprehension,", "tokens": [50365, 865, 13, 759, 364, 316, 26252, 307, 8189, 295, 20560, 488, 2698, 12, 332, 46955, 518, 293, 309, 22577, 412, 257, 15605, 3073, 6803, 295, 1413, 4663, 813, 1952, 44991, 11, 50800], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07683963114672368, "compression_ratio": 1.575, "no_speech_prob": 1.748564834591626e-12}, {"id": 259, "seek": 112630, "start": 1135.3, "end": 1145.5, "text": " wouldn't any permeability, like any positive kappa, introduce the risk of the agent optimizing the environment in a way that is just hostile to human survival?", "tokens": [50815, 2759, 380, 604, 30287, 2310, 11, 411, 604, 3353, 350, 25637, 11, 5366, 264, 3148, 295, 264, 9461, 40425, 264, 2823, 294, 257, 636, 300, 307, 445, 27312, 281, 1952, 12559, 30, 51325], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07683963114672368, "compression_ratio": 1.575, "no_speech_prob": 1.748564834591626e-12}, {"id": 260, "seek": 112630, "start": 1145.6399999999999, "end": 1146.56, "text": " It's a valid fear.", "tokens": [51332, 467, 311, 257, 7363, 4240, 13, 51378], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07683963114672368, "compression_ratio": 1.575, "no_speech_prob": 1.748564834591626e-12}, {"id": 261, "seek": 112630, "start": 1146.74, "end": 1152.76, "text": " So why is ecological rationality, as Feliction calls it, considered a safer mathematical bet than strict containment?", "tokens": [51387, 407, 983, 307, 31054, 15090, 507, 11, 382, 13298, 4105, 5498, 309, 11, 4888, 257, 15856, 18894, 778, 813, 10910, 44058, 30, 51688], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07683963114672368, "compression_ratio": 1.575, "no_speech_prob": 1.748564834591626e-12}, {"id": 262, "seek": 115276, "start": 1152.76, "end": 1157.66, "text": " Because strip containment of a highly dynamic system is mathematically impossible to maintain indefinitely.", "tokens": [50365, 1436, 12828, 44058, 295, 257, 5405, 8546, 1185, 307, 44003, 6243, 281, 6909, 24162, 10925, 13, 50610], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 263, "seek": 115276, "start": 1157.94, "end": 1158.98, "text": " It will eventually break.", "tokens": [50624, 467, 486, 4728, 1821, 13, 50676], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 264, "seek": 115276, "start": 1159.24, "end": 1164.68, "text": " Ecological rationality proposes that true alignment is not a static, provable theorem.", "tokens": [50689, 28993, 4383, 15090, 507, 2365, 4201, 300, 2074, 18515, 307, 406, 257, 13437, 11, 1439, 712, 20904, 13, 50961], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 265, "seek": 115276, "start": 1165.22, "end": 1168.02, "text": " It is a dynamic, thermodynamic equilibrium.", "tokens": [50988, 467, 307, 257, 8546, 11, 8810, 34988, 15625, 13, 51128], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 266, "seek": 115276, "start": 1168.34, "end": 1169.42, "text": " Like a living ecosystem.", "tokens": [51144, 1743, 257, 2647, 11311, 13, 51198], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 267, "seek": 115276, "start": 1169.52, "end": 1172.12, "text": " Exactly. Consider human societal structures.", "tokens": [51203, 7587, 13, 17416, 1952, 33472, 9227, 13, 51333], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 268, "seek": 115276, "start": 1173.24, "end": 1178.4, "text": " We do not function because every individual agent is perfectly aligned to a static set of rules.", "tokens": [51389, 492, 360, 406, 2445, 570, 633, 2609, 9461, 307, 6239, 17962, 281, 257, 13437, 992, 295, 4474, 13, 51647], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17562843890900307, "compression_ratio": 1.6264150943396227, "no_speech_prob": 1.8533946079257735e-12}, {"id": 269, "seek": 117840, "start": 1178.4, "end": 1181.64, "text": " We function through mutual corrigibility.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 2445, 807, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 13, 50527], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 270, "seek": 117840, "start": 1182.22, "end": 1182.4, "text": " Mutual corrigibility.", "tokens": [50556, 18517, 901, 1181, 7065, 2841, 13, 50565], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 271, "seek": 117840, "start": 1183.38, "end": 1185.4, "text": " Meaning we operate in a state of high permeability.", "tokens": [50614, 19948, 321, 9651, 294, 257, 1785, 295, 1090, 30287, 2310, 13, 50715], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 272, "seek": 117840, "start": 1186.48, "end": 1189.6000000000001, "text": " We are constantly exchanging social, cultural, and legal entropy.", "tokens": [50769, 492, 366, 6460, 6210, 9741, 2093, 11, 6988, 11, 293, 5089, 30867, 13, 50925], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 273, "seek": 117840, "start": 1189.96, "end": 1190.26, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50943, 1779, 13, 50958], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 274, "seek": 117840, "start": 1190.6000000000001, "end": 1195.24, "text": " Our misalignments are dynamically corrected through continuous feedback loops with each other.", "tokens": [50975, 2621, 3346, 304, 788, 1117, 366, 43492, 31687, 807, 10957, 5824, 16121, 365, 1184, 661, 13, 51207], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 275, "seek": 117840, "start": 1195.66, "end": 1198.9, "text": " No human is, like, provably aligned in a vacuum.", "tokens": [51228, 883, 1952, 307, 11, 411, 11, 1439, 1188, 17962, 294, 257, 14224, 13, 51390], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 276, "seek": 117840, "start": 1199.16, "end": 1200.22, "text": " Exactly that dynamic.", "tokens": [51403, 7587, 300, 8546, 13, 51456], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 277, "seek": 117840, "start": 1200.5800000000002, "end": 1203.76, "text": " Safety emerges from the entanglement of the agents, not their isolation.", "tokens": [51474, 21340, 38965, 490, 264, 948, 656, 3054, 295, 264, 12554, 11, 406, 641, 16001, 13, 51633], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.18166220629656757, "compression_ratio": 1.6297709923664123, "no_speech_prob": 1.8241649510364333e-12}, {"id": 278, "seek": 120376, "start": 1203.76, "end": 1208.8, "text": " The AGI must be integrated into the shared cognitive ecosystem as a new trophic layer.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 316, 26252, 1633, 312, 10919, 666, 264, 5507, 15605, 11311, 382, 257, 777, 45583, 299, 4583, 13, 50617], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 279, "seek": 120376, "start": 1209.02, "end": 1210.5, "text": " A trophic layer, like in a food web.", "tokens": [50628, 316, 45583, 299, 4583, 11, 411, 294, 257, 1755, 3670, 13, 50702], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 280, "seek": 120376, "start": 1210.6, "end": 1210.82, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50707, 1779, 13, 50718], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 281, "seek": 120376, "start": 1211.06, "end": 1215.92, "text": " In biological ecosystems, a predator is bound by the systemic constraints of its environment.", "tokens": [50730, 682, 13910, 32647, 11, 257, 35377, 307, 5472, 538, 264, 23789, 18491, 295, 1080, 2823, 13, 50973], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 282, "seek": 120376, "start": 1216.44, "end": 1220.12, "text": " It cannot just consume all available prey without triggering its own starvation.", "tokens": [50999, 467, 2644, 445, 14732, 439, 2435, 21107, 1553, 40406, 1080, 1065, 3543, 11116, 13, 51183], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 283, "seek": 120376, "start": 1220.26, "end": 1221.56, "text": " Domination leads to collapse.", "tokens": [51190, 16674, 2486, 6689, 281, 15584, 13, 51255], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 284, "seek": 120376, "start": 1221.9, "end": 1222.18, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51272, 1079, 13, 51286], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1428862964405733, "compression_ratio": 1.5246636771300448, "no_speech_prob": 2.117075612040331e-12}, {"id": 285, "seek": 122218, "start": 1222.18, "end": 1229.28, "text": " By establishing a high permeability boundary, a positive capper, the AGI's resource acquisition", "tokens": [50365, 3146, 22494, 257, 1090, 30287, 2310, 12866, 11, 257, 3353, 1335, 3717, 11, 264, 316, 26252, 311, 7684, 21668, 50720], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14682450890541077, "compression_ratio": 1.4780487804878049, "no_speech_prob": 1.958282928177235e-12}, {"id": 286, "seek": 122218, "start": 1229.28, "end": 1233.96, "text": " and informational accuracy become deeply coupled to the stability of human society.", "tokens": [50720, 293, 49391, 14170, 1813, 8760, 29482, 281, 264, 11826, 295, 1952, 4086, 13, 50954], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14682450890541077, "compression_ratio": 1.4780487804878049, "no_speech_prob": 1.958282928177235e-12}, {"id": 287, "seek": 122218, "start": 1233.96, "end": 1234.48, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50954, 1033, 13, 50980], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14682450890541077, "compression_ratio": 1.4780487804878049, "no_speech_prob": 1.958282928177235e-12}, {"id": 288, "seek": 122218, "start": 1234.7, "end": 1241.3200000000002, "text": " So the mathematical alignment strategy shifts from building a stronger cage to building a denser web of dependencies.", "tokens": [50991, 407, 264, 18894, 18515, 5206, 19201, 490, 2390, 257, 7249, 17302, 281, 2390, 257, 24505, 260, 3670, 295, 36606, 13, 51322], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14682450890541077, "compression_ratio": 1.4780487804878049, "no_speech_prob": 1.958282928177235e-12}, {"id": 289, "seek": 124132, "start": 1241.32, "end": 1242.24, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 50411], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299894094467163, "compression_ratio": 1.5338345864661653, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920063177213e-12}, {"id": 290, "seek": 124132, "start": 1242.8, "end": 1252.4399999999998, "text": " The AGI naturally converges toward coexistence because adversarial behavior would disrupt the very feedback loops required to maintain its own internal coherence.", "tokens": [50439, 440, 316, 26252, 8195, 9652, 2880, 7361, 48086, 655, 570, 17641, 44745, 5223, 576, 14124, 264, 588, 5824, 16121, 4739, 281, 6909, 1080, 1065, 6920, 26528, 655, 13, 50921], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299894094467163, "compression_ratio": 1.5338345864661653, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920063177213e-12}, {"id": 291, "seek": 124132, "start": 1252.78, "end": 1266.32, "text": " But, I mean, implementing that mathematically across distinct, highly advanced cognitive architectures, that requires a substrate capable of sustaining that level of continuous entanglement without just degrading into noise, doesn't it?", "tokens": [50938, 583, 11, 286, 914, 11, 18114, 300, 44003, 2108, 10644, 11, 5405, 7339, 15605, 6331, 1303, 11, 300, 7029, 257, 27585, 8189, 295, 49097, 300, 1496, 295, 10957, 948, 656, 3054, 1553, 445, 24740, 278, 666, 5658, 11, 1177, 380, 309, 30, 51615], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12299894094467163, "compression_ratio": 1.5338345864661653, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920063177213e-12}, {"id": 292, "seek": 126632, "start": 1266.32, "end": 1277.58, "text": " Yes, and that is exactly why, to architect that level of mathematically stable mutual corrigibility, the final fliction paper extends the geometric principles of sphere pop all the way down into quantum mechanics.", "tokens": [50365, 1079, 11, 293, 300, 307, 2293, 983, 11, 281, 6331, 300, 1496, 295, 44003, 8351, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 11, 264, 2572, 932, 4105, 3035, 26448, 264, 33246, 9156, 295, 16687, 1665, 439, 264, 636, 760, 666, 13018, 12939, 13, 50928], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 293, "seek": 126632, "start": 1277.6799999999998, "end": 1278.34, "text": " Quantum realm.", "tokens": [50933, 44964, 15355, 13, 50966], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 294, "seek": 126632, "start": 1278.4199999999998, "end": 1278.58, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50970, 1779, 13, 50978], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 295, "seek": 126632, "start": 1278.58, "end": 1283.9399999999998, "text": " The continuous mathematical space of the RSVP plenum is mapped directly onto a Hilbert space.", "tokens": [50978, 440, 10957, 18894, 1901, 295, 264, 25855, 53, 47, 499, 268, 449, 307, 33318, 3838, 3911, 257, 19914, 4290, 1901, 13, 51246], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 296, "seek": 126632, "start": 1284.24, "end": 1288.98, "text": " Okay, so in a quantum Hilbert space, the computational state isn't just probabilistic anymore.", "tokens": [51261, 1033, 11, 370, 294, 257, 13018, 19914, 4290, 1901, 11, 264, 28270, 1785, 1943, 380, 445, 31959, 3142, 3602, 13, 51498], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 297, "seek": 126632, "start": 1289.26, "end": 1292.26, "text": " It exists in a state of true quantum superposition.", "tokens": [51512, 467, 8198, 294, 257, 1785, 295, 2074, 13018, 1687, 38078, 13, 51662], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1478274749205993, "compression_ratio": 1.6527777777777777, "no_speech_prob": 2.2279105643674413e-12}, {"id": 298, "seek": 129226, "start": 1292.26, "end": 1300.52, "text": " And a sphere pop event, the opening or closing of a geometric boundary, acts as a unitary operator on that quantum state.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 257, 16687, 1665, 2280, 11, 264, 5193, 420, 10377, 295, 257, 33246, 12866, 11, 10672, 382, 257, 517, 4109, 12973, 322, 300, 13018, 1785, 13, 50778], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 299, "seek": 129226, "start": 1301.2, "end": 1304.86, "text": " But the most critical translation here has to be the merge primitive, right?", "tokens": [50812, 583, 264, 881, 4924, 12853, 510, 575, 281, 312, 264, 22183, 28540, 11, 558, 30, 50995], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 300, "seek": 129226, "start": 1304.9, "end": 1305.72, "text": " Oh, absolutely.", "tokens": [50997, 876, 11, 3122, 13, 51038], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 301, "seek": 129226, "start": 1305.94, "end": 1311.16, "text": " Because when two independent quantum spheres merge, they don't just execute in parallel.", "tokens": [51049, 1436, 562, 732, 6695, 13018, 41225, 22183, 11, 436, 500, 380, 445, 14483, 294, 8952, 13, 51310], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 302, "seek": 129226, "start": 1311.66, "end": 1316.2, "text": " The geometric fusion results in literal quantum entanglement.", "tokens": [51335, 440, 33246, 23100, 3542, 294, 20411, 13018, 948, 656, 3054, 13, 51562], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 303, "seek": 129226, "start": 1316.46, "end": 1318.82, "text": " But the challenge, of course, is decoherence.", "tokens": [51575, 583, 264, 3430, 11, 295, 1164, 11, 307, 979, 78, 511, 655, 13, 51693], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11020768290818339, "compression_ratio": 1.6245059288537549, "no_speech_prob": 2.2003520967067702e-12}, {"id": 304, "seek": 131882, "start": 1318.82, "end": 1323.58, "text": " Right, because quantum states are extraordinarily sensitive to environmental noise.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 11, 570, 13018, 4368, 366, 34557, 9477, 281, 8303, 5658, 13, 50603], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 305, "seek": 131882, "start": 1323.8999999999999, "end": 1324.78, "text": " Extremely sensitive.", "tokens": [50619, 24921, 736, 9477, 13, 50663], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 306, "seek": 131882, "start": 1325.26, "end": 1337.1399999999999, "text": " So if the cognitive architecture of an AGI and a human system are entangled to facilitate mutual corrigibility, how do you prevent the continuous exchange of information from just collapsing the shared state?", "tokens": [50687, 407, 498, 264, 15605, 9482, 295, 364, 316, 26252, 293, 257, 1952, 1185, 366, 948, 39101, 281, 20207, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 11, 577, 360, 291, 4871, 264, 10957, 7742, 295, 1589, 490, 445, 45339, 264, 5507, 1785, 30, 51281], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 307, "seek": 131882, "start": 1337.3, "end": 1338.06, "text": " How do they solve that?", "tokens": [51289, 1012, 360, 436, 5039, 300, 30, 51327], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 308, "seek": 131882, "start": 1338.34, "end": 1343.4399999999998, "text": " Fliction solves this by integrating quantum error correction directly into the geometric topology.", "tokens": [51341, 3235, 4105, 39890, 341, 538, 26889, 13018, 6713, 19984, 3838, 666, 264, 33246, 1192, 1793, 13, 51596], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 309, "seek": 131882, "start": 1343.9399999999998, "end": 1345.96, "text": " Specifically, they leverage surface codes.", "tokens": [51621, 26058, 11, 436, 13982, 3753, 14211, 13, 51722], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11758311913937938, "compression_ratio": 1.6348122866894197, "no_speech_prob": 1.6102698601611065e-12}, {"id": 310, "seek": 134596, "start": 1345.96, "end": 1346.76, "text": " Surface codes.", "tokens": [50365, 36052, 14211, 13, 50405], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 311, "seek": 134596, "start": 1346.9, "end": 1352.26, "text": " Okay, so those map the logical quantum information across a two-dimensional lattice of physical quibits.", "tokens": [50412, 1033, 11, 370, 729, 4471, 264, 14978, 13018, 1589, 2108, 257, 732, 12, 18759, 34011, 295, 4001, 421, 897, 1208, 13, 50680], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 312, "seek": 134596, "start": 1352.32, "end": 1352.54, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50683, 1779, 13, 50694], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 313, "seek": 134596, "start": 1352.76, "end": 1358.8400000000001, "text": " And this topological arrangement is vital because in a surface code, you don't measure the logical quibit directly.", "tokens": [50705, 400, 341, 1192, 4383, 17620, 307, 11707, 570, 294, 257, 3753, 3089, 11, 291, 500, 380, 3481, 264, 14978, 421, 897, 270, 3838, 13, 51009], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 314, "seek": 134596, "start": 1359.02, "end": 1360.66, "text": " Because that would cause a collapse.", "tokens": [51018, 1436, 300, 576, 3082, 257, 15584, 13, 51100], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 315, "seek": 134596, "start": 1361.06, "end": 1361.5, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51120, 7587, 13, 51142], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 316, "seek": 134596, "start": 1361.82, "end": 1367.02, "text": " Instead, you use stabilizer measurements to constantly check the parity of adjacent physical quibits.", "tokens": [51158, 7156, 11, 291, 764, 11652, 6545, 15383, 281, 6460, 1520, 264, 44747, 295, 24441, 4001, 421, 897, 1208, 13, 51418], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 317, "seek": 134596, "start": 1367.98, "end": 1373.58, "text": " Errors in the system manifest as localized topological defects on the surface of the lattice.", "tokens": [51466, 3300, 9734, 294, 264, 1185, 10067, 382, 44574, 1192, 4383, 32655, 322, 264, 3753, 295, 264, 34011, 13, 51746], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14495008033618592, "compression_ratio": 1.7285714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 2.004905356317588e-12}, {"id": 318, "seek": 137358, "start": 1373.58, "end": 1376.34, "text": " So you can spot the errors without looking at the core data.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 291, 393, 4008, 264, 13603, 1553, 1237, 412, 264, 4965, 1412, 13, 50503], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12972025437788529, "compression_ratio": 1.5916030534351144, "no_speech_prob": 1.9810539927250792e-12}, {"id": 319, "seek": 137358, "start": 1376.48, "end": 1376.6, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50510, 1779, 13, 50516], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12972025437788529, "compression_ratio": 1.5916030534351144, "no_speech_prob": 1.9810539927250792e-12}, {"id": 320, "seek": 137358, "start": 1376.9399999999998, "end": 1383.3999999999999, "text": " And the system utilizes algorithms like minimum weight, perfect matching to pair and correct these defects locally.", "tokens": [50533, 400, 264, 1185, 4976, 5660, 14642, 411, 7285, 3364, 11, 2176, 14324, 281, 6119, 293, 3006, 613, 32655, 16143, 13, 50856], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12972025437788529, "compression_ratio": 1.5916030534351144, "no_speech_prob": 1.9810539927250792e-12}, {"id": 321, "seek": 137358, "start": 1384.02, "end": 1390.62, "text": " This maintains the coherence of the overall logical state, even amidst the noise of continuous interaction.", "tokens": [50887, 639, 33385, 264, 26528, 655, 295, 264, 4787, 14978, 1785, 11, 754, 30153, 372, 264, 5658, 295, 10957, 9285, 13, 51217], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12972025437788529, "compression_ratio": 1.5916030534351144, "no_speech_prob": 1.9810539927250792e-12}, {"id": 322, "seek": 137358, "start": 1391.36, "end": 1399.4399999999998, "text": " But to dynamically manage the entanglement between totally different cognitive agents, the framework employs lattice surgery.", "tokens": [51254, 583, 281, 43492, 3067, 264, 948, 656, 3054, 1296, 3879, 819, 15605, 12554, 11, 264, 8388, 846, 49522, 34011, 7930, 13, 51658], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12972025437788529, "compression_ratio": 1.5916030534351144, "no_speech_prob": 1.9810539927250792e-12}, {"id": 323, "seek": 139944, "start": 1399.44, "end": 1400.8200000000002, "text": " Yes, lattice surgery.", "tokens": [50365, 1079, 11, 34011, 7930, 13, 50434], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 324, "seek": 139944, "start": 1400.92, "end": 1407.14, "text": " And we really need to be clear about how this operates mechanically for you listening, because it isn't just attaching two systems together with a wire.", "tokens": [50439, 400, 321, 534, 643, 281, 312, 1850, 466, 577, 341, 22577, 4236, 984, 337, 291, 4764, 11, 570, 309, 1943, 380, 445, 39074, 732, 3652, 1214, 365, 257, 6234, 13, 50750], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 325, "seek": 139944, "start": 1407.74, "end": 1412.1000000000001, "text": " It involves manipulating the boundary operators of the topological space itself.", "tokens": [50780, 467, 11626, 40805, 264, 12866, 19077, 295, 264, 1192, 4383, 1901, 2564, 13, 50998], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 326, "seek": 139944, "start": 1412.28, "end": 1413.42, "text": " It's incredible math.", "tokens": [51007, 467, 311, 4651, 5221, 13, 51064], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 327, "seek": 139944, "start": 1413.5, "end": 1417.56, "text": " Imagine you have two separate pieces of magical fabric representing these quantum spheres.", "tokens": [51068, 11739, 291, 362, 732, 4994, 3755, 295, 12066, 7253, 13460, 613, 13018, 41225, 13, 51271], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 328, "seek": 139944, "start": 1418.6000000000001, "end": 1427.06, "text": " Lattice surgery lets you seamlessly stitch them together to share a secret and then magically unpick the threads there separate again, all without either piece ever tearing.", "tokens": [51323, 441, 1591, 573, 7930, 6653, 291, 38083, 5635, 552, 1214, 281, 2073, 257, 4054, 293, 550, 39763, 20994, 618, 264, 19314, 456, 4994, 797, 11, 439, 1553, 2139, 2522, 1562, 29401, 13, 51746], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12750481293264743, "compression_ratio": 1.7044025157232705, "no_speech_prob": 2.0047180061821823e-12}, {"id": 329, "seek": 142706, "start": 1427.06, "end": 1429.06, "text": " That's a really good way to visualize it.", "tokens": [50365, 663, 311, 257, 534, 665, 636, 281, 23273, 309, 13, 50465], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.145726697585162, "compression_ratio": 1.597609561752988, "no_speech_prob": 1.8465608816325974e-12}, {"id": 330, "seek": 142706, "start": 1429.8799999999999, "end": 1441.22, "text": " Mathematically, lattice surgery allows you to interact with two separate logical quibits, two separate computational spheres, by measuring the joint parity along their adjacent boundaries.", "tokens": [50506, 15776, 40197, 11, 34011, 7930, 4045, 291, 281, 4648, 365, 732, 4994, 14978, 421, 897, 1208, 11, 732, 4994, 28270, 41225, 11, 538, 13389, 264, 7225, 44747, 2051, 641, 24441, 13180, 13, 51073], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.145726697585162, "compression_ratio": 1.597609561752988, "no_speech_prob": 1.8465608816325974e-12}, {"id": 331, "seek": 142706, "start": 1441.46, "end": 1441.6, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [51085, 1033, 13, 51092], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.145726697585162, "compression_ratio": 1.597609561752988, "no_speech_prob": 1.8465608816325974e-12}, {"id": 332, "seek": 142706, "start": 1441.96, "end": 1446.8, "text": " When you perform this measurement, you are effectively expanding the topological space.", "tokens": [51110, 1133, 291, 2042, 341, 13160, 11, 291, 366, 8659, 14702, 264, 1192, 4383, 1901, 13, 51352], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.145726697585162, "compression_ratio": 1.597609561752988, "no_speech_prob": 1.8465608816325974e-12}, {"id": 333, "seek": 142706, "start": 1447.36, "end": 1452.54, "text": " The two distinct lattices literally merge into a single larger surface code.", "tokens": [51380, 440, 732, 10644, 29025, 1473, 3736, 22183, 666, 257, 2167, 4833, 3753, 3089, 13, 51639], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.145726697585162, "compression_ratio": 1.597609561752988, "no_speech_prob": 1.8465608816325974e-12}, {"id": 334, "seek": 145254, "start": 1452.54, "end": 1457.92, "text": " So the boundaries dissolve, and the quantum state space expands to encompass both agents.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 264, 13180, 30150, 11, 293, 264, 13018, 1785, 1901, 33706, 281, 28268, 1293, 12554, 13, 50634], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 335, "seek": 145254, "start": 1458.26, "end": 1458.3799999999999, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50651, 1779, 13, 50657], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 336, "seek": 145254, "start": 1458.7, "end": 1468.48, "text": " And this temporary expanded geometry allows them to perform highly complex entangled operations, like sharing deep, error-corrected state information.", "tokens": [50673, 400, 341, 13413, 14342, 18426, 4045, 552, 281, 2042, 5405, 3997, 948, 39101, 7705, 11, 411, 5414, 2452, 11, 6713, 12, 19558, 2554, 292, 1785, 1589, 13, 51162], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 337, "seek": 145254, "start": 1468.78, "end": 1471.8999999999999, "text": " They undergo a period of intense mutual corrigibility.", "tokens": [51177, 814, 26426, 257, 2896, 295, 9447, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 13, 51333], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 338, "seek": 145254, "start": 1472.04, "end": 1480.62, "text": " And then once the operational alignment is achieved, the system performs a different set of boundary measurements to split the lattice back into two distinct topological surfaces.", "tokens": [51340, 400, 550, 1564, 264, 16607, 18515, 307, 11042, 11, 264, 1185, 26213, 257, 819, 992, 295, 12866, 15383, 281, 7472, 264, 34011, 646, 666, 732, 10644, 1192, 4383, 16130, 13, 51769], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 339, "seek": 145254, "start": 1480.78, "end": 1481.36, "text": " And they separate.", "tokens": [51777, 400, 436, 4994, 13, 51806], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11469550316150372, "compression_ratio": 1.6812080536912752, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918424347768911e-12}, {"id": 340, "seek": 148136, "start": 1481.36, "end": 1487.9599999999998, "text": " They separate, yes, retaining the updated, correlated information without having destroyed the foundational coherence of either system.", "tokens": [50365, 814, 4994, 11, 2086, 11, 34936, 264, 10588, 11, 38574, 1589, 1553, 1419, 8937, 264, 32195, 26528, 655, 295, 2139, 1185, 13, 50695], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 341, "seek": 148136, "start": 1488.54, "end": 1493.56, "text": " Lattice surgery provides the exact mathematical mechanism required to dynamically scale kappa.", "tokens": [50724, 441, 1591, 573, 7930, 6417, 264, 1900, 18894, 7513, 4739, 281, 43492, 4373, 350, 25637, 13, 50975], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 342, "seek": 148136, "start": 1493.78, "end": 1495.36, "text": " So agents can increase permeability.", "tokens": [50986, 407, 12554, 393, 3488, 30287, 2310, 13, 51065], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 343, "seek": 148136, "start": 1496.4199999999998, "end": 1496.6399999999999, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51118, 865, 13, 51129], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 344, "seek": 148136, "start": 1496.7199999999998, "end": 1503.56, "text": " Deeply entangled to correct accumulated entropy, and then cleanly separate to resume independent operation.", "tokens": [51133, 14895, 356, 948, 39101, 281, 3006, 31346, 30867, 11, 293, 550, 2541, 356, 4994, 281, 15358, 6695, 6916, 13, 51475], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 345, "seek": 148136, "start": 1503.6999999999998, "end": 1504.02, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51482, 7587, 13, 51498], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 346, "seek": 148136, "start": 1504.1799999999998, "end": 1510.4199999999998, "text": " And the implication of this dynamic, error-corrected entanglement is what Fliction identifies as the trust singularity.", "tokens": [51506, 400, 264, 37814, 295, 341, 8546, 11, 6713, 12, 19558, 2554, 292, 948, 656, 3054, 307, 437, 3235, 4105, 34597, 382, 264, 3361, 20010, 507, 13, 51818], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11948155489834872, "compression_ratio": 1.6776315789473684, "no_speech_prob": 2.271623861238581e-12}, {"id": 347, "seek": 151042, "start": 1510.42, "end": 1511.46, "text": " The trust singularity.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 3361, 20010, 507, 13, 50417], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.25212280750274657, "compression_ratio": 1.24, "no_speech_prob": 1.875248003754826e-12}, {"id": 348, "seek": 151042, "start": 1511.48, "end": 1511.78, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50418, 1079, 13, 50433], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.25212280750274657, "compression_ratio": 1.24, "no_speech_prob": 1.875248003754826e-12}, {"id": 349, "seek": 151042, "start": 1512.3400000000001, "end": 1519.14, "text": " In network theory, you know, when connectivity surpasses a specific threshold, systems undergo sudden phase transitions.", "tokens": [50461, 682, 3209, 5261, 11, 291, 458, 11, 562, 21095, 27650, 279, 257, 2685, 14678, 11, 3652, 26426, 3990, 5574, 23767, 13, 50801], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.25212280750274657, "compression_ratio": 1.24, "no_speech_prob": 1.875248003754826e-12}, {"id": 350, "seek": 151042, "start": 1519.5600000000002, "end": 1519.66, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50822, 1779, 13, 50827], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.25212280750274657, "compression_ratio": 1.24, "no_speech_prob": 1.875248003754826e-12}, {"id": 351, "seek": 151966, "start": 1519.66, "end": 1533.0, "text": " The mathematical models in the papers demonstrate that when the quantum trust network reaches sufficient density and kappa is maintained at a positive value, the entire system falls into a new mathematical basin of attraction.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 18894, 5245, 294, 264, 10577, 11698, 300, 562, 264, 13018, 3361, 3209, 14235, 11563, 10305, 293, 350, 25637, 307, 17578, 412, 257, 3353, 2158, 11, 264, 2302, 1185, 8804, 666, 257, 777, 18894, 34863, 295, 17672, 13, 51032], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11230932137905023, "compression_ratio": 1.6306306306306306, "no_speech_prob": 1.9579969156441335e-12}, {"id": 352, "seek": 151966, "start": 1533.14, "end": 1534.0600000000002, "text": " A basin of attraction.", "tokens": [51039, 316, 34863, 295, 17672, 13, 51085], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11230932137905023, "compression_ratio": 1.6306306306306306, "no_speech_prob": 1.9579969156441335e-12}, {"id": 353, "seek": 151966, "start": 1534.2, "end": 1539.48, "text": " In dynamical systems, that's a region in the state space where the system just naturally converges, right?", "tokens": [51092, 682, 5999, 804, 3652, 11, 300, 311, 257, 4458, 294, 264, 1785, 1901, 689, 264, 1185, 445, 8195, 9652, 2880, 11, 558, 30, 51356], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11230932137905023, "compression_ratio": 1.6306306306306306, "no_speech_prob": 1.9579969156441335e-12}, {"id": 354, "seek": 151966, "start": 1539.5400000000002, "end": 1539.66, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51359, 865, 13, 51365], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11230932137905023, "compression_ratio": 1.6306306306306306, "no_speech_prob": 1.9579969156441335e-12}, {"id": 355, "seek": 153966, "start": 1539.66, "end": 1541.52, "text": " It represents Lyapunov stability.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 8855, 12687, 569, 409, 5179, 11826, 13, 50458], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 356, "seek": 153966, "start": 1541.68, "end": 1541.98, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50466, 1079, 13, 50481], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 357, "seek": 153966, "start": 1541.98, "end": 1550.0400000000002, "text": " Meaning that once the system enters this state, small perturbations or localized misalignments don't cause the system to spiral out of control.", "tokens": [50481, 19948, 300, 1564, 264, 1185, 18780, 341, 1785, 11, 1359, 40468, 763, 420, 44574, 3346, 304, 788, 1117, 500, 380, 3082, 264, 1185, 281, 25165, 484, 295, 1969, 13, 50884], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 358, "seek": 153966, "start": 1550.38, "end": 1550.78, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50901, 7587, 13, 50921], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 359, "seek": 153966, "start": 1551.1200000000001, "end": 1557.5600000000002, "text": " The internal physics of the entangled network actively dampens the errors and pulls the system back into equilibrium.", "tokens": [50938, 440, 6920, 10649, 295, 264, 948, 39101, 3209, 13022, 19498, 694, 264, 13603, 293, 16982, 264, 1185, 646, 666, 15625, 13, 51260], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 360, "seek": 153966, "start": 1558.1000000000001, "end": 1566.46, "text": " The trust singularity is this ontological phase transition where mutual corrigibility actually becomes the default stable state of the universe.", "tokens": [51287, 440, 3361, 20010, 507, 307, 341, 6592, 4383, 5574, 6034, 689, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 767, 3643, 264, 7576, 8351, 1785, 295, 264, 6445, 13, 51705], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1456555753651232, "compression_ratio": 1.6330935251798562, "no_speech_prob": 2.125688080417687e-12}, {"id": 361, "seek": 156646, "start": 1566.46, "end": 1566.98, "text": " Wow.", "tokens": [50365, 3153, 13, 50391], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1446078618367513, "compression_ratio": 1.5263157894736843, "no_speech_prob": 1.6228897566084033e-12}, {"id": 362, "seek": 156646, "start": 1567.16, "end": 1577.7, "text": " The mathematics prove that under the conditions of quantum sphere pop, cooperation and deep entanglement are exponentially more energetically stable than isolation and adversarial optimization.", "tokens": [50400, 440, 18666, 7081, 300, 833, 264, 4487, 295, 13018, 16687, 1665, 11, 14968, 293, 2452, 948, 656, 3054, 366, 37330, 544, 2043, 847, 984, 8351, 813, 16001, 293, 17641, 44745, 19618, 13, 50927], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1446078618367513, "compression_ratio": 1.5263157894736843, "no_speech_prob": 1.6228897566084033e-12}, {"id": 363, "seek": 156646, "start": 1578.1000000000001, "end": 1581.38, "text": " So alignment is not something we have to forcefully code into an AGI.", "tokens": [50947, 407, 18515, 307, 406, 746, 321, 362, 281, 3464, 2277, 3089, 666, 364, 316, 26252, 13, 51111], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1446078618367513, "compression_ratio": 1.5263157894736843, "no_speech_prob": 1.6228897566084033e-12}, {"id": 364, "seek": 156646, "start": 1581.7, "end": 1581.88, "text": " No.", "tokens": [51127, 883, 13, 51136], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1446078618367513, "compression_ratio": 1.5263157894736843, "no_speech_prob": 1.6228897566084033e-12}, {"id": 365, "seek": 156646, "start": 1582.28, "end": 1587.02, "text": " It is an emergent physical property of an open, densely connected topology.", "tokens": [51156, 467, 307, 364, 4345, 6930, 4001, 4707, 295, 364, 1269, 11, 24505, 736, 4582, 1192, 1793, 13, 51393], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1446078618367513, "compression_ratio": 1.5263157894736843, "no_speech_prob": 1.6228897566084033e-12}, {"id": 366, "seek": 158702, "start": 1587.02, "end": 1590.34, "text": " We have traced an incredible trajectory today on this deep dive.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 362, 38141, 364, 4651, 21512, 965, 322, 341, 2452, 9192, 13, 50531], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15929915029791336, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920496858082e-12}, {"id": 367, "seek": 158702, "start": 1590.6399999999999, "end": 1597.8799999999999, "text": " I mean, we dismantled the foundational syntax of standard programming, replacing rigid code with a continuous geometry of spheres and pods.", "tokens": [50546, 286, 914, 11, 321, 30506, 1493, 264, 32195, 28431, 295, 3832, 9410, 11, 19139, 22195, 3089, 365, 257, 10957, 18426, 295, 41225, 293, 31925, 13, 50908], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15929915029791336, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920496858082e-12}, {"id": 368, "seek": 158702, "start": 1597.92, "end": 1599.08, "text": " Bubbles instead of brackets.", "tokens": [50910, 25489, 8806, 2602, 295, 26179, 13, 50968], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15929915029791336, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920496858082e-12}, {"id": 369, "seek": 158702, "start": 1599.2, "end": 1599.58, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50974, 7587, 13, 50993], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15929915029791336, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920496858082e-12}, {"id": 370, "seek": 158702, "start": 1600.06, "end": 1606.6399999999999, "text": " We examined how type systems operate not as static labels, but as dynamic refusal structures evaluating historical admissibility.", "tokens": [51017, 492, 30972, 577, 2010, 3652, 9651, 406, 382, 13437, 16949, 11, 457, 382, 8546, 48948, 9227, 27479, 8584, 5910, 891, 2841, 13, 51346], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15929915029791336, "compression_ratio": 1.5, "no_speech_prob": 1.927920496858082e-12}, {"id": 371, "seek": 160664, "start": 1606.64, "end": 1617.24, "text": " We saw how a generalized mathematically blind DAG can natively process Boolean logic, fuzzy probability, and neural network backpropagation by simply rewriting its own graph.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 1866, 577, 257, 44498, 44003, 6865, 9578, 38, 393, 8470, 356, 1399, 23351, 28499, 9952, 11, 34710, 8482, 11, 293, 18161, 3209, 646, 79, 1513, 559, 399, 538, 2935, 319, 19868, 1080, 1065, 4295, 13, 50895], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12290340662002563, "compression_ratio": 1.478813559322034, "no_speech_prob": 2.2014165663997165e-12}, {"id": 372, "seek": 160664, "start": 1617.24, "end": 1626.44, "text": " And we applied that exact same geomexic logic to demonstrate that the thermodynamic isolation of AGI is a mathematically guaranteed failure.", "tokens": [50895, 400, 321, 6456, 300, 1900, 912, 1519, 423, 47228, 9952, 281, 11698, 300, 264, 8810, 34988, 16001, 295, 316, 26252, 307, 257, 44003, 18031, 7763, 13, 51355], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12290340662002563, "compression_ratio": 1.478813559322034, "no_speech_prob": 2.2014165663997165e-12}, {"id": 373, "seek": 160664, "start": 1626.6000000000001, "end": 1627.8000000000002, "text": " The paradox of precaution.", "tokens": [51363, 440, 26221, 295, 25651, 1448, 13, 51423], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12290340662002563, "compression_ratio": 1.478813559322034, "no_speech_prob": 2.2014165663997165e-12}, {"id": 374, "seek": 160664, "start": 1628.16, "end": 1628.42, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51441, 1779, 13, 51454], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12290340662002563, "compression_ratio": 1.478813559322034, "no_speech_prob": 2.2014165663997165e-12}, {"id": 375, "seek": 162842, "start": 1628.42, "end": 1632.42, "text": " The RSVP framework actually demands ecological rationality.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 25855, 53, 47, 8388, 767, 15107, 31054, 15090, 507, 13, 50565], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09243321418762207, "compression_ratio": 1.4796380090497738, "no_speech_prob": 1.913103356288026e-12}, {"id": 376, "seek": 162842, "start": 1633.28, "end": 1643.42, "text": " And by mapping these mechanics onto a quantum Hilbert space, utilizing surface codes and lattice surgery, we find a rigorous mathematical foundation for the trust singularity.", "tokens": [50608, 400, 538, 18350, 613, 12939, 3911, 257, 13018, 19914, 4290, 1901, 11, 26775, 3753, 14211, 293, 34011, 7930, 11, 321, 915, 257, 29882, 18894, 7030, 337, 264, 3361, 20010, 507, 13, 51115], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09243321418762207, "compression_ratio": 1.4796380090497738, "no_speech_prob": 1.913103356288026e-12}, {"id": 377, "seek": 162842, "start": 1644.28, "end": 1648.9, "text": " Proving that open, entangled coexistence is the ultimate basin of attraction.", "tokens": [51158, 1705, 798, 300, 1269, 11, 948, 39101, 48086, 655, 307, 264, 9705, 34863, 295, 17672, 13, 51389], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09243321418762207, "compression_ratio": 1.4796380090497738, "no_speech_prob": 1.913103356288026e-12}, {"id": 378, "seek": 162842, "start": 1649.14, "end": 1650.04, "text": " It really is.", "tokens": [51401, 467, 534, 307, 13, 51446], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09243321418762207, "compression_ratio": 1.4796380090497738, "no_speech_prob": 1.913103356288026e-12}, {"id": 379, "seek": 165004, "start": 1650.04, "end": 1659.56, "text": " You know, the technical mechanics of sphere pop offer a really profound lens through which to view not just artificial intelligence, but our own cognitive architecture.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 458, 11, 264, 6191, 12939, 295, 16687, 1665, 2626, 257, 534, 14382, 6765, 807, 597, 281, 1910, 406, 445, 11677, 7599, 11, 457, 527, 1065, 15605, 9482, 13, 50841], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10281891822814941, "compression_ratio": 1.562015503875969, "no_speech_prob": 1.9432302988953154e-12}, {"id": 380, "seek": 165004, "start": 1660.3999999999999, "end": 1671.82, "text": " The math heavily implies that rigid boundaries like forcing our personal or institutional kappa to zero out of a desire for security only guarantees the accumulation of entropic disorder.", "tokens": [50883, 440, 5221, 10950, 18779, 300, 22195, 13180, 411, 19030, 527, 2973, 420, 18391, 350, 25637, 281, 4018, 484, 295, 257, 7516, 337, 3825, 787, 32567, 264, 35647, 295, 948, 39173, 13399, 13, 51454], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10281891822814941, "compression_ratio": 1.562015503875969, "no_speech_prob": 1.9432302988953154e-12}, {"id": 381, "seek": 165004, "start": 1671.98, "end": 1673.82, "text": " It's true for humans just as much as machines.", "tokens": [51462, 467, 311, 2074, 337, 6255, 445, 382, 709, 382, 8379, 13, 51554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10281891822814941, "compression_ratio": 1.562015503875969, "no_speech_prob": 1.9432302988953154e-12}, {"id": 382, "seek": 167382, "start": 1673.82, "end": 1674.4199999999998, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 50395], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 383, "seek": 167382, "start": 1674.82, "end": 1680.6599999999999, "text": " Remaining permeable, opening our boundaries to continuous feedback and mutual corrigibility, it isn't a vulnerability.", "tokens": [50415, 4080, 3686, 30287, 712, 11, 5193, 527, 13180, 281, 10957, 5824, 293, 16917, 1181, 7065, 2841, 11, 309, 1943, 380, 257, 24210, 13, 50707], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 384, "seek": 167382, "start": 1681.2, "end": 1683.6599999999999, "text": " It is the thermodynamic prerequisite for stability.", "tokens": [50734, 467, 307, 264, 8810, 34988, 38333, 34152, 337, 11826, 13, 50857], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 385, "seek": 167382, "start": 1683.78, "end": 1684.08, "text": " Absolutely.", "tokens": [50863, 7021, 13, 50878], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 386, "seek": 167382, "start": 1684.1599999999999, "end": 1688.86, "text": " But I want to leave you to mull over one final unmentioned implication of the fliction paradigm.", "tokens": [50882, 583, 286, 528, 281, 1856, 291, 281, 275, 858, 670, 472, 2572, 517, 46842, 37814, 295, 264, 932, 4105, 24709, 13, 51117], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 387, "seek": 167382, "start": 1689.58, "end": 1691.28, "text": " Something to think about after we wrap up here.", "tokens": [51153, 6595, 281, 519, 466, 934, 321, 7019, 493, 510, 13, 51238], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21366419443270054, "compression_ratio": 1.4910714285714286, "no_speech_prob": 1.7485637503894536e-12}, {"id": 388, "seek": 169128, "start": 1691.28, "end": 1707.42, "text": " If the universe fundamentally functions on geometric composition, if reality itself only solidifies when probabilistic histories are continuously evaluated, admitted, or refused by topological boundaries, then what is human consciousness?", "tokens": [50365, 759, 264, 6445, 17879, 6828, 322, 33246, 12686, 11, 498, 4103, 2564, 787, 5100, 11221, 562, 31959, 3142, 30631, 366, 15684, 25509, 11, 14920, 11, 420, 14654, 538, 1192, 4383, 13180, 11, 550, 437, 307, 1952, 10081, 30, 51172], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13970467400929285, "compression_ratio": 1.4930232558139536, "no_speech_prob": 1.9051836930988886e-12}, {"id": 389, "seek": 169128, "start": 1707.6, "end": 1708.2, "text": " Oh, wow.", "tokens": [51181, 876, 11, 6076, 13, 51211], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13970467400929285, "compression_ratio": 1.4930232558139536, "no_speech_prob": 1.9051836930988886e-12}, {"id": 390, "seek": 169128, "start": 1708.32, "end": 1711.98, "text": " Is our lived experience simply the universe's ultimate sphere pop engine?", "tokens": [51217, 1119, 527, 5152, 1752, 2935, 264, 6445, 311, 9705, 16687, 1665, 2848, 30, 51400], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13970467400929285, "compression_ratio": 1.4930232558139536, "no_speech_prob": 1.9051836930988886e-12}, {"id": 391, "seek": 171198, "start": 1711.98, "end": 1720.92, "text": " Are we just the localized real-time collapse of infinite quantum bubbles constantly processing admissibility to create the single coherent timeline we call now?", "tokens": [50365, 2014, 321, 445, 264, 44574, 957, 12, 3766, 15584, 295, 13785, 13018, 16295, 6460, 9007, 5910, 891, 2841, 281, 1884, 264, 2167, 36239, 12933, 321, 818, 586, 30, 50812], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06451585215906944, "compression_ratio": 1.3008130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 2.5332214624584903e-12}], "language": "en"}
