30, 13, 50903], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20684753320156, "compression_ratio": 1.2352941176470589, "no_speech_prob": 1.825057683105258e-12}, {"id": 25, "seek": 5804, "start": 69.3, "end": 69.4, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50928, 1779, 13, 50933], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20684753320156, "compression_ratio": 1.2352941176470589, "no_speech_prob": 1.825057683105258e-12}, {"id": 26, "seek": 6940, "start": 69.4, "end": 75.80000000000001, "text": " And yet, conceptually, we tend to force both of those phenomenologies into the exact same architectural metaphor.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 1939, 11, 3410, 671, 11, 321, 3928, 281, 3464, 1293, 295, 729, 9388, 6204, 666, 264, 1900, 912, 26621, 19157, 13, 50685], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1599879437182323, "compression_ratio": 1.5622317596566524, "no_speech_prob": 1.426927478086204e-12}, {"id": 27, "seek": 6940, "start": 76.36, "end": 80.96000000000001, "text": " We treat them both as operations interacting with a, like a storage box.", "tokens": [50713, 492, 2387, 552, 1293, 382, 7705, 18017, 365, 257, 11, 411, 257, 6725, 2424, 13, 50943], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1599879437182323, "compression_ratio": 1.5622317596566524, "no_speech_prob": 1.426927478086204e-12}, {"id": 28, "seek": 6940, "start": 81.06, "end": 82.14, "text": " The old hard drive analogy.", "tokens": [50948, 440, 1331, 1152, 3332, 21663, 13, 51002], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1599879437182323, "compression_ratio": 1.5622317596566524, "no_speech_prob": 1.426927478086204e-12}, {"id": 29, "seek": 6940, "start": 82.24000000000001, "end": 82.7, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51007, 7587, 13, 51030], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1599879437182323, "compression_ratio": 1.5622317596566524, "no_speech_prob": 1.426927478086204e-12}, {"id": 30, "seek": 6940, "start": 83.12, "end": 91.64000000000001, "text": " We assume the interpreter pulls operational values out of memory addresses, overwrites old states with new integers, and returns the result.", "tokens": [51051, 492, 6552, 264, 34132, 16982, 16607, 4190, 484, 295, 4675, 16862, 11, 670, 86, 30931, 1331, 4368, 365, 777, 41674, 11, 293, 11247, 264, 1874, 13, 51477], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1599879437182323, "compression_ratio": 1.5622317596566524, "no_speech_prob": 1.426927478086204e-12}, {"id": 31, "seek": 9164, "start": 92.26, "end": 96.82, "text": " And simultaneously, we model human memory as this biological rate array.", "tokens": [50396, 400, 16561, 11, 321, 2316, 1952, 4675, 382, 341, 13910, 3314, 10225, 13, 50624], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1303395132223765, "compression_ratio": 1.6307692307692307, "no_speech_prob": 1.585884201737997e-12}, {"id": 32, "seek": 9164, "start": 96.98, "end": 102.8, "text": " Right. Assuming that forgetting a passphrase just means a cluster of data was zeroed out or, you know, corrupted in the box.", "tokens": [50632, 1779, 13, 6281, 24919, 300, 25428, 257, 1320, 44598, 651, 445, 1355, 257, 13630, 295, 1412, 390, 4018, 292, 484, 420, 11, 291, 458, 11, 39480, 294, 264, 2424, 13, 50923], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1303395132223765, "compression_ratio": 1.6307692307692307, "no_speech_prob": 1.585884201737997e-12}, {"id": 33, "seek": 9164, "start": 102.8, "end": 106.52, "text": " Right. But what if that entire paradigm is just a complete hallucination?", "tokens": [50923, 1779, 13, 583, 437, 498, 300, 2302, 24709, 307, 445, 257, 3566, 35212, 2486, 30, 51109], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1303395132223765, "compression_ratio": 1.6307692307692307, "no_speech_prob": 1.585884201737997e-12}, {"id": 34, "seek": 9164, "start": 107.08, "end": 115.1, "text": " What if the way we construct computational logic and the way we model the degradation of human memory are both built on a fundamentally flawed ontology?", "tokens": [51137, 708, 498, 264, 636, 321, 7690, 28270, 9952, 293, 264, 636, 321, 2316, 264, 40519, 295, 1952, 4675, 366, 1293, 3094, 322, 257, 17879, 38823, 6592, 1793, 30, 51538], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1303395132223765, "compression_ratio": 1.6307692307692307, "no_speech_prob": 1.585884201737997e-12}, {"id": 35, "seek": 11510, "start": 115.1, "end": 118.36, "text": " Well, that is the exact premise of the sources we are looking at today.", "tokens": [50365, 1042, 11, 300, 307, 264, 1900, 22045, 295, 264, 7139, 321, 366, 1237, 412, 965, 13, 50528], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1450619348665563, "compression_ratio": 1.4563106796116505, "no_speech_prob": 2.1928312030766728e-12}, {"id": 36, "seek": 11510, "start": 118.47999999999999, "end": 126.36, "text": " Yes. So, welcome to today's Deep Dive. We are digging into two monolithic 2026 monographs by the independent researcher, Fliction.", "tokens": [50534, 1079, 13, 407, 11, 2928, 281, 965, 311, 14895, 413, 488, 13, 492, 366, 17343, 666, 732, 1108, 42878, 945, 10880, 1108, 3108, 82, 538, 264, 6695, 21751, 11, 3235, 4105, 13, 50928], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1450619348665563, "compression_ratio": 1.4563106796116505, "no_speech_prob": 2.1928312030766728e-12}, {"id": 37, "seek": 11510, "start": 126.64, "end": 127.5, "text": " And they are dense.", "tokens": [50942, 400, 436, 366, 18011, 13, 50985], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1450619348665563, "compression_ratio": 1.4563106796116505, "no_speech_prob": 2.1928312030766728e-12}, {"id": 38, "seek": 11510, "start": 127.91999999999999, "end": 132.35999999999999, "text": " Oh, incredibly dense. But we're looking at the first one, Beyond Parentheses.", "tokens": [51006, 876, 11, 6252, 18011, 13, 583, 321, 434, 1237, 412, 264, 700, 472, 11, 19707, 430, 20616, 23639, 13, 51228], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1450619348665563, "compression_ratio": 1.4563106796116505, "no_speech_prob": 2.1928312030766728e-12}, {"id": 39, "seek": 13236, "start": 132.36, "end": 154.58, "text": " These texts are, I mean, mathematically brutal, but they force a paradigm shift that is basically impossible to ignore once you actually grasp it.", "tokens": [50365, 1981, 15765, 366, 11, 286, 914, 11, 44003, 17878, 11, 457, 436, 3464, 257, 24709, 5513, 300, 307, 1936, 6243, 281, 11200, 1564, 291, 767, 21743, 309, 13, 51476], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10434330254793167, "compression_ratio": 1.280701754385965, "no_speech_prob": 1.5735375242381666e-12}, {"id": 40, "seek": 15458, "start": 154.58, "end": 162.92000000000002, "text": " Our mission today is to map out this mind-bending shift. We are moving away from the idea of information as symbols in a storage box.", "tokens": [50365, 2621, 4447, 965, 307, 281, 4471, 484, 341, 1575, 12, 65, 2029, 5513, 13, 492, 366, 2684, 1314, 490, 264, 1558, 295, 1589, 382, 16944, 294, 257, 6725, 2424, 13, 50782], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05607892407311334, "compression_ratio": 1.5850340136054422, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918428684577601e-12}, {"id": 41, "seek": 15458, "start": 162.92000000000002, "end": 169.10000000000002, "text": " Right. Because Fliction is proposing that computation must be modeled as an irreversible, growing geometric history.", "tokens": [50782, 1779, 13, 1436, 3235, 4105, 307, 29939, 300, 24903, 1633, 312, 37140, 382, 364, 16014, 840, 964, 11, 4194, 33246, 2503, 13, 51091], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05607892407311334, "compression_ratio": 1.5850340136054422, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918428684577601e-12}, {"id": 42, "seek": 15458, "start": 169.22000000000003, "end": 169.94, "text": " Which is wild.", "tokens": [51097, 3013, 307, 4868, 13, 51133], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05607892407311334, "compression_ratio": 1.5850340136054422, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918428684577601e-12}, {"id": 43, "seek": 15458, "start": 170.16000000000003, "end": 181.12, "text": " It is. And that memory, whether biological or institutional, is not a hard drive. It's a physical landscape of repair paths that literally, like, geometrically deforms the moment you forget something.", "tokens": [51144, 467, 307, 13, 400, 300, 4675, 11, 1968, 13910, 420, 18391, 11, 307, 406, 257, 1152, 3332, 13, 467, 311, 257, 4001, 9661, 295, 10535, 14518, 300, 3736, 11, 411, 11, 12956, 81, 984, 36094, 82, 264, 1623, 291, 2870, 746, 13, 51692], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05607892407311334, "compression_ratio": 1.5850340136054422, "no_speech_prob": 1.5918428684577601e-12}, {"id": 44, "seek": 18112, "start": 181.12, "end": 190.1, "text": " Okay, let's unpack this. Because if computation is no longer the manipulation of symbols in a mutable state, we basically have to rebuild our understanding of logic from the ground up.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 11, 718, 311, 26699, 341, 13, 1436, 498, 24903, 307, 572, 2854, 264, 26475, 295, 16944, 294, 257, 5839, 712, 1785, 11, 321, 1936, 362, 281, 16877, 527, 3701, 295, 9952, 490, 264, 2727, 493, 13, 50814], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 45, "seek": 18112, "start": 190.20000000000002, "end": 190.8, "text": " We really do.", "tokens": [50819, 492, 534, 360, 13, 50849], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 46, "seek": 18112, "start": 191.14000000000001, "end": 196.5, "text": " And Fliction starts by targeting something we all learned in elementary school math, the parenthesis algorithm.", "tokens": [50866, 400, 3235, 4105, 3719, 538, 17918, 746, 321, 439, 3264, 294, 16429, 1395, 5221, 11, 264, 23350, 9374, 9284, 13, 51134], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 47, "seek": 18112, "start": 196.86, "end": 200.12, "text": " Right. The foundational abstraction of all symbolic computations.", "tokens": [51152, 1779, 13, 440, 32195, 37765, 295, 439, 25755, 2807, 763, 13, 51315], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 48, "seek": 18112, "start": 200.74, "end": 204.9, "text": " Yeah. From basic math homework to highly complex compilers.", "tokens": [51346, 865, 13, 3358, 3875, 5221, 14578, 281, 5405, 3997, 715, 388, 433, 13, 51554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 49, "seek": 18112, "start": 205.04000000000002, "end": 208.20000000000002, "text": " Because the parenthesis algorithm is how we define scope and precedence.", "tokens": [51561, 1436, 264, 23350, 9374, 9284, 307, 577, 321, 6964, 11923, 293, 16969, 655, 13, 51719], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 50, "seek": 18112, "start": 208.32, "end": 209.22, "text": " Right. PEMDES.", "tokens": [51725, 1779, 13, 430, 6683, 35, 2358, 13, 51770], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11155887509955735, "compression_ratio": 1.6582278481012658, "no_speech_prob": 1.3724729902922506e-12}, {"id": 51, "seek": 20922, "start": 209.22, "end": 219.38, "text": " Exactly. If you feed an interpreter a nested expression, say, three times, open parenthesis, two plus, open parenthesis, five times four, close, close, minus seven.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 759, 291, 3154, 364, 34132, 257, 15646, 292, 6114, 11, 584, 11, 1045, 1413, 11, 1269, 23350, 9374, 11, 732, 1804, 11, 1269, 23350, 9374, 11, 1732, 1413, 1451, 11, 1998, 11, 1998, 11, 3175, 3407, 13, 50873], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05723102033630875, "compression_ratio": 1.7148014440433212, "no_speech_prob": 1.3778428268121368e-12}, {"id": 52, "seek": 20922, "start": 219.46, "end": 220.88, "text": " That's a mouthful, but yeah.", "tokens": [50877, 663, 311, 257, 4525, 906, 11, 457, 1338, 13, 50948], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05723102033630875, "compression_ratio": 1.7148014440433212, "no_speech_prob": 1.3778428268121368e-12}, {"id": 53, "seek": 20922, "start": 221.07999999999998, "end": 225.24, "text": " The compiler doesn't evaluate that linearly. It doesn't just read left to right.", "tokens": [50958, 440, 31958, 1177, 380, 13059, 300, 43586, 13, 467, 1177, 380, 445, 1401, 1411, 281, 558, 13, 51166], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05723102033630875, "compression_ratio": 1.7148014440433212, "no_speech_prob": 1.3778428268121368e-12}, {"id": 54, "seek": 20922, "start": 225.34, "end": 226.92, "text": " It looks for the deepest layer.", "tokens": [51171, 467, 1542, 337, 264, 28288, 4583, 13, 51250], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05723102033630875, "compression_ratio": 1.7148014440433212, "no_speech_prob": 1.3778428268121368e-12}, {"id": 55, "seek": 20922, "start": 227.16, "end": 236.76, "text": " Right. It locates the innermost bounded space, the five times four, evaluates it to 20, and essentially collapses that local scope, replacing it with the scalar result.", "tokens": [51262, 1779, 13, 467, 1628, 1024, 264, 7714, 966, 555, 37498, 1901, 11, 264, 1732, 1413, 1451, 11, 6133, 1024, 309, 281, 945, 11, 293, 4476, 48765, 300, 2654, 11923, 11, 19139, 309, 365, 264, 39684, 1874, 13, 51742], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.05723102033630875, "compression_ratio": 1.7148014440433212, "no_speech_prob": 1.3778428268121368e-12}, {"id": 56, "seek": 23676, "start": 236.76, "end": 239.26, "text": " It resolves the architecture from the inside out.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 7923, 977, 264, 9482, 490, 264, 1854, 484, 13, 50490], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 57, "seek": 23676, "start": 239.38, "end": 240.28, "text": " Systematically, yes.", "tokens": [50496, 8910, 5030, 11, 2086, 13, 50541], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 58, "seek": 23676, "start": 240.35999999999999, "end": 247.85999999999999, "text": " But Fliction isolates a massive architectural blind spot in how modern execution environments handle this process.", "tokens": [50545, 583, 3235, 4105, 7381, 1024, 257, 5994, 26621, 6865, 4008, 294, 577, 4363, 15058, 12388, 4813, 341, 1399, 13, 50920], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 59, "seek": 23676, "start": 248.17999999999998, "end": 250.98, "text": " It is what he terms the chalkboard mentality.", "tokens": [50936, 467, 307, 437, 415, 2115, 264, 28660, 3787, 21976, 13, 51076], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 60, "seek": 23676, "start": 251.32, "end": 255.16, "text": " The chalkboard mentality. Yeah, that is the defining characteristic of mutable state.", "tokens": [51093, 440, 28660, 3787, 21976, 13, 865, 11, 300, 307, 264, 17827, 16282, 295, 5839, 712, 1785, 13, 51285], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 61, "seek": 23676, "start": 255.32, "end": 257.38, "text": " Because when you do math on a chalkboard.", "tokens": [51293, 1436, 562, 291, 360, 5221, 322, 257, 28660, 3787, 13, 51396], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 62, "seek": 23676, "start": 257.46, "end": 262.62, "text": " Right. When an interpreter resolves that five times four into 20, it discards the operational history.", "tokens": [51400, 1779, 13, 1133, 364, 34132, 7923, 977, 300, 1732, 1413, 1451, 666, 945, 11, 309, 2983, 2287, 264, 16607, 2503, 13, 51658], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13844084739685059, "compression_ratio": 1.6559139784946237, "no_speech_prob": 1.2445944882338855e-12}, {"id": 63, "seek": 26262, "start": 262.62, "end": 264.68, "text": " You erase the intermediate steps.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 23525, 264, 19376, 4439, 13, 50468], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17135916815863717, "compression_ratio": 1.5053191489361701, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758179909205252e-12}, {"id": 64, "seek": 26262, "start": 264.78000000000003, "end": 267.26, "text": " Exactly. It overwrites the memory registers.", "tokens": [50473, 7587, 13, 467, 670, 86, 30931, 264, 4675, 38351, 13, 50597], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17135916815863717, "compression_ratio": 1.5053191489361701, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758179909205252e-12}, {"id": 65, "seek": 26262, "start": 268.04, "end": 270.62, "text": " The system only cares about the transient current state.", "tokens": [50636, 440, 1185, 787, 12310, 466, 264, 41998, 2190, 1785, 13, 50765], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17135916815863717, "compression_ratio": 1.5053191489361701, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758179909205252e-12}, {"id": 66, "seek": 26262, "start": 271.38, "end": 280.26, "text": " The intermediate steps, the specific geometric construction of how that 20 was actually derived, are aggressively zeroed out to free up heap space.", "tokens": [50803, 440, 19376, 4439, 11, 264, 2685, 33246, 6435, 295, 577, 300, 945, 390, 767, 18949, 11, 366, 32024, 4018, 292, 484, 281, 1737, 493, 33591, 1901, 13, 51247], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17135916815863717, "compression_ratio": 1.5053191489361701, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758179909205252e-12}, {"id": 67, "seek": 28026, "start": 280.26, "end": 292.8, "text": " So it's like, if traditional computing is like baking a cake, you put the ingredients in the oven, and the microsecond, the cake is baked, the recipe, the dirty mixing bowls, and the eggshells all just instantaneously vanish from the universe.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 309, 311, 411, 11, 498, 5164, 15866, 307, 411, 12102, 257, 5908, 11, 291, 829, 264, 6952, 294, 264, 9090, 11, 293, 264, 3123, 37841, 18882, 11, 264, 5908, 307, 19453, 11, 264, 6782, 11, 264, 9360, 11983, 28513, 11, 293, 264, 6466, 21288, 82, 439, 445, 9836, 13131, 43584, 490, 264, 6445, 13, 50992], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 68, "seek": 28026, "start": 292.96, "end": 293.65999999999997, "text": " Poof! Gone.", "tokens": [51000, 430, 29496, 0, 39068, 13, 51035], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 69, "seek": 28026, "start": 293.9, "end": 300.53999999999996, "text": " You possess the final output, the cake, but you maintain absolutely zero topological record of the construction process.", "tokens": [51047, 509, 17490, 264, 2572, 5598, 11, 264, 5908, 11, 457, 291, 6909, 3122, 4018, 1192, 4383, 2136, 295, 264, 6435, 1399, 13, 51379], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 70, "seek": 28026, "start": 300.68, "end": 303.15999999999997, "text": " That is the standard execution model, yes.", "tokens": [51386, 663, 307, 264, 3832, 15058, 2316, 11, 2086, 13, 51510], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 71, "seek": 28026, "start": 303.28, "end": 303.42, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51516, 865, 13, 51523], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 72, "seek": 28026, "start": 303.52, "end": 307.7, "text": " And I mean, it works reasonably well for isolated, deterministic, single-threaded scripts.", "tokens": [51528, 400, 286, 914, 11, 309, 1985, 23551, 731, 337, 14621, 11, 15957, 3142, 11, 2167, 12, 392, 2538, 292, 23294, 13, 51737], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 73, "seek": 28026, "start": 307.86, "end": 308.14, "text": " Sure.", "tokens": [51745, 4894, 13, 51759], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0928701198462284, "compression_ratio": 1.6261682242990654, "no_speech_prob": 1.832190215517171e-12}, {"id": 74, "seek": 30814, "start": 308.14, "end": 313.78, "text": " But Fliction argues this deliberate amnesia completely obscures the actual geometry of computation.", "tokens": [50365, 583, 3235, 4105, 38218, 341, 30515, 669, 4081, 654, 2584, 22082, 1303, 264, 3539, 18426, 295, 24903, 13, 50647], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 75, "seek": 30814, "start": 314.91999999999996, "end": 317.91999999999996, "text": " So to fix this, he introduces the sphere-pop calculus.", "tokens": [50704, 407, 281, 3191, 341, 11, 415, 31472, 264, 16687, 12, 13872, 33400, 13, 50854], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 76, "seek": 30814, "start": 318.09999999999997, "end": 318.62, "text": " Sphere-pop?", "tokens": [50863, 318, 6605, 12, 13872, 30, 50889], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 77, "seek": 30814, "start": 318.9, "end": 325.47999999999996, "text": " Right. In sphere-pop, syntax isn't textual punctuation. It is explicit geometry. A parenthesis is modeled as a sphere.", "tokens": [50903, 1779, 13, 682, 16687, 12, 13872, 11, 28431, 1943, 380, 2487, 901, 27006, 16073, 13, 467, 307, 13691, 18426, 13, 316, 23350, 9374, 307, 37140, 382, 257, 16687, 13, 51232], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 78, "seek": 30814, "start": 325.64, "end": 327.12, "text": " Like a literal 3D shape.", "tokens": [51240, 1743, 257, 20411, 805, 35, 3909, 13, 51314], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 79, "seek": 30814, "start": 327.3, "end": 331.12, "text": " Well, topologically, yes. It's a strictly autonomous geometric region.", "tokens": [51323, 1042, 11, 1192, 17157, 11, 2086, 13, 467, 311, 257, 20792, 23797, 33246, 4458, 13, 51514], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13636151870878616, "compression_ratio": 1.5679012345679013, "no_speech_prob": 1.4895717038304612e-12}, {"id": 80, "seek": 33112, "start": 331.12, "end": 338.62, "text": " So when I instantiate a function, and, you know, open a parenthesis, I am spinning up an isolated local universe.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 562, 286, 9836, 13024, 257, 2445, 11, 293, 11, 291, 458, 11, 1269, 257, 23350, 9374, 11, 286, 669, 15640, 493, 364, 14621, 2654, 6445, 13, 50740], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10344308422457787, "compression_ratio": 1.5406504065040652, "no_speech_prob": 1.410525559200626e-12}, {"id": 81, "seek": 33112, "start": 338.82, "end": 345.04, "text": " Precisely. And the variables and operations inside that sphere are completely sealed off from the global scope.", "tokens": [50750, 48746, 736, 13, 400, 264, 9102, 293, 7705, 1854, 300, 16687, 366, 2584, 21514, 766, 490, 264, 4338, 11923, 13, 51061], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10344308422457787, "compression_ratio": 1.5406504065040652, "no_speech_prob": 1.410525559200626e-12}, {"id": 82, "seek": 33112, "start": 345.1, "end": 346.8, "text": " Okay, but then how do you get the answer out?", "tokens": [51064, 1033, 11, 457, 550, 577, 360, 291, 483, 264, 1867, 484, 30, 51149], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10344308422457787, "compression_ratio": 1.5406504065040652, "no_speech_prob": 1.410525559200626e-12}, {"id": 83, "seek": 33112, "start": 347.3, "end": 354.48, "text": " Evaluation is no longer an act of rewriting a memory address. Evaluation is a geometric event called a pop.", "tokens": [51174, 462, 46504, 307, 572, 2854, 364, 605, 295, 319, 19868, 257, 4675, 2985, 13, 462, 46504, 307, 257, 33246, 2280, 1219, 257, 1665, 13, 51533], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10344308422457787, "compression_ratio": 1.5406504065040652, "no_speech_prob": 1.410525559200626e-12}, {"id": 84, "seek": 35448, "start": 354.48, "end": 356.76, "text": " A pop. Like popping a bubble.", "tokens": [50365, 316, 1665, 13, 1743, 18374, 257, 12212, 13, 50479], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10894706772594917, "compression_ratio": 1.5789473684210527, "no_speech_prob": 1.817939245321587e-12}, {"id": 85, "seek": 35448, "start": 356.98, "end": 361.44, "text": " Basically, yeah. A pop is the physical dissolution of that computational boundary.", "tokens": [50490, 8537, 11, 1338, 13, 316, 1665, 307, 264, 4001, 7802, 3386, 295, 300, 28270, 12866, 13, 50713], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10894706772594917, "compression_ratio": 1.5789473684210527, "no_speech_prob": 1.817939245321587e-12}, {"id": 86, "seek": 35448, "start": 362.02000000000004, "end": 370.88, "text": " The sphere pops, the localized boundary vanishes, and the coherent value produced inside is structurally integrated into the surrounding computational graph.", "tokens": [50742, 440, 16687, 16795, 11, 264, 44574, 12866, 3161, 16423, 11, 293, 264, 36239, 2158, 7126, 1854, 307, 6594, 6512, 10919, 666, 264, 11498, 28270, 4295, 13, 51185], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10894706772594917, "compression_ratio": 1.5789473684210527, "no_speech_prob": 1.817939245321587e-12}, {"id": 87, "seek": 35448, "start": 370.98, "end": 373.66, "text": " Okay, wait. I need to push back on the hardware implementation here.", "tokens": [51190, 1033, 11, 1699, 13, 286, 643, 281, 2944, 646, 322, 264, 8837, 11420, 510, 13, 51324], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10894706772594917, "compression_ratio": 1.5789473684210527, "no_speech_prob": 1.817939245321587e-12}, {"id": 88, "seek": 35448, "start": 373.72, "end": 374.38, "text": " I figured you might.", "tokens": [51327, 286, 8932, 291, 1062, 13, 51360], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10894706772594917, "compression_ratio": 1.5789473684210527, "no_speech_prob": 1.817939245321587e-12}, {"id": 89, "seek": 37438, "start": 374.38, "end": 386.62, "text": " Because if evaluation is just a pop that integrates a result into a growing graph, and we literally never overwrite or erase the intermediate steps, you are going to hit a physical hardware wall so fast.", "tokens": [50365, 1436, 498, 13344, 307, 445, 257, 1665, 300, 3572, 1024, 257, 1874, 666, 257, 4194, 4295, 11, 293, 321, 3736, 1128, 670, 21561, 420, 23525, 264, 19376, 4439, 11, 291, 366, 516, 281, 2045, 257, 4001, 8837, 2929, 370, 2370, 13, 50977], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 90, "seek": 37438, "start": 386.8, "end": 387.76, "text": " I mean, RAM is finite.", "tokens": [50986, 286, 914, 11, 14561, 307, 19362, 13, 51034], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 91, "seek": 37438, "start": 388.78, "end": 396.32, "text": " Why on earth would we architect a system that intentionally generates a massive, infinitely growing topological trail of dirty mixing bowls?", "tokens": [51085, 1545, 322, 4120, 576, 321, 6331, 257, 1185, 300, 22062, 23815, 257, 5994, 11, 36227, 4194, 1192, 4383, 9924, 295, 9360, 11983, 28513, 30, 51462], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 92, "seek": 37438, "start": 396.42, "end": 397.7, "text": " It sounds horribly inefficient.", "tokens": [51467, 467, 3263, 45028, 43495, 13, 51531], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 93, "seek": 37438, "start": 397.86, "end": 398.04, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [51539, 865, 13, 51548], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 94, "seek": 37438, "start": 398.12, "end": 399.78, "text": " It sounds impossible.", "tokens": [51552, 467, 3263, 6243, 13, 51635], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13326318485220684, "compression_ratio": 1.5932835820895523, "no_speech_prob": 1.8179316559063796e-12}, {"id": 95, "seek": 39978, "start": 399.78, "end": 405.59999999999997, "text": " How does Spearpop handle garbage collection without violating this core principle of immutable history?", "tokens": [50365, 1012, 775, 3550, 289, 13872, 4813, 14150, 5765, 1553, 42201, 341, 4965, 8665, 295, 3397, 32148, 2503, 30, 50656], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 96, "seek": 39978, "start": 406.02, "end": 407.84, "text": " Well, that is the immediate engineering hurdle.", "tokens": [50677, 1042, 11, 300, 307, 264, 11629, 7043, 47423, 13, 50768], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 97, "seek": 39978, "start": 407.97999999999996, "end": 408.15999999999997, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50775, 865, 13, 50784], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 98, "seek": 39978, "start": 408.32, "end": 411.91999999999996, "text": " But you have to look at why Fliction's retaining the history in the first place.", "tokens": [50792, 583, 291, 362, 281, 574, 412, 983, 3235, 4105, 311, 34936, 264, 2503, 294, 264, 700, 1081, 13, 50972], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 99, "seek": 39978, "start": 412.02, "end": 412.65999999999997, "text": " Okay. Why?", "tokens": [50977, 1033, 13, 1545, 30, 51009], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 100, "seek": 39978, "start": 412.85999999999996, "end": 418.15999999999997, "text": " It is entirely about algorithmic provenance in non-deterministic environments.", "tokens": [51019, 467, 307, 7696, 466, 9284, 299, 12785, 719, 294, 2107, 12, 49136, 259, 3142, 12388, 13, 51284], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 101, "seek": 39978, "start": 418.79999999999995, "end": 421.17999999999995, "text": " Provenance? Like the origin story of the data?", "tokens": [51316, 1705, 553, 719, 30, 1743, 264, 4957, 1657, 295, 264, 1412, 30, 51435], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 102, "seek": 39978, "start": 421.4, "end": 421.91999999999996, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51446, 7587, 13, 51472], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 103, "seek": 39978, "start": 422.76, "end": 425.71999999999997, "text": " We don't live in a single-threaded deterministic world anymore.", "tokens": [51514, 492, 500, 380, 1621, 294, 257, 2167, 12, 392, 2538, 292, 15957, 3142, 1002, 3602, 13, 51662], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.161461430737096, "compression_ratio": 1.5664335664335665, "no_speech_prob": 1.4439633299820342e-12}, {"id": 104, "seek": 42572, "start": 425.72, "end": 430.02000000000004, "text": " Our runtimes are highly concurrent, distributed, and probabilistic.", "tokens": [50365, 2621, 49435, 1532, 366, 5405, 37702, 11, 12631, 11, 293, 31959, 3142, 13, 50580], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 105, "seek": 42572, "start": 430.14000000000004, "end": 432.42, "text": " Right. We have machine learning, distributed nodes.", "tokens": [50586, 1779, 13, 492, 362, 3479, 2539, 11, 12631, 13891, 13, 50700], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 106, "seek": 42572, "start": 432.48, "end": 436.8, "text": " Exactly. So imagine node A and node B both output the integer five.", "tokens": [50703, 7587, 13, 407, 3811, 9984, 316, 293, 9984, 363, 1293, 5598, 264, 24922, 1732, 13, 50919], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 107, "seek": 42572, "start": 436.90000000000003, "end": 437.12, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50924, 1033, 13, 50935], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 108, "seek": 42572, "start": 437.32000000000005, "end": 444.38000000000005, "text": " But node A derived it from a strict cryptographic hash, and node B derived it from a low-confidence stochastic model.", "tokens": [50945, 583, 9984, 316, 18949, 309, 490, 257, 10910, 9844, 12295, 22019, 11, 293, 9984, 363, 18949, 309, 490, 257, 2295, 12, 47273, 342, 8997, 2750, 2316, 13, 51298], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 109, "seek": 42572, "start": 444.5, "end": 450.58000000000004, "text": " Oh, I see. A traditional mutable state system treats both of those fives as just identical integers.", "tokens": [51304, 876, 11, 286, 536, 13, 316, 5164, 5839, 712, 1785, 1185, 19566, 1293, 295, 729, 283, 1539, 382, 445, 14800, 41674, 13, 51608], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 110, "seek": 42572, "start": 450.86, "end": 452.1, "text": " Right. It strips the context.", "tokens": [51622, 1779, 13, 467, 19842, 264, 4319, 13, 51684], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 111, "seek": 42572, "start": 452.16, "end": 453.56, "text": " That strips the provenance completely.", "tokens": [51687, 663, 19842, 264, 12785, 719, 2584, 13, 51757], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11617400429465553, "compression_ratio": 1.693661971830986, "no_speech_prob": 1.5071323095777744e-12}, {"id": 112, "seek": 45356, "start": 453.56, "end": 462.98, "text": " Exactly. But in SpherePop, the history is the primary semantic object. You cannot separate a value from its geometric derivation.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 583, 294, 318, 6605, 38677, 11, 264, 2503, 307, 264, 6194, 47982, 2657, 13, 509, 2644, 4994, 257, 2158, 490, 1080, 33246, 10151, 399, 13, 50836], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1097832251032558, "compression_ratio": 1.65993265993266, "no_speech_prob": 1.775826664537905e-12}, {"id": 113, "seek": 45356, "start": 463.56, "end": 469.92, "text": " The five from node A and the five from node B are entirely different geometric entities because their histories are different.", "tokens": [50865, 440, 1732, 490, 9984, 316, 293, 264, 1732, 490, 9984, 363, 366, 7696, 819, 33246, 16667, 570, 641, 30631, 366, 819, 13, 51183], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1097832251032558, "compression_ratio": 1.65993265993266, "no_speech_prob": 1.775826664537905e-12}, {"id": 114, "seek": 45356, "start": 470.04, "end": 474.32, "text": " Okay. That makes sense for data integrity. But what about the hardware limit? The RAM issue?", "tokens": [51189, 1033, 13, 663, 1669, 2020, 337, 1412, 16000, 13, 583, 437, 466, 264, 8837, 4948, 30, 440, 14561, 2734, 30, 51403], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1097832251032558, "compression_ratio": 1.65993265993266, "no_speech_prob": 1.775826664537905e-12}, {"id": 115, "seek": 45356, "start": 474.52, "end": 482.72, "text": " Right. So garbage collection in SpherePop isn't achieved by overriding active state. It is achieved by establishing irrestorability boundaries.", "tokens": [51413, 1779, 13, 407, 14150, 5765, 294, 318, 6605, 38677, 1943, 380, 11042, 538, 670, 81, 2819, 4967, 1785, 13, 467, 307, 11042, 538, 22494, 3418, 4149, 284, 2310, 13180, 13, 51823], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1097832251032558, "compression_ratio": 1.65993265993266, "no_speech_prob": 1.775826664537905e-12}, {"id": 116, "seek": 48272, "start": 482.72, "end": 484.72, "text": " Irrestorability boundaries.", "tokens": [50365, 9151, 4149, 284, 2310, 13180, 13, 50465], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10598898469732049, "compression_ratio": 1.5481171548117154, "no_speech_prob": 2.1160375968803935e-12}, {"id": 117, "seek": 48272, "start": 484.90000000000003, "end": 491.46000000000004, "text": " Yes. The runtime identifies subgraphs that can no longer topologically influence the active wavefront of computation.", "tokens": [50474, 1079, 13, 440, 34474, 34597, 1422, 34091, 82, 300, 393, 572, 2854, 1192, 17157, 6503, 264, 4967, 5772, 11496, 295, 24903, 13, 50802], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10598898469732049, "compression_ratio": 1.5481171548117154, "no_speech_prob": 2.1160375968803935e-12}, {"id": 118, "seek": 48272, "start": 491.70000000000005, "end": 494.98, "text": " So parts of the math that literally can't affect the final answer anymore.", "tokens": [50814, 407, 3166, 295, 264, 5221, 300, 3736, 393, 380, 3345, 264, 2572, 1867, 3602, 13, 50978], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10598898469732049, "compression_ratio": 1.5481171548117154, "no_speech_prob": 2.1160375968803935e-12}, {"id": 119, "seek": 48272, "start": 495.1, "end": 503.76000000000005, "text": " Exactly. And it allows them to drop out of the admissibility manifold. It isn't deleting a file. It is along a causal chain to functionally decohere.", "tokens": [50984, 7587, 13, 400, 309, 4045, 552, 281, 3270, 484, 295, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 47138, 13, 467, 1943, 380, 48946, 257, 3991, 13, 467, 307, 2051, 257, 38755, 5021, 281, 2445, 379, 979, 1445, 323, 13, 51417], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10598898469732049, "compression_ratio": 1.5481171548117154, "no_speech_prob": 2.1160375968803935e-12}, {"id": 120, "seek": 50376, "start": 503.76, "end": 510.84, "text": " Okay. So we are trading mutable state for an irreversible geometric history that provides absolute operational provenance.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 13, 407, 321, 366, 9529, 5839, 712, 1785, 337, 364, 16014, 840, 964, 33246, 2503, 300, 6417, 8236, 16607, 12785, 719, 13, 50719], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11259856678190686, "compression_ratio": 1.5661157024793388, "no_speech_prob": 1.616127045557525e-12}, {"id": 121, "seek": 50376, "start": 511.03999999999996, "end": 516.9, "text": " But if we can't aggressively overwrite memory registers, how do we handle variable assignment?", "tokens": [50729, 583, 498, 321, 393, 380, 32024, 670, 21561, 4675, 38351, 11, 577, 360, 321, 4813, 7006, 15187, 30, 51022], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11259856678190686, "compression_ratio": 1.5661157024793388, "no_speech_prob": 1.616127045557525e-12}, {"id": 122, "seek": 50376, "start": 517.4, "end": 520.96, "text": " Because, I mean, the bedrock of traditional programming is substitution.", "tokens": [51047, 1436, 11, 286, 914, 11, 264, 2901, 17799, 295, 5164, 9410, 307, 35827, 13, 51225], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11259856678190686, "compression_ratio": 1.5661157024793388, "no_speech_prob": 1.616127045557525e-12}, {"id": 123, "seek": 50376, "start": 521.52, "end": 526.8199999999999, "text": " I assign a value to X and the compiler just substitutes that value wherever X is called.", "tokens": [51253, 286, 6269, 257, 2158, 281, 1783, 293, 264, 31958, 445, 26441, 1819, 300, 2158, 8660, 1783, 307, 1219, 13, 51518], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11259856678190686, "compression_ratio": 1.5661157024793388, "no_speech_prob": 1.616127045557525e-12}, {"id": 124, "seek": 52682, "start": 526.82, "end": 529.96, "text": " Well, substitution is fundamentally incompatible with SpherePop.", "tokens": [50365, 1042, 11, 35827, 307, 17879, 40393, 267, 964, 365, 318, 6605, 38677, 13, 50522], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 125, "seek": 52682, "start": 530.5, "end": 533.9200000000001, "text": " Because substitution implies copying a transient state.", "tokens": [50549, 1436, 35827, 18779, 27976, 257, 41998, 1785, 13, 50720], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 126, "seek": 52682, "start": 534.1, "end": 538.36, "text": " Right. You can't just copy-paste a state if the state doesn't exist independently of its history.", "tokens": [50729, 1779, 13, 509, 393, 380, 445, 5055, 12, 79, 9079, 257, 1785, 498, 264, 1785, 1177, 380, 2514, 21761, 295, 1080, 2503, 13, 50942], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 127, "seek": 52682, "start": 538.94, "end": 541.84, "text": " So fliction replaces substitution with replay.", "tokens": [50971, 407, 932, 4105, 46734, 35827, 365, 23836, 13, 51116], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 128, "seek": 52682, "start": 542.08, "end": 544.08, "text": " Replay. Let's get into the mechanics of replay.", "tokens": [51128, 1300, 2858, 13, 961, 311, 483, 666, 264, 12939, 295, 23836, 13, 51228], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 129, "seek": 52682, "start": 544.44, "end": 550.4200000000001, "text": " How does it differ from, say, a standard beta reduction in lambda calculus?", "tokens": [51246, 1012, 775, 309, 743, 490, 11, 584, 11, 257, 3832, 9861, 11004, 294, 13607, 33400, 30, 51545], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1180302640225025, "compression_ratio": 1.58130081300813, "no_speech_prob": 1.5732998671219578e-12}, {"id": 130, "seek": 55042, "start": 550.42, "end": 556.8399999999999, "text": " Okay. So in lambda calculus, beta reduction literally replaces the bound variables with the argument.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 13, 407, 294, 13607, 33400, 11, 9861, 11004, 3736, 46734, 264, 5472, 9102, 365, 264, 6770, 13, 50686], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 131, "seek": 55042, "start": 557.14, "end": 557.8199999999999, "text": " It rewrites it.", "tokens": [50701, 467, 319, 86, 30931, 309, 13, 50735], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 132, "seek": 55042, "start": 557.88, "end": 561.24, "text": " Yes. It modifies the expression. Replay doesn't modify anything.", "tokens": [50738, 1079, 13, 467, 1072, 11221, 264, 6114, 13, 1300, 2858, 1177, 380, 16927, 1340, 13, 50906], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 133, "seek": 55042, "start": 561.8399999999999, "end": 566.42, "text": " Because the identity of an object in SpherePop is its value plus its specific historical derivation.", "tokens": [50936, 1436, 264, 6575, 295, 364, 2657, 294, 318, 6605, 38677, 307, 1080, 2158, 1804, 1080, 2685, 8584, 10151, 399, 13, 51165], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 134, "seek": 55042, "start": 567.12, "end": 568.4399999999999, "text": " So they are tied together forever.", "tokens": [51200, 407, 436, 366, 9601, 1214, 5680, 13, 51266], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 135, "seek": 55042, "start": 568.64, "end": 576.56, "text": " Exactly. When a function requires an argument, the runtime physically replays the historical sequence of computational events that produce that value.", "tokens": [51276, 7587, 13, 1133, 257, 2445, 7029, 364, 6770, 11, 264, 34474, 9762, 23836, 82, 264, 8584, 8310, 295, 28270, 3931, 300, 5258, 300, 2158, 13, 51672], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 136, "seek": 55042, "start": 576.5999999999999, "end": 577.8, "text": " Yeah. It reruns the history.", "tokens": [51674, 865, 13, 467, 43819, 26684, 264, 2503, 13, 51734], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10800818567690643, "compression_ratio": 1.66, "no_speech_prob": 1.832633437365283e-12}, {"id": 137, "seek": 57780, "start": 577.8, "end": 581.0, "text": " It reconstructs the admissible historical context.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 31499, 82, 264, 5910, 41073, 8584, 4319, 13, 50525], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1851419246557987, "compression_ratio": 1.4642857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.591846771585581e-12}, {"id": 138, "seek": 57780, "start": 581.18, "end": 581.3199999999999, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50534, 865, 13, 50541], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1851419246557987, "compression_ratio": 1.4642857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.591846771585581e-12}, {"id": 139, "seek": 57780, "start": 581.64, "end": 587.18, "text": " You are dragging the entire causal provenance forward into the new evaluation.", "tokens": [50557, 509, 366, 24385, 264, 2302, 38755, 12785, 719, 2128, 666, 264, 777, 13344, 13, 50834], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1851419246557987, "compression_ratio": 1.4642857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.591846771585581e-12}, {"id": 140, "seek": 57780, "start": 587.5, "end": 593.8399999999999, "text": " That is wild. But that significantly alters how we handle invalid operations or runtime errors, doesn't it?", "tokens": [50850, 663, 307, 4868, 13, 583, 300, 10591, 419, 1559, 577, 321, 4813, 34702, 7705, 420, 34474, 13603, 11, 1177, 380, 309, 30, 51167], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1851419246557987, "compression_ratio": 1.4642857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.591846771585581e-12}, {"id": 141, "seek": 57780, "start": 594.0999999999999, "end": 595.8599999999999, "text": " It changes everything about error handling.", "tokens": [51180, 467, 2962, 1203, 466, 6713, 13175, 13, 51268], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1851419246557987, "compression_ratio": 1.4642857142857142, "no_speech_prob": 1.591846771585581e-12}, {"id": 142, "seek": 59586, "start": 595.86, "end": 615.64, "text": " Because in standard architectures, if a script attempts an invalid operation, like a null pointer to reference or, I don't know, dividing by zero, the runtime attempts the execution, throws an exception, and then initiates a highly expensive stack unwinding process to panic and crash.", "tokens": [50365, 1436, 294, 3832, 6331, 1303, 11, 498, 257, 5755, 15257, 364, 34702, 6916, 11, 411, 257, 18184, 23918, 281, 6408, 420, 11, 286, 500, 380, 458, 11, 26764, 538, 4018, 11, 264, 34474, 15257, 264, 15058, 11, 19251, 364, 11183, 11, 293, 550, 6265, 1024, 257, 5405, 5124, 8630, 14853, 9245, 1399, 281, 14783, 293, 8252, 13, 51354], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.042647452581496464, "compression_ratio": 1.6693877551020408, "no_speech_prob": 1.7144813129962855e-12}, {"id": 143, "seek": 59586, "start": 615.78, "end": 622.24, "text": " Right. Because traditional architectures permit the system to enter an invalid state before realizing the state is invalid.", "tokens": [51361, 1779, 13, 1436, 5164, 6331, 1303, 13423, 264, 1185, 281, 3242, 364, 34702, 1785, 949, 16734, 264, 1785, 307, 34702, 13, 51684], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.042647452581496464, "compression_ratio": 1.6693877551020408, "no_speech_prob": 1.7144813129962855e-12}, {"id": 144, "seek": 62224, "start": 622.24, "end": 625.0600000000001, "text": " You don't know it's a mistake until you've already written it on the talk board.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 500, 380, 458, 309, 311, 257, 6146, 1826, 291, 600, 1217, 3720, 309, 322, 264, 751, 3150, 13, 50506], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10156790776686235, "compression_ratio": 1.4834710743801653, "no_speech_prob": 1.675018522322158e-12}, {"id": 145, "seek": 62224, "start": 625.1, "end": 629.38, "text": " Exactly. SpherePop circumvents it entirely through a mechanism called refusal.", "tokens": [50508, 7587, 13, 318, 6605, 38677, 7125, 85, 791, 309, 7696, 807, 257, 7513, 1219, 48948, 13, 50722], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10156790776686235, "compression_ratio": 1.4834710743801653, "no_speech_prob": 1.675018522322158e-12}, {"id": 146, "seek": 62224, "start": 629.74, "end": 632.3, "text": " Refusal. So it evaluates admissibility before extension?", "tokens": [50740, 16957, 11765, 13, 407, 309, 6133, 1024, 5910, 891, 2841, 949, 10320, 30, 50868], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10156790776686235, "compression_ratio": 1.4834710743801653, "no_speech_prob": 1.675018522322158e-12}, {"id": 147, "seek": 62224, "start": 632.58, "end": 641.42, "text": " Yes. Because history is immutable and cannot be overwritten, you simply cannot allow an incoherent operation to attach to the geometric graph.", "tokens": [50882, 1079, 13, 1436, 2503, 307, 3397, 32148, 293, 2644, 312, 670, 26859, 11, 291, 2935, 2644, 2089, 364, 834, 78, 511, 317, 6916, 281, 5085, 281, 264, 33246, 4295, 13, 51324], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10156790776686235, "compression_ratio": 1.4834710743801653, "no_speech_prob": 1.675018522322158e-12}, {"id": 148, "seek": 64142, "start": 641.42, "end": 644.18, "text": " It's like blocking a bad Lego brick from snapping on.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 311, 411, 17776, 257, 1578, 28761, 16725, 490, 42727, 322, 13, 50503], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11660418667636074, "compression_ratio": 1.5378787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758287245220328e-12}, {"id": 149, "seek": 64142, "start": 644.18, "end": 656.86, "text": " Exactly. The runtime evaluates the topological admissibility of a continuation. If a sphere attempts a geometrically invalid operation, the extension is simply refused.", "tokens": [50503, 7587, 13, 440, 34474, 6133, 1024, 264, 1192, 4383, 5910, 891, 2841, 295, 257, 29357, 13, 759, 257, 16687, 15257, 257, 12956, 81, 984, 34702, 6916, 11, 264, 10320, 307, 2935, 14654, 13, 51137], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11660418667636074, "compression_ratio": 1.5378787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758287245220328e-12}, {"id": 150, "seek": 64142, "start": 657.3199999999999, "end": 659.4599999999999, "text": " It never becomes part of the historical record.", "tokens": [51160, 467, 1128, 3643, 644, 295, 264, 8584, 2136, 13, 51267], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11660418667636074, "compression_ratio": 1.5378787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758287245220328e-12}, {"id": 151, "seek": 64142, "start": 659.5799999999999, "end": 659.88, "text": " Never.", "tokens": [51273, 7344, 13, 51288], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11660418667636074, "compression_ratio": 1.5378787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758287245220328e-12}, {"id": 152, "seek": 64142, "start": 660.16, "end": 668.98, "text": " The core graph remains completely pristine without the system ever having to dedicate CPU cycles to unwinding a corrupted stack.", "tokens": [51302, 440, 4965, 4295, 7023, 2584, 582, 42745, 1553, 264, 1185, 1562, 1419, 281, 30718, 13199, 17796, 281, 14853, 9245, 257, 39480, 8630, 13, 51743], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11660418667636074, "compression_ratio": 1.5378787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7758287245220328e-12}, {"id": 153, "seek": 66898, "start": 668.98, "end": 675.34, "text": " If we connect this to the bigger picture, the elegance of refusal is most apparent when we look at concurrency.", "tokens": [50365, 759, 321, 1745, 341, 281, 264, 3801, 3036, 11, 264, 14459, 719, 295, 48948, 307, 881, 18335, 562, 321, 574, 412, 23702, 10457, 13, 50683], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 154, "seek": 66898, "start": 675.6, "end": 682.0600000000001, "text": " Oh, this is the part that blew my mind. Because how does traditional software handle multiple threads operating simultaneously?", "tokens": [50696, 876, 11, 341, 307, 264, 644, 300, 19075, 452, 1575, 13, 1436, 577, 775, 5164, 4722, 4813, 3866, 19314, 7447, 16561, 30, 51019], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 155, "seek": 66898, "start": 682.3000000000001, "end": 684.0, "text": " With massive engineering headaches.", "tokens": [51031, 2022, 5994, 7043, 35046, 13, 51116], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 156, "seek": 66898, "start": 684.14, "end": 689.7, "text": " Yeah. You have to write explicit threadlocks, mutexes, and semaphores just to prevent race conditions.", "tokens": [51123, 865, 13, 509, 362, 281, 2464, 13691, 7207, 34896, 11, 24523, 47047, 11, 293, 4361, 13957, 2706, 445, 281, 4871, 4569, 4487, 13, 51401], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 157, "seek": 66898, "start": 689.8000000000001, "end": 693.94, "text": " Right. Ensuring two threads don't try to overwrite the same memory address at the exact same time.", "tokens": [51406, 1779, 13, 25979, 1345, 732, 19314, 500, 380, 853, 281, 670, 21561, 264, 912, 4675, 2985, 412, 264, 1900, 912, 565, 13, 51613], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 158, "seek": 66898, "start": 694.12, "end": 697.72, "text": " But all of those workarounds are just symptoms of the mutable state problem, aren't they?", "tokens": [51622, 583, 439, 295, 729, 589, 289, 4432, 366, 445, 8332, 295, 264, 5839, 712, 1785, 1154, 11, 3212, 380, 436, 30, 51802], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06559312980593617, "compression_ratio": 1.6153846153846154, "no_speech_prob": 1.8393596108029486e-12}, {"id": 159, "seek": 69772, "start": 697.72, "end": 700.58, "text": " Exactly. And fliction solves this with the merge operator.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 400, 932, 4105, 39890, 341, 365, 264, 22183, 12973, 13, 50508], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09388039588928222, "compression_ratio": 1.6747967479674797, "no_speech_prob": 1.6426251634935052e-12}, {"id": 160, "seek": 69772, "start": 701.44, "end": 708.1800000000001, "text": " So think about a directed acyclic graph representing our earlier math equation, but let's restructure it slightly.", "tokens": [50551, 407, 519, 466, 257, 12898, 696, 88, 66, 1050, 4295, 13460, 527, 3071, 5221, 5367, 11, 457, 718, 311, 1472, 2885, 309, 4748, 13, 50888], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09388039588928222, "compression_ratio": 1.6747967479674797, "no_speech_prob": 1.6426251634935052e-12}, {"id": 161, "seek": 69772, "start": 708.9, "end": 716.58, "text": " Imagine it's open parenthesis, 2 plus 3, close parenthesis, multiplied by open parenthesis, 4 plus 5, close parenthesis.", "tokens": [50924, 11739, 309, 311, 1269, 23350, 9374, 11, 568, 1804, 805, 11, 1998, 23350, 9374, 11, 17207, 538, 1269, 23350, 9374, 11, 1017, 1804, 1025, 11, 1998, 23350, 9374, 13, 51308], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09388039588928222, "compression_ratio": 1.6747967479674797, "no_speech_prob": 1.6426251634935052e-12}, {"id": 162, "seek": 69772, "start": 716.72, "end": 723.6, "text": " Okay. So we have a parent multiplication sphere containing two distinct child spheres, the 2 plus 3 and the 4 plus 5.", "tokens": [51315, 1033, 13, 407, 321, 362, 257, 2596, 27290, 16687, 19273, 732, 10644, 1440, 41225, 11, 264, 568, 1804, 805, 293, 264, 1017, 1804, 1025, 13, 51659], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09388039588928222, "compression_ratio": 1.6747967479674797, "no_speech_prob": 1.6426251634935052e-12}, {"id": 163, "seek": 72360, "start": 723.6, "end": 733.58, "text": " Right. Now textually, an interpreter might parse that sequentially left to right, but geometrically, those two child spheres share zero dependencies.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 823, 2487, 671, 11, 364, 34132, 1062, 48377, 300, 5123, 3137, 1411, 281, 558, 11, 457, 12956, 81, 984, 11, 729, 732, 1440, 41225, 2073, 4018, 36606, 13, 50864], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08448407470539052, "compression_ratio": 1.64453125, "no_speech_prob": 1.6555165441647923e-12}, {"id": 164, "seek": 72360, "start": 733.88, "end": 740.22, "text": " Right. The addition of 4 and 5 does not require any input from the addition of 2 and 3. They are totally separate operations.", "tokens": [50879, 1779, 13, 440, 4500, 295, 1017, 293, 1025, 775, 406, 3651, 604, 4846, 490, 264, 4500, 295, 568, 293, 805, 13, 814, 366, 3879, 4994, 7705, 13, 51196], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08448407470539052, "compression_ratio": 1.64453125, "no_speech_prob": 1.6555165441647923e-12}, {"id": 165, "seek": 72360, "start": 740.6, "end": 748.82, "text": " Therefore, in sphere pop, concurrency is not a feature you have to explicitly code. It is the natural geometric default of independent histories.", "tokens": [51215, 7504, 11, 294, 16687, 1665, 11, 23702, 10457, 307, 406, 257, 4111, 291, 362, 281, 20803, 3089, 13, 467, 307, 264, 3303, 33246, 7576, 295, 6695, 30631, 13, 51626], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08448407470539052, "compression_ratio": 1.64453125, "no_speech_prob": 1.6555165441647923e-12}, {"id": 166, "seek": 74882, "start": 748.82, "end": 751.4000000000001, "text": " Because they share no edges in the dependency graph, right?", "tokens": [50365, 1436, 436, 2073, 572, 8819, 294, 264, 33621, 4295, 11, 558, 30, 50494], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08196873542590019, "compression_ratio": 1.5217391304347827, "no_speech_prob": 2.175302689713665e-12}, {"id": 167, "seek": 74882, "start": 751.4000000000001, "end": 758.98, "text": " Exactly. Those spheres pop simultaneously. The merge operator simply allows topologically independent histories to evolve in parallel.", "tokens": [50494, 7587, 13, 3950, 41225, 1665, 16561, 13, 440, 22183, 12973, 2935, 4045, 1192, 17157, 6695, 30631, 281, 16693, 294, 8952, 13, 50873], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08196873542590019, "compression_ratio": 1.5217391304347827, "no_speech_prob": 2.175302689713665e-12}, {"id": 168, "seek": 74882, "start": 759.22, "end": 761.9200000000001, "text": " No mutex is required because nothing is being overwritten.", "tokens": [50885, 883, 24523, 87, 307, 4739, 570, 1825, 307, 885, 670, 26859, 13, 51020], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08196873542590019, "compression_ratio": 1.5217391304347827, "no_speech_prob": 2.175302689713665e-12}, {"id": 169, "seek": 74882, "start": 762.22, "end": 767.08, "text": " I was thinking about this, and it is so much like real life. It's like cooking a complex dinner.", "tokens": [51035, 286, 390, 1953, 466, 341, 11, 293, 309, 307, 370, 709, 411, 957, 993, 13, 467, 311, 411, 6361, 257, 3997, 6148, 13, 51278], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08196873542590019, "compression_ratio": 1.5217391304347827, "no_speech_prob": 2.175302689713665e-12}, {"id": 170, "seek": 76708, "start": 767.08, "end": 784.72, "text": " Well, you are reducing a sauce on the stove while your partner is setting the table. You aren't executing a single threaded synchronous loop where you stir the sauce once, pause, walk over and place one fork, pause, walk back and stir the sauce again.", "tokens": [50365, 1042, 11, 291, 366, 12245, 257, 4880, 322, 264, 19263, 1339, 428, 4975, 307, 3287, 264, 3199, 13, 509, 3212, 380, 32368, 257, 2167, 47493, 44743, 6367, 689, 291, 8946, 264, 4880, 1564, 11, 10465, 11, 1792, 670, 293, 1081, 472, 17716, 11, 10465, 11, 1792, 646, 293, 8946, 264, 4880, 797, 13, 51247], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08406245347225305, "compression_ratio": 1.5909090909090908, "no_speech_prob": 2.4083630055515837e-12}, {"id": 171, "seek": 76708, "start": 784.84, "end": 785.96, "text": " Right. That would be insane.", "tokens": [51253, 1779, 13, 663, 576, 312, 10838, 13, 51309], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08406245347225305, "compression_ratio": 1.5909090909090908, "no_speech_prob": 2.4083630055515837e-12}, {"id": 172, "seek": 78596, "start": 785.96, "end": 799.4200000000001, "text": " You are executing a merge of independent causal histories. You are operating concurrently, and you only topologically combine those histories when the components are merged together at the end when dinner is served.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 366, 32368, 257, 22183, 295, 6695, 38755, 30631, 13, 509, 366, 7447, 37702, 356, 11, 293, 291, 787, 1192, 17157, 10432, 729, 30631, 562, 264, 6677, 366, 36427, 1214, 412, 264, 917, 562, 6148, 307, 7584, 13, 51038], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06756345687373992, "compression_ratio": 1.5678391959798994, "no_speech_prob": 1.6945030448245468e-12}, {"id": 173, "seek": 78596, "start": 799.6800000000001, "end": 804.5400000000001, "text": " That is an excellent way to visualize it. The geometry inherently dictates the execution timing.", "tokens": [51051, 663, 307, 364, 7103, 636, 281, 23273, 309, 13, 440, 18426, 27993, 12569, 1024, 264, 15058, 10822, 13, 51294], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.06756345687373992, "compression_ratio": 1.5678391959798994, "no_speech_prob": 1.6945030448245468e-12}, {"id": 174, "seek": 80454, "start": 804.54, "end": 816.7199999999999, "text": " Okay, here's where it gets really interesting. We have this continuously expanding concurrent graph of popping spheres. We have replay dragging provenance forward and refusal maintaining structural integrity.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 11, 510, 311, 689, 309, 2170, 534, 1880, 13, 492, 362, 341, 15684, 14702, 37702, 4295, 295, 18374, 41225, 13, 492, 362, 23836, 24385, 12785, 719, 2128, 293, 48948, 14916, 15067, 16000, 13, 50974], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09398903733208067, "compression_ratio": 1.5833333333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.5368492069234296e-12}, {"id": 175, "seek": 80454, "start": 817.04, "end": 817.12, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50990, 1779, 13, 50994], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09398903733208067, "compression_ratio": 1.5833333333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.5368492069234296e-12}, {"id": 176, "seek": 80454, "start": 817.14, "end": 827.16, "text": " What is actually deciding the logic of those pops? Because in standard computing, if I am compiling, say, C++A, the execution engine and the logic of the language are tightly coupled.", "tokens": [50995, 708, 307, 767, 17990, 264, 9952, 295, 729, 16795, 30, 1436, 294, 3832, 15866, 11, 498, 286, 669, 715, 4883, 11, 584, 11, 383, 25472, 32, 11, 264, 15058, 2848, 293, 264, 9952, 295, 264, 2856, 366, 21952, 29482, 13, 51496], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09398903733208067, "compression_ratio": 1.5833333333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.5368492069234296e-12}, {"id": 177, "seek": 82716, "start": 827.16, "end": 834.28, "text": " They are completely inseparable. The engine that moves the bits through the registers inherently knows what the bits represent.", "tokens": [50365, 814, 366, 2584, 33874, 42012, 13, 440, 2848, 300, 6067, 264, 9239, 807, 264, 38351, 27993, 3255, 437, 264, 9239, 2906, 13, 50721], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0801822026570638, "compression_ratio": 1.7508650519031141, "no_speech_prob": 1.5251257288323439e-12}, {"id": 178, "seek": 82716, "start": 834.56, "end": 843.38, "text": " But Flixion introduces something called the universal operator machine, the UOM, and this completely decouples the geometric graph from the logical execution.", "tokens": [50735, 583, 3235, 970, 313, 31472, 746, 1219, 264, 11455, 12973, 3479, 11, 264, 624, 5251, 11, 293, 341, 2584, 979, 263, 2622, 264, 33246, 4295, 490, 264, 14978, 15058, 13, 51176], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0801822026570638, "compression_ratio": 1.7508650519031141, "no_speech_prob": 1.5251257288323439e-12}, {"id": 179, "seek": 82716, "start": 843.92, "end": 854.5, "text": " Yes. The UOM is arguably the most significant architectural breakthrough in the first text. Flixion separates the execution engine from the operator logic entirely.", "tokens": [51203, 1079, 13, 440, 624, 5251, 307, 26771, 264, 881, 4776, 26621, 22397, 294, 264, 700, 2487, 13, 3235, 970, 313, 34149, 264, 15058, 2848, 490, 264, 12973, 9952, 7696, 13, 51732], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0801822026570638, "compression_ratio": 1.7508650519031141, "no_speech_prob": 1.5251257288323439e-12}, {"id": 180, "seek": 82716, "start": 854.74, "end": 856.62, "text": " Wait, how does an engine not know what it's executing?", "tokens": [51744, 3802, 11, 577, 775, 364, 2848, 406, 458, 437, 309, 311, 32368, 30, 51838], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0801822026570638, "compression_ratio": 1.7508650519031141, "no_speech_prob": 1.5251257288323439e-12}, {"id": 181, "seek": 85662, "start": 856.62, "end": 872.7, "text": " The UOM only knows how to navigate the geometry of the graph. That's it. It looks for spheres with resolved dependencies, pops them, extends the history, and routes the output. It is completely blind to the actual mathematical or logical meaning of the operations it is performing.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 624, 5251, 787, 3255, 577, 281, 12350, 264, 18426, 295, 264, 4295, 13, 663, 311, 309, 13, 467, 1542, 337, 41225, 365, 20772, 36606, 11, 16795, 552, 11, 26448, 264, 2503, 11, 293, 18242, 264, 5598, 13, 467, 307, 2584, 6865, 281, 264, 3539, 18894, 420, 14978, 3620, 295, 264, 7705, 309, 307, 10205, 13, 51169], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.04068371813784363, "compression_ratio": 1.678714859437751, "no_speech_prob": 1.5614781603140448e-12}, {"id": 182, "seek": 85662, "start": 872.94, "end": 880.82, "text": " Let me try an analogy here. It is like a train track system. The dependency graph of the spheres, the history, is the network of tracks.", "tokens": [51181, 961, 385, 853, 364, 21663, 510, 13, 467, 307, 411, 257, 3847, 2837, 1185, 13, 440, 33621, 4295, 295, 264, 41225, 11, 264, 2503, 11, 307, 264, 3209, 295, 10218, 13, 51575], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.04068371813784363, "compression_ratio": 1.678714859437751, "no_speech_prob": 1.5614781603140448e-12}, {"id": 183, "seek": 88082, "start": 880.82, "end": 881.3000000000001, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 13, 50389], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07396958768367767, "compression_ratio": 1.4919786096256684, "no_speech_prob": 1.4782116503075926e-12}, {"id": 184, "seek": 88082, "start": 881.5200000000001, "end": 895.0200000000001, "text": " The UOM is the automated switching system. It routes the traffic, it prevents collisions, and it ensures continuous movement. But the UOM doesn't care what kind of train you place on those tracks. The operator library is the specific type of train you load onto the system.", "tokens": [50400, 440, 624, 5251, 307, 264, 18473, 16493, 1185, 13, 467, 18242, 264, 6419, 11, 309, 22367, 46537, 11, 293, 309, 28111, 10957, 3963, 13, 583, 264, 624, 5251, 1177, 380, 1127, 437, 733, 295, 3847, 291, 1081, 322, 729, 10218, 13, 440, 12973, 6405, 307, 264, 2685, 2010, 295, 3847, 291, 3677, 3911, 264, 1185, 13, 51075], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07396958768367767, "compression_ratio": 1.4919786096256684, "no_speech_prob": 1.4782116503075926e-12}, {"id": 185, "seek": 89502, "start": 895.02, "end": 900.54, "text": " So the train analogy is close, but it actually breaks down when we factor in the concurrency we just discussed.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 264, 3847, 21663, 307, 1998, 11, 457, 309, 767, 9857, 760, 562, 321, 5952, 294, 264, 23702, 10457, 321, 445, 7152, 13, 50641], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0859738537388989, "compression_ratio": 1.683168316831683, "no_speech_prob": 1.2643884420363016e-12}, {"id": 186, "seek": 89502, "start": 900.68, "end": 901.62, "text": " Oh, really? Why?", "tokens": [50648, 876, 11, 534, 30, 1545, 30, 50695], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0859738537388989, "compression_ratio": 1.683168316831683, "no_speech_prob": 1.2643884420363016e-12}, {"id": 187, "seek": 89502, "start": 901.8, "end": 911.0, "text": " Because a train implies a fixed linear vehicle traversing a path. The UOM is much more like a propagating wavefront through a physical medium.", "tokens": [50704, 1436, 257, 3847, 18779, 257, 6806, 8213, 5864, 23149, 278, 257, 3100, 13, 440, 624, 5251, 307, 709, 544, 411, 257, 12425, 990, 5772, 11496, 807, 257, 4001, 6399, 13, 51164], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0859738537388989, "compression_ratio": 1.683168316831683, "no_speech_prob": 1.2643884420363016e-12}, {"id": 188, "seek": 89502, "start": 911.16, "end": 911.84, "text": " A wavefront.", "tokens": [51172, 316, 5772, 11496, 13, 51206], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0859738537388989, "compression_ratio": 1.683168316831683, "no_speech_prob": 1.2643884420363016e-12}, {"id": 189, "seek": 89502, "start": 912.18, "end": 924.0799999999999, "text": " Right. The wavefront advances based solely on the structural integrity of the medium, the graph. The operator library determines the frequency and amplitude of that wave, but the UOM just facilitates the physical propagation.", "tokens": [51223, 1779, 13, 440, 5772, 11496, 25297, 2361, 23309, 322, 264, 15067, 16000, 295, 264, 6399, 11, 264, 4295, 13, 440, 12973, 6405, 24799, 264, 7893, 293, 27433, 295, 300, 5772, 11, 457, 264, 624, 5251, 445, 10217, 30035, 264, 4001, 38377, 13, 51818], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.0859738537388989, "compression_ratio": 1.683168316831683, "no_speech_prob": 1.2643884420363016e-12}, {"id": 190, "seek": 92408, "start": 924.08, "end": 930.7, "text": " Okay. I see the distinction. So if I instantiate the UOM and I plug in a strict Boolean operator library.", "tokens": [50365, 1033, 13, 286, 536, 264, 16844, 13, 407, 498, 286, 9836, 13024, 264, 624, 5251, 293, 286, 5452, 294, 257, 10910, 23351, 28499, 12973, 6405, 13, 50696], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10067888585532583, "compression_ratio": 1.5625, "no_speech_prob": 1.4050138006163615e-12}, {"id": 191, "seek": 92408, "start": 930.8000000000001, "end": 940.26, "text": " Then an operational node labeled ANDD functions as a standard logical gate. True and true yields true. The wavefront propagates deterministically.", "tokens": [50701, 1396, 364, 16607, 9984, 21335, 8093, 35, 6828, 382, 257, 3832, 14978, 8539, 13, 13587, 293, 2074, 32168, 2074, 13, 440, 5772, 11496, 12425, 1024, 15957, 20458, 13, 51174], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10067888585532583, "compression_ratio": 1.5625, "no_speech_prob": 1.4050138006163615e-12}, {"id": 192, "seek": 92408, "start": 940.5600000000001, "end": 946.22, "text": " Okay. But if I hot swap that library without changing the graph and inject a fuzzy logic library.", "tokens": [51189, 1033, 13, 583, 498, 286, 2368, 18135, 300, 6405, 1553, 4473, 264, 4295, 293, 10711, 257, 34710, 9952, 6405, 13, 51472], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10067888585532583, "compression_ratio": 1.5625, "no_speech_prob": 1.4050138006163615e-12}, {"id": 193, "seek": 94622, "start": 946.22, "end": 950.78, "text": " The underlying geometric graph, the track, so to speak, doesn't change by a single vector.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 14217, 33246, 4295, 11, 264, 2837, 11, 370, 281, 1710, 11, 1177, 380, 1319, 538, 257, 2167, 8062, 13, 50593], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07104576092499953, "compression_ratio": 1.519031141868512, "no_speech_prob": 1.3513189048644514e-12}, {"id": 194, "seek": 94622, "start": 951.0, "end": 960.76, "text": " But now that exact same ANDD node computes degrees of truth. Instead of a binary true or false, it might output, say, a 0.72 certainty threshold.", "tokens": [50604, 583, 586, 300, 1900, 912, 8093, 35, 9984, 715, 1819, 5310, 295, 3494, 13, 7156, 295, 257, 17434, 2074, 420, 7908, 11, 309, 1062, 5598, 11, 584, 11, 257, 1958, 13, 28890, 27022, 14678, 13, 51092], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07104576092499953, "compression_ratio": 1.519031141868512, "no_speech_prob": 1.3513189048644514e-12}, {"id": 195, "seek": 94622, "start": 961.14, "end": 966.82, "text": " The UOM routes the data identically. But the semantics of the history have fundamentally shifted.", "tokens": [51111, 440, 624, 5251, 18242, 264, 1412, 2473, 984, 13, 583, 264, 4361, 45298, 295, 264, 2503, 362, 17879, 18892, 13, 51395], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07104576092499953, "compression_ratio": 1.519031141868512, "no_speech_prob": 1.3513189048644514e-12}, {"id": 196, "seek": 94622, "start": 966.94, "end": 973.24, "text": " And the application that makes this truly revolutionary. If I swap in a differentiable operator library.", "tokens": [51401, 400, 264, 3861, 300, 1669, 341, 4908, 22687, 13, 759, 286, 18135, 294, 257, 819, 9364, 12973, 6405, 13, 51716], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.07104576092499953, "compression_ratio": 1.519031141868512, "no_speech_prob": 1.3513189048644514e-12}, {"id": 197, "seek": 97324, "start": 973.24, "end": 978.54, "text": " Then you instantly transition from a deterministic execution to a machine learning environment.", "tokens": [50365, 1396, 291, 13518, 6034, 490, 257, 15957, 3142, 15058, 281, 257, 3479, 2539, 2823, 13, 50630], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 198, "seek": 97324, "start": 978.72, "end": 979.2, "text": " Just like that.", "tokens": [50639, 1449, 411, 300, 13, 50663], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 199, "seek": 97324, "start": 979.36, "end": 985.28, "text": " Just like that. The input nodes become continuous tensors. The operator spheres become activation functions.", "tokens": [50671, 1449, 411, 300, 13, 440, 4846, 13891, 1813, 10957, 10688, 830, 13, 440, 12973, 41225, 1813, 24433, 6828, 13, 50967], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 200, "seek": 97324, "start": 985.6800000000001, "end": 988.86, "text": " And most importantly, that replay mechanism we discussed earlier.", "tokens": [50987, 400, 881, 8906, 11, 300, 23836, 7513, 321, 7152, 3071, 13, 51146], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 201, "seek": 97324, "start": 989.0600000000001, "end": 995.12, "text": " Oh. Because it maintains the full causal history, it acts as the perfect architecture for backpropagation.", "tokens": [51156, 876, 13, 1436, 309, 33385, 264, 1577, 38755, 2503, 11, 309, 10672, 382, 264, 2176, 9482, 337, 646, 79, 1513, 559, 399, 13, 51459], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 202, "seek": 97324, "start": 995.3, "end": 999.9, "text": " Exactly. You traverse the replay history backward to calculate the gradients for descent.", "tokens": [51468, 7587, 13, 509, 45674, 264, 23836, 2503, 23897, 281, 8873, 264, 2771, 2448, 337, 23475, 13, 51698], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12066906573725682, "compression_ratio": 1.6597938144329898, "no_speech_prob": 1.9356467383796483e-12}, {"id": 203, "seek": 99990, "start": 999.9, "end": 1005.48, "text": " You have one singular universal operator machine evaluating a single geometric graph.", "tokens": [50365, 509, 362, 472, 20010, 11455, 12973, 3479, 27479, 257, 2167, 33246, 4295, 13, 50644], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 204, "seek": 99990, "start": 1005.8199999999999, "end": 1014.3199999999999, "text": " And it is capable of executing Boolean logic, probabilistic reasoning, and deep neural network training purely by swapping the operator library.", "tokens": [50661, 400, 309, 307, 8189, 295, 32368, 23351, 28499, 9952, 11, 31959, 3142, 21577, 11, 293, 2452, 18161, 3209, 3097, 17491, 538, 1693, 10534, 264, 12973, 6405, 13, 51086], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 205, "seek": 99990, "start": 1014.4599999999999, "end": 1017.0, "text": " It is a stunning unification of computational logic.", "tokens": [51093, 467, 307, 257, 18550, 517, 3774, 295, 28270, 9952, 13, 51220], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 206, "seek": 99990, "start": 1017.4599999999999, "end": 1021.5799999999999, "text": " You aren't building disparate siloed execution engines for different tasks.", "tokens": [51243, 509, 3212, 380, 2390, 14548, 473, 3425, 78, 292, 15058, 12982, 337, 819, 9608, 13, 51449], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 207, "seek": 99990, "start": 1021.68, "end": 1026.08, "text": " You are simply altering the laws of physics inside a single geometric universe.", "tokens": [51454, 509, 366, 2935, 11337, 278, 264, 6064, 295, 10649, 1854, 257, 2167, 33246, 6445, 13, 51674], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 208, "seek": 99990, "start": 1026.2, "end": 1027.08, "text": " It's beautiful, really.", "tokens": [51680, 467, 311, 2238, 11, 534, 13, 51724], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1295177173614502, "compression_ratio": 1.6594982078853047, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054601646528724e-12}, {"id": 209, "seek": 102708, "start": 1027.08, "end": 1033.84, "text": " But this reliance on constructing and replaying history provides a rather dark bridge to Fliction's second paper.", "tokens": [50365, 583, 341, 1039, 6276, 322, 39969, 293, 23836, 278, 2503, 6417, 257, 2831, 2877, 7283, 281, 3235, 4105, 311, 1150, 3035, 13, 50703], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10392895340919495, "compression_ratio": 1.6151202749140894, "no_speech_prob": 1.6750290390832312e-12}, {"id": 210, "seek": 102708, "start": 1034.3999999999999, "end": 1034.6799999999998, "text": " It does.", "tokens": [50731, 467, 775, 13, 50745], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10392895340919495, "compression_ratio": 1.6151202749140894, "no_speech_prob": 1.6750290390832312e-12}, {"id": 211, "seek": 102708, "start": 1035.06, "end": 1044.6799999999998, "text": " Because if the entire system is predicated on the capacity to replay or repair a causal chain, what happens to the geometry when that capacity is destroyed?", "tokens": [50764, 1436, 498, 264, 2302, 1185, 307, 3852, 3587, 322, 264, 6042, 281, 23836, 420, 10535, 257, 38755, 5021, 11, 437, 2314, 281, 264, 18426, 562, 300, 6042, 307, 8937, 30, 51245], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10392895340919495, "compression_ratio": 1.6151202749140894, "no_speech_prob": 1.6750290390832312e-12}, {"id": 212, "seek": 102708, "start": 1045.1399999999999, "end": 1056.3, "text": " What's fascinating here is that Fliction takes this highly abstract calculus, which was designed for silicon environments, and seamlessly maps it onto biological and institutional observers.", "tokens": [51268, 708, 311, 10343, 510, 307, 300, 3235, 4105, 2516, 341, 5405, 12649, 33400, 11, 597, 390, 4761, 337, 22848, 12388, 11, 293, 38083, 11317, 309, 3911, 13910, 293, 18391, 48090, 13, 51826], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.10392895340919495, "compression_ratio": 1.6151202749140894, "no_speech_prob": 1.6750290390832312e-12}, {"id": 213, "seek": 105630, "start": 1056.3, "end": 1059.3799999999999, "text": " Which brings us to erasure is deformation.", "tokens": [50365, 3013, 5607, 505, 281, 1189, 2508, 307, 34364, 13, 50519], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 214, "seek": 105630, "start": 1059.84, "end": 1060.08, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50542, 1079, 13, 50554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 215, "seek": 105630, "start": 1060.84, "end": 1067.3999999999999, "text": " And he opens by entirely discarding the cognitive science consensus that memory is a storage mechanism.", "tokens": [50592, 400, 415, 9870, 538, 7696, 31597, 278, 264, 15605, 3497, 19115, 300, 4675, 307, 257, 6725, 7513, 13, 50920], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 216, "seek": 105630, "start": 1067.46, "end": 1072.1, "text": " Returning to our opening discussion, memory is not a box in the brain where engrams are filed away.", "tokens": [50923, 11495, 10656, 281, 527, 5193, 5017, 11, 4675, 307, 406, 257, 2424, 294, 264, 3567, 689, 465, 1342, 82, 366, 18789, 1314, 13, 51155], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 217, "seek": 105630, "start": 1072.22, "end": 1073.3999999999999, "text": " It is definitely not a box.", "tokens": [51161, 467, 307, 2138, 406, 257, 2424, 13, 51220], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 218, "seek": 105630, "start": 1073.62, "end": 1076.74, "text": " Fliction leans heavily into active inference models here.", "tokens": [51231, 3235, 4105, 476, 599, 10950, 666, 4967, 38253, 5245, 510, 13, 51387], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16124669710795084, "compression_ratio": 1.5529953917050692, "no_speech_prob": 1.7970248769941244e-12}, {"id": 219, "seek": 107674, "start": 1076.74, "end": 1084.64, "text": " To remember a distinction, whether it is the visual differentiation between a predator and prey, or the syntactic structure of a cryptographic passphrase.", "tokens": [50365, 1407, 1604, 257, 16844, 11, 1968, 309, 307, 264, 5056, 38902, 1296, 257, 35377, 293, 21107, 11, 420, 264, 23980, 19892, 3877, 295, 257, 9844, 12295, 1320, 44598, 651, 13, 50760], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 220, "seek": 107674, "start": 1084.7, "end": 1086.38, "text": " Like the one we couldn't remember earlier.", "tokens": [50763, 1743, 264, 472, 321, 2809, 380, 1604, 3071, 13, 50847], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 221, "seek": 107674, "start": 1086.52, "end": 1086.78, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50854, 1779, 13, 50867], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 222, "seek": 107674, "start": 1087.16, "end": 1089.58, "text": " Remembering that is not retrieving a static file.", "tokens": [50886, 5459, 278, 300, 307, 406, 19817, 798, 257, 13437, 3991, 13, 51007], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 223, "seek": 107674, "start": 1089.78, "end": 1093.14, "text": " To remember is strictly defined as possessing the repair repertoire.", "tokens": [51017, 1407, 1604, 307, 20792, 7642, 382, 17490, 278, 264, 10535, 49604, 13, 51185], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 224, "seek": 107674, "start": 1093.2, "end": 1094.08, "text": " Repair repertoire.", "tokens": [51188, 3696, 1246, 49604, 13, 51232], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15513848095405391, "compression_ratio": 1.6442307692307692, "no_speech_prob": 2.1253710597024522e-12}, {"id": 225, "seek": 109408, "start": 1094.08, "end": 1094.52, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50365, 1079, 13, 50387], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 226, "seek": 109408, "start": 1095.1399999999999, "end": 1102.82, "text": " It is the specific set of operators required to reconstruct that distinction after it has been perturbed by noise or time.", "tokens": [50418, 467, 307, 264, 2685, 992, 295, 19077, 4739, 281, 31499, 300, 16844, 934, 309, 575, 668, 13269, 374, 2883, 538, 5658, 420, 565, 13, 50802], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 227, "seek": 109408, "start": 1103.1599999999999, "end": 1103.3, "text": " Wait.", "tokens": [50819, 3802, 13, 50826], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 228, "seek": 109408, "start": 1103.56, "end": 1106.82, "text": " So, forgetting isn't the deletion of a file.", "tokens": [50839, 407, 11, 25428, 1943, 380, 264, 1103, 302, 313, 295, 257, 3991, 13, 51002], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 229, "seek": 109408, "start": 1107.0, "end": 1109.04, "text": " It's losing the tools to rebuild it.", "tokens": [51011, 467, 311, 7027, 264, 3873, 281, 16877, 309, 13, 51113], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 230, "seek": 109408, "start": 1109.22, "end": 1109.54, "text": " Correct.", "tokens": [51122, 12753, 13, 51138], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 231, "seek": 109408, "start": 1109.54, "end": 1113.96, "text": " Your memory is defined by your capacity to repair access to a state.", "tokens": [51138, 2260, 4675, 307, 7642, 538, 428, 6042, 281, 10535, 2105, 281, 257, 1785, 13, 51359], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 232, "seek": 109408, "start": 1114.1799999999998, "end": 1119.1599999999999, "text": " If you cannot repair the access, the state falls outside your universe of distinctions.", "tokens": [51370, 759, 291, 2644, 10535, 264, 2105, 11, 264, 1785, 8804, 2380, 428, 6445, 295, 1483, 49798, 13, 51619], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 233, "seek": 109408, "start": 1119.74, "end": 1122.8999999999999, "text": " And this physically alters the geometry of the observer's world.", "tokens": [51648, 400, 341, 9762, 419, 1559, 264, 18426, 295, 264, 27878, 311, 1002, 13, 51806], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1799052172693713, "compression_ratio": 1.6457564575645756, "no_speech_prob": 2.1760950246613175e-12}, {"id": 234, "seek": 112290, "start": 1122.9, "end": 1126.14, "text": " Fliction calls this admissibility contraction, right?", "tokens": [50365, 3235, 4105, 5498, 341, 5910, 891, 2841, 37372, 11, 558, 30, 50527], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 235, "seek": 112290, "start": 1126.3000000000002, "end": 1126.52, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50535, 1079, 13, 50546], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 236, "seek": 112290, "start": 1127.1200000000001, "end": 1130.7, "text": " The observer's reality is strictly bounded by their admissibility.", "tokens": [50576, 440, 27878, 311, 4103, 307, 20792, 37498, 538, 641, 5910, 891, 2841, 13, 50755], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 237, "seek": 112290, "start": 1131.2, "end": 1134.26, "text": " Manifold the total set of states they can successfully restore.", "tokens": [50780, 2458, 351, 2641, 264, 3217, 992, 295, 4368, 436, 393, 10727, 15227, 13, 50933], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 238, "seek": 112290, "start": 1134.44, "end": 1134.7, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50942, 1033, 13, 50955], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 239, "seek": 112290, "start": 1134.88, "end": 1136.7800000000002, "text": " When an operator is lost from the repertoire.", "tokens": [50964, 1133, 364, 12973, 307, 2731, 490, 264, 49604, 13, 51059], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 240, "seek": 112290, "start": 1137.2, "end": 1139.94, "text": " An erasure event that manifold literally contracts.", "tokens": [51080, 1107, 1189, 2508, 2280, 300, 47138, 3736, 13952, 13, 51217], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 241, "seek": 112290, "start": 1140.6200000000001, "end": 1143.66, "text": " The universe of restorable distinctions geometrically shrinks inward.", "tokens": [51251, 440, 6445, 295, 1472, 15249, 1483, 49798, 12956, 81, 984, 9884, 16431, 29876, 13, 51403], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 242, "seek": 112290, "start": 1144.26, "end": 1148.98, "text": " But if the boundaries of our internal world literally shrink when we forget, how is that quantified?", "tokens": [51433, 583, 498, 264, 13180, 295, 527, 6920, 1002, 3736, 23060, 562, 321, 2870, 11, 577, 307, 300, 4426, 2587, 30, 51669], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 243, "seek": 112290, "start": 1149.3400000000001, "end": 1151.8600000000001, "text": " Because Fliction doesn't just use this as a poetic metaphor.", "tokens": [51687, 1436, 3235, 4105, 1177, 380, 445, 764, 341, 382, 257, 41080, 19157, 13, 51813], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16083593666553497, "compression_ratio": 1.6881028938906752, "no_speech_prob": 1.73494324375717e-12}, {"id": 244, "seek": 115186, "start": 1151.86, "end": 1154.26, "text": " He proves it using differential geometry.", "tokens": [50365, 634, 25019, 309, 1228, 15756, 18426, 13, 50485], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 245, "seek": 115186, "start": 1154.4599999999998, "end": 1154.7199999999998, "text": " It does.", "tokens": [50495, 467, 775, 13, 50508], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 246, "seek": 115186, "start": 1155.08, "end": 1158.4199999999998, "text": " He models this using what he calls the erasure deformation tensor.", "tokens": [50526, 634, 5245, 341, 1228, 437, 415, 5498, 264, 1189, 2508, 34364, 40863, 13, 50693], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 247, "seek": 115186, "start": 1158.54, "end": 1158.6599999999999, "text": " Okay.", "tokens": [50699, 1033, 13, 50705], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 248, "seek": 115186, "start": 1158.82, "end": 1159.62, "text": " Break that down for me.", "tokens": [50713, 16925, 300, 760, 337, 385, 13, 50753], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 249, "seek": 115186, "start": 1159.8999999999999, "end": 1169.52, "text": " So, he treats the admissibility manifold as a remaining in space, where the loss of a repair operator directly alters the local metric tensor of that space.", "tokens": [50767, 407, 11, 415, 19566, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 47138, 382, 257, 8877, 294, 1901, 11, 689, 264, 4470, 295, 257, 10535, 12973, 3838, 419, 1559, 264, 2654, 20678, 40863, 295, 300, 1901, 13, 51248], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 250, "seek": 115186, "start": 1169.76, "end": 1170.06, "text": " Meaning?", "tokens": [51260, 19948, 30, 51275], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 251, "seek": 115186, "start": 1170.3799999999999, "end": 1174.6599999999999, "text": " Meaning it isn't just that a region of memory is cordoned off or locked away.", "tokens": [51291, 19948, 309, 1943, 380, 445, 300, 257, 4458, 295, 4675, 307, 12250, 19009, 766, 420, 9376, 1314, 13, 51505], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1503933925254672, "compression_ratio": 1.6024590163934427, "no_speech_prob": 1.8250409863918016e-12}, {"id": 252, "seek": 117466, "start": 1174.66, "end": 1179.3000000000002, "text": " The actual geometry of the space warps and generates singularities.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 3539, 18426, 295, 264, 1901, 1516, 1878, 293, 23815, 20010, 1088, 13, 50597], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 253, "seek": 117466, "start": 1179.72, "end": 1182.6200000000001, "text": " Let's ground this in the phenomenology of forgetting for a second.", "tokens": [50618, 961, 311, 2727, 341, 294, 264, 9388, 1793, 295, 25428, 337, 257, 1150, 13, 50763], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 254, "seek": 117466, "start": 1182.76, "end": 1185.26, "text": " Think of a word that is on the tip of your tongue.", "tokens": [50770, 6557, 295, 257, 1349, 300, 307, 322, 264, 4125, 295, 428, 10601, 13, 50895], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 255, "seek": 117466, "start": 1185.5800000000002, "end": 1185.76, "text": " Yeah.", "tokens": [50911, 865, 13, 50920], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 256, "seek": 117466, "start": 1185.96, "end": 1188.76, "text": " It takes immense mental energy to recall it.", "tokens": [50930, 467, 2516, 22920, 4973, 2281, 281, 9901, 309, 13, 51070], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 257, "seek": 117466, "start": 1189.02, "end": 1193.46, "text": " You are exerting, like, almost frustrating cognitive effort to retrieve it.", "tokens": [51083, 509, 366, 454, 27187, 11, 411, 11, 1920, 16522, 15605, 4630, 281, 30254, 309, 13, 51305], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 258, "seek": 117466, "start": 1193.5600000000002, "end": 1193.8000000000002, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51310, 1779, 13, 51322], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 259, "seek": 117466, "start": 1193.92, "end": 1195.8400000000001, "text": " And that cognitive strain is not an illusion.", "tokens": [51328, 400, 300, 15605, 14249, 307, 406, 364, 18854, 13, 51424], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 260, "seek": 117466, "start": 1196.4, "end": 1201.38, "text": " It is the direct physical manifestation of the metric distortion calculated by the tensor.", "tokens": [51452, 467, 307, 264, 2047, 4001, 29550, 295, 264, 20678, 28426, 15598, 538, 264, 40863, 13, 51701], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16901452200753347, "compression_ratio": 1.6170212765957446, "no_speech_prob": 1.8111273114920778e-12}, {"id": 261, "seek": 120138, "start": 1201.38, "end": 1201.98, "text": " Really?", "tokens": [50365, 4083, 30, 50395], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24925822019577026, "compression_ratio": 1.3732394366197183, "no_speech_prob": 1.6813161106410401e-12}, {"id": 262, "seek": 120138, "start": 1202.4, "end": 1202.66, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [50416, 1079, 13, 50429], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24925822019577026, "compression_ratio": 1.3732394366197183, "no_speech_prob": 1.6813161106410401e-12}, {"id": 263, "seek": 120138, "start": 1203.44, "end": 1211.96, "text": " As a specific memory approaches the boundary of your restorability as you lose the operators to reconstruct it, the metric distance to that memory stretches toward infinity.", "tokens": [50468, 1018, 257, 2685, 4675, 11587, 264, 12866, 295, 428, 46594, 2310, 382, 291, 3624, 264, 19077, 281, 31499, 309, 11, 264, 20678, 4560, 281, 300, 4675, 29058, 7361, 13202, 13, 50894], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24925822019577026, "compression_ratio": 1.3732394366197183, "no_speech_prob": 1.6813161106410401e-12}, {"id": 264, "seek": 120138, "start": 1212.18, "end": 1212.7, "text": " Oh, wow.", "tokens": [50905, 876, 11, 6076, 13, 50931], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.24925822019577026, "compression_ratio": 1.3732394366197183, "no_speech_prob": 1.6813161106410401e-12}, {"id": 265, "seek": 121270, "start": 1212.7, "end": 1219.1000000000001, "text": " The effort you feel is your cognitive apparatus attempting to drag its awareness across a severely deformed geometric space.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 4630, 291, 841, 307, 428, 15605, 38573, 22001, 281, 5286, 1080, 8888, 2108, 257, 26271, 368, 22892, 33246, 1901, 13, 50685], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 266, "seek": 121270, "start": 1219.1000000000001, "end": 1222.72, "text": " The distance to the memory is literally stretching toward infinity.", "tokens": [50685, 440, 4560, 281, 264, 4675, 307, 3736, 19632, 7361, 13202, 13, 50866], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 267, "seek": 121270, "start": 1223.52, "end": 1226.26, "text": " And this leads to the concept of the hysteresis functional.", "tokens": [50906, 400, 341, 6689, 281, 264, 3410, 295, 264, 35915, 9374, 11745, 13, 51043], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 268, "seek": 121270, "start": 1227.14, "end": 1231.26, "text": " Because traversing that deformed space is not symmetrical, is it?", "tokens": [51087, 1436, 23149, 278, 300, 368, 22892, 1901, 307, 406, 40360, 11, 307, 309, 30, 51293], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 269, "seek": 121270, "start": 1231.46, "end": 1231.96, "text": " Not at all.", "tokens": [51303, 1726, 412, 439, 13, 51328], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 270, "seek": 121270, "start": 1232.94, "end": 1240.3600000000001, "text": " Hysteresis, in state-space models, describes a system where the path forward is fundamentally different from the path backward.", "tokens": [51377, 5701, 3120, 9374, 11, 294, 1785, 12, 24824, 5245, 11, 15626, 257, 1185, 689, 264, 3100, 2128, 307, 17879, 819, 490, 264, 3100, 23897, 13, 51748], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 271, "seek": 121270, "start": 1240.82, "end": 1241.1200000000001, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51771, 1779, 13, 51786], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.20155968439011346, "compression_ratio": 1.6666666666666667, "no_speech_prob": 1.6815711149920087e-12}, {"id": 272, "seek": 124112, "start": 1241.12, "end": 1253.6999999999998, "text": " So, fliction applies a functional to map the asymmetry between the destruction cost, which is the energy required to lose an operator, and the restoration cost, the energy required to reacquire it.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 11, 932, 4105, 13165, 257, 11745, 281, 4471, 264, 37277, 9889, 1296, 264, 13563, 2063, 11, 597, 307, 264, 2281, 4739, 281, 3624, 364, 12973, 11, 293, 264, 23722, 2063, 11, 264, 2281, 4739, 281, 319, 326, 358, 621, 309, 13, 50994], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11651140235992799, "compression_ratio": 1.5953488372093023, "no_speech_prob": 1.5189534742846011e-12}, {"id": 273, "seek": 124112, "start": 1253.76, "end": 1256.3999999999999, "text": " Let's use an analogy of a physical landscape for this.", "tokens": [50997, 961, 311, 764, 364, 21663, 295, 257, 4001, 9661, 337, 341, 13, 51129], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11651140235992799, "compression_ratio": 1.5953488372093023, "no_speech_prob": 1.5189534742846011e-12}, {"id": 274, "seek": 124112, "start": 1256.54, "end": 1260.9599999999998, "text": " Imagine a specialized repair pathway as a trail through a dense forest.", "tokens": [51136, 11739, 257, 19813, 10535, 18590, 382, 257, 9924, 807, 257, 18011, 6719, 13, 51357], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11651140235992799, "compression_ratio": 1.5953488372093023, "no_speech_prob": 1.5189534742846011e-12}, {"id": 275, "seek": 124112, "start": 1261.12, "end": 1261.7399999999998, "text": " Okay, I like that.", "tokens": [51365, 1033, 11, 286, 411, 300, 13, 51396], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11651140235992799, "compression_ratio": 1.5953488372093023, "no_speech_prob": 1.5189534742846011e-12}, {"id": 276, "seek": 126174, "start": 1261.74, "end": 1268.86, "text": " Reversible forgetting where the restoration cost is high but not infinite is like allowing the trail to become severely overgrown with weeds.", "tokens": [50365, 1300, 840, 964, 25428, 689, 264, 23722, 2063, 307, 1090, 457, 406, 13785, 307, 411, 8293, 264, 9924, 281, 1813, 26271, 670, 38413, 365, 26370, 13, 50721], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 277, "seek": 126174, "start": 1269.22, "end": 1272.1, "text": " The destruction cost was simply the passive passage of time, right?", "tokens": [50739, 440, 13563, 2063, 390, 2935, 264, 14975, 11497, 295, 565, 11, 558, 30, 50883], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 278, "seek": 126174, "start": 1272.1, "end": 1273.14, "text": " We're just letting the weeds grow.", "tokens": [50883, 492, 434, 445, 8295, 264, 26370, 1852, 13, 50935], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 279, "seek": 126174, "start": 1273.36, "end": 1273.78, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50946, 7587, 13, 50967], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 280, "seek": 126174, "start": 1274.28, "end": 1279.18, "text": " But the restoration cost requires active physical labor to hack through the brush and clear the path.", "tokens": [50992, 583, 264, 23722, 2063, 7029, 4967, 4001, 5938, 281, 10339, 807, 264, 5287, 293, 1850, 264, 3100, 13, 51237], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 281, "seek": 126174, "start": 1279.6200000000001, "end": 1280.74, "text": " This is partial hysteresis.", "tokens": [51259, 639, 307, 14641, 35915, 9374, 13, 51315], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 282, "seek": 126174, "start": 1281.48, "end": 1281.74, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51352, 1079, 13, 51365], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 283, "seek": 126174, "start": 1281.92, "end": 1286.1200000000001, "text": " Very akin to attempting to write in a programming language you haven't used in a decade.", "tokens": [51374, 4372, 47540, 281, 22001, 281, 2464, 294, 257, 9410, 2856, 291, 2378, 380, 1143, 294, 257, 10378, 13, 51584], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 284, "seek": 126174, "start": 1286.28, "end": 1287.2, "text": " Oh, that's perfect.", "tokens": [51592, 876, 11, 300, 311, 2176, 13, 51638], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19681970612341618, "compression_ratio": 1.6402640264026402, "no_speech_prob": 2.0766342204853183e-12}, {"id": 285, "seek": 128720, "start": 1287.2, "end": 1297.3, "text": " The syntactic operators are heavily obscured by noise, the metric distance is stretched, but with sufficient cognitive effort, you can clear the path and restore the repertoire.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 23980, 19892, 19077, 366, 10950, 22082, 3831, 538, 5658, 11, 264, 20678, 4560, 307, 23563, 11, 457, 365, 11563, 15605, 4630, 11, 291, 393, 1850, 264, 3100, 293, 15227, 264, 49604, 13, 50870], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17800110946466893, "compression_ratio": 1.5491803278688525, "no_speech_prob": 1.4722214333046102e-12}, {"id": 286, "seek": 128720, "start": 1298.16, "end": 1301.6000000000001, "text": " But permanent forgetting where the hysteresis becomes infinite.", "tokens": [50913, 583, 10996, 25428, 689, 264, 35915, 9374, 3643, 13785, 13, 51085], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17800110946466893, "compression_ratio": 1.5491803278688525, "no_speech_prob": 1.4722214333046102e-12}, {"id": 287, "seek": 128720, "start": 1302.56, "end": 1308.88, "text": " That is like an entity paving a massive, reinforced concrete parking lot over that entire woods.", "tokens": [51133, 663, 307, 411, 364, 13977, 280, 6152, 257, 5994, 11, 31365, 9859, 9893, 688, 670, 300, 2302, 15296, 13, 51449], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17800110946466893, "compression_ratio": 1.5491803278688525, "no_speech_prob": 1.4722214333046102e-12}, {"id": 288, "seek": 128720, "start": 1309.18, "end": 1310.5800000000002, "text": " The destruction happens swiftly.", "tokens": [51464, 440, 13563, 2314, 49891, 13, 51534], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17800110946466893, "compression_ratio": 1.5491803278688525, "no_speech_prob": 1.4722214333046102e-12}, {"id": 289, "seek": 128720, "start": 1310.8400000000001, "end": 1311.1000000000001, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51547, 1779, 13, 51560], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17800110946466893, "compression_ratio": 1.5491803278688525, "no_speech_prob": 1.4722214333046102e-12}, {"id": 290, "seek": 131110, "start": 1311.1, "end": 1313.8799999999999, "text": " But the restoration cost is now functionally infinite.", "tokens": [50365, 583, 264, 23722, 2063, 307, 586, 2445, 379, 13785, 13, 50504], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 291, "seek": 131110, "start": 1314.4399999999998, "end": 1316.1, "text": " You cannot just clear the path anymore.", "tokens": [50532, 509, 2644, 445, 1850, 264, 3100, 3602, 13, 50615], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 292, "seek": 131110, "start": 1316.6999999999998, "end": 1322.4599999999998, "text": " You would have to demolish the concrete, reseed the soil, and wait decades for the ecosystem to regenerate.", "tokens": [50645, 509, 576, 362, 281, 26933, 742, 264, 9859, 11, 2025, 292, 264, 6704, 11, 293, 1699, 7878, 337, 264, 11311, 281, 26358, 473, 13, 50933], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 293, "seek": 131110, "start": 1322.8799999999999, "end": 1328.02, "text": " When the restoration cost reaches infinity, the distinction has crossed the irrestorability boundary.", "tokens": [50954, 1133, 264, 23722, 2063, 14235, 13202, 11, 264, 16844, 575, 14622, 264, 3418, 4149, 284, 2310, 12866, 13, 51211], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 294, "seek": 131110, "start": 1328.54, "end": 1331.9199999999998, "text": " And crossing that boundary does terrible things to the topology of the manifold.", "tokens": [51237, 400, 14712, 300, 12866, 775, 6237, 721, 281, 264, 1192, 1793, 295, 264, 47138, 13, 51406], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 295, "seek": 131110, "start": 1332.28, "end": 1334.6999999999998, "text": " We aren't just talking about distances stretching anymore.", "tokens": [51424, 492, 3212, 380, 445, 1417, 466, 22182, 19632, 3602, 13, 51545], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 296, "seek": 131110, "start": 1334.9199999999998, "end": 1339.32, "text": " We are talking about the fundamental shape of the observer's reality breaking down.", "tokens": [51556, 492, 366, 1417, 466, 264, 8088, 3909, 295, 264, 27878, 311, 4103, 7697, 760, 13, 51776], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13526999539342419, "compression_ratio": 1.8206896551724139, "no_speech_prob": 1.5489059687623374e-12}, {"id": 297, "seek": 133932, "start": 1339.32, "end": 1341.76, "text": " Right. Memory loss doesn't just stretch distances.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 38203, 4470, 1177, 380, 445, 5985, 22182, 13, 50487], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 298, "seek": 133932, "start": 1342.08, "end": 1344.96, "text": " It fundamentally changes the qualitative shape of what remains.", "tokens": [50503, 467, 17879, 2962, 264, 31312, 3909, 295, 437, 7023, 13, 50647], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 299, "seek": 133932, "start": 1345.52, "end": 1348.78, "text": " And Flixion maps this out using persistent homology, doesn't he?", "tokens": [50675, 400, 3235, 970, 313, 11317, 341, 484, 1228, 24315, 3655, 1793, 11, 1177, 380, 415, 30, 50838], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 300, "seek": 133932, "start": 1349.06, "end": 1349.48, "text": " He does.", "tokens": [50852, 634, 775, 13, 50873], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 301, "seek": 133932, "start": 1349.7, "end": 1357.1399999999999, "text": " He tracks how the topological features of the memory space evolve or devolve during these infinite cost erasure events.", "tokens": [50884, 634, 10218, 577, 264, 1192, 4383, 4122, 295, 264, 4675, 1901, 16693, 420, 1905, 37361, 1830, 613, 13785, 2063, 1189, 2508, 3931, 13, 51256], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 302, "seek": 133932, "start": 1357.26, "end": 1358.78, "text": " The persistence module of memory.", "tokens": [51262, 440, 37617, 10088, 295, 4675, 13, 51338], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 303, "seek": 133932, "start": 1358.96, "end": 1359.36, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51347, 7587, 13, 51367], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 304, "seek": 133932, "start": 1359.36, "end": 1366.32, "text": " He utilizes persistent homology to analyze the Betty numbers of the manifold as operators are iteratively removed.", "tokens": [51367, 634, 4976, 5660, 24315, 3655, 1793, 281, 12477, 264, 30270, 3547, 295, 264, 47138, 382, 19077, 366, 17138, 19020, 7261, 13, 51715], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15051705246671623, "compression_ratio": 1.6236933797909407, "no_speech_prob": 2.184802035468114e-12}, {"id": 305, "seek": 136632, "start": 1366.32, "end": 1370.3799999999999, "text": " And he identifies highly distinct topological modes of collapse.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 415, 34597, 5405, 10644, 1192, 4383, 14068, 295, 15584, 13, 50568], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 306, "seek": 136632, "start": 1370.98, "end": 1374.8799999999999, "text": " The most immediate is zero-dimensional collapse or fragmentation.", "tokens": [50598, 440, 881, 11629, 307, 4018, 12, 18759, 15584, 420, 9241, 19631, 13, 50793], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 307, "seek": 136632, "start": 1376.1599999999999, "end": 1378.6, "text": " How does zero-dimensional fragmentation actually manifest?", "tokens": [50857, 1012, 775, 4018, 12, 18759, 9241, 19631, 767, 10067, 30, 50979], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 308, "seek": 136632, "start": 1378.82, "end": 1379.6799999999998, "text": " What does that look like?", "tokens": [50990, 708, 775, 300, 574, 411, 30, 51033], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 309, "seek": 136632, "start": 1380.1, "end": 1385.74, "text": " Visualize the admissibility manifold as a massive, continuously connected simplicial complex.", "tokens": [51054, 23187, 1125, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 47138, 382, 257, 5994, 11, 15684, 4582, 1034, 4770, 831, 3997, 13, 51336], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 310, "seek": 136632, "start": 1385.8999999999999, "end": 1387.4199999999998, "text": " Like a huge interconnected web.", "tokens": [51344, 1743, 257, 2603, 36611, 3670, 13, 51420], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.19183260434633725, "compression_ratio": 1.5934579439252337, "no_speech_prob": 1.9056425274582844e-12}, {"id": 311, "seek": 138742, "start": 1387.42, "end": 1400.94, "text": " Right. If the observer loses a critical cut point operator, say, a fundamental piece of tacit knowledge that acts as a bridge between diverse domains, the complex shatters, the manifold fragments into entirely disconnected components.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 759, 264, 27878, 18293, 257, 4924, 1723, 935, 12973, 11, 584, 11, 257, 8088, 2522, 295, 25018, 270, 3601, 300, 10672, 382, 257, 7283, 1296, 9521, 25514, 11, 264, 3997, 402, 37690, 11, 264, 47138, 29197, 666, 7696, 29426, 6677, 13, 51041], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08976777675932487, "compression_ratio": 1.709090909090909, "no_speech_prob": 1.8037812996724023e-12}, {"id": 312, "seek": 138742, "start": 1401.3200000000002, "end": 1406.42, "text": " So you retain local clusters of highly functional memory, but they can no longer mutually relate to one another.", "tokens": [51060, 407, 291, 18340, 2654, 23313, 295, 5405, 11745, 4675, 11, 457, 436, 393, 572, 2854, 39144, 10961, 281, 472, 1071, 13, 51315], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08976777675932487, "compression_ratio": 1.709090909090909, "no_speech_prob": 1.8037812996724023e-12}, {"id": 313, "seek": 138742, "start": 1406.5600000000002, "end": 1406.8600000000001, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [51322, 7587, 13, 51337], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08976777675932487, "compression_ratio": 1.709090909090909, "no_speech_prob": 1.8037812996724023e-12}, {"id": 314, "seek": 138742, "start": 1407.02, "end": 1416.8000000000002, "text": " You might have pieces of memory that are perfectly intact, like an island of expertise in one domain and an intact island in another, but the geometric bridge allowing conceptual synthesis is just destroyed.", "tokens": [51345, 509, 1062, 362, 3755, 295, 4675, 300, 366, 6239, 23493, 11, 411, 364, 6077, 295, 11769, 294, 472, 9274, 293, 364, 23493, 6077, 294, 1071, 11, 457, 264, 33246, 7283, 8293, 24106, 30252, 307, 445, 8937, 13, 51834], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.08976777675932487, "compression_ratio": 1.709090909090909, "no_speech_prob": 1.8037812996724023e-12}, {"id": 315, "seek": 141680, "start": 1416.8, "end": 1428.98, "text": " The global connectivity of the observer is severed, but the mathematics reveal something significantly more counterintuitive when we look at one-dimensional topological collapse.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 4338, 21095, 295, 264, 27878, 307, 2802, 292, 11, 457, 264, 18666, 10658, 746, 10591, 544, 5682, 686, 48314, 562, 321, 574, 412, 472, 12, 18759, 1192, 4383, 15584, 13, 50974], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1461867332458496, "compression_ratio": 1.5178571428571428, "no_speech_prob": 1.8686031454800967e-12}, {"id": 316, "seek": 141680, "start": 1429.1599999999999, "end": 1433.62, "text": " Ah, this is the most bizarre consequence of the paper, the whole creation theorem.", "tokens": [50983, 2438, 11, 341, 307, 264, 881, 18265, 18326, 295, 264, 3035, 11, 264, 1379, 8016, 20904, 13, 51206], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1461867332458496, "compression_ratio": 1.5178571428571428, "no_speech_prob": 1.8686031454800967e-12}, {"id": 317, "seek": 141680, "start": 1433.82, "end": 1434.06, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51216, 1079, 13, 51228], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1461867332458496, "compression_ratio": 1.5178571428571428, "no_speech_prob": 1.8686031454800967e-12}, {"id": 318, "seek": 141680, "start": 1434.1599999999999, "end": 1437.48, "text": " Because it fundamentally challenges our intuition about information loss.", "tokens": [51233, 1436, 309, 17879, 4759, 527, 24002, 466, 1589, 4470, 13, 51399], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1461867332458496, "compression_ratio": 1.5178571428571428, "no_speech_prob": 1.8686031454800967e-12}, {"id": 319, "seek": 143748, "start": 1437.48, "end": 1448.24, "text": " We assume that losing data makes a system simpler, but fliction proves that removing a contractible region of operators can actually generate a non-contractible loop within the manifold.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 6552, 300, 7027, 1412, 1669, 257, 1185, 18587, 11, 457, 932, 4105, 25019, 300, 12720, 257, 4364, 964, 4458, 295, 19077, 393, 767, 8460, 257, 2107, 12, 9000, 1897, 964, 6367, 1951, 264, 47138, 13, 50903], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 320, "seek": 143748, "start": 1448.8, "end": 1448.9, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50931, 1779, 13, 50936], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 321, "seek": 143748, "start": 1449.04, "end": 1451.5, "text": " How can losing something make you more complex?", "tokens": [50943, 1012, 393, 7027, 746, 652, 291, 544, 3997, 30, 51066], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 322, "seek": 143748, "start": 1451.66, "end": 1454.22, "text": " Because you have carved a geometric void into the space.", "tokens": [51074, 1436, 291, 362, 28613, 257, 33246, 22009, 666, 264, 1901, 13, 51202], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 323, "seek": 143748, "start": 1454.68, "end": 1459.76, "text": " If you remove a solid cluster of operators, the system doesn't just cleanly shrink around it.", "tokens": [51225, 759, 291, 4159, 257, 5100, 13630, 295, 19077, 11, 264, 1185, 1177, 380, 445, 2541, 356, 23060, 926, 309, 13, 51479], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 324, "seek": 143748, "start": 1459.92, "end": 1462.74, "text": " It can leave behind an inaccessible repair cycle.", "tokens": [51487, 467, 393, 1856, 2261, 364, 33230, 780, 964, 10535, 6586, 13, 51628], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 325, "seek": 143748, "start": 1462.8, "end": 1463.98, "text": " A hole in their world.", "tokens": [51631, 316, 5458, 294, 641, 1002, 13, 51690], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13629752666026623, "compression_ratio": 1.6726618705035972, "no_speech_prob": 2.06047505446616e-12}, {"id": 326, "seek": 146398, "start": 1463.98, "end": 1464.56, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 50394], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 327, "seek": 146398, "start": 1465.18, "end": 1471.8, "text": " The observer develops the topological loop that orbits the missing core, but they lack the operators to traverse the interior space.", "tokens": [50425, 440, 27878, 25453, 264, 1192, 4383, 6367, 300, 43522, 264, 5361, 4965, 11, 457, 436, 5011, 264, 19077, 281, 45674, 264, 10636, 1901, 13, 50756], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 328, "seek": 146398, "start": 1472.26, "end": 1479.0, "text": " This maps flawlessly onto the clinical observation of confabulatory behavior in patients with severe neural trauma.", "tokens": [50779, 639, 11317, 13717, 12048, 3911, 264, 9115, 14816, 295, 1497, 14057, 4745, 5223, 294, 4209, 365, 8922, 18161, 11407, 13, 51116], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 329, "seek": 146398, "start": 1479.3, "end": 1479.6200000000001, "text": " It does.", "tokens": [51131, 467, 775, 13, 51147], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 330, "seek": 146398, "start": 1479.84, "end": 1490.64, "text": " When a patient with, say, Korsakoff syndrome or a specific brain lesion is asked a question that falls into their memory deficit, they don't always just say, I don't know.", "tokens": [51158, 1133, 257, 4537, 365, 11, 584, 11, 591, 830, 514, 4506, 19371, 420, 257, 2685, 3567, 1512, 313, 307, 2351, 257, 1168, 300, 8804, 666, 641, 4675, 22132, 11, 436, 500, 380, 1009, 445, 584, 11, 286, 500, 380, 458, 13, 51698], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 331, "seek": 146398, "start": 1490.8, "end": 1492.7, "text": " Often they don't even realize they don't know.", "tokens": [51706, 20043, 436, 500, 380, 754, 4325, 436, 500, 380, 458, 13, 51801], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09356429887854535, "compression_ratio": 1.6609589041095891, "no_speech_prob": 1.5671615481022139e-12}, {"id": 332, "seek": 149270, "start": 1492.7, "end": 1493.1000000000001, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 13, 50385], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 333, "seek": 149270, "start": 1493.26, "end": 1499.7, "text": " They will frequently generate elaborate, highly detailed, and entirely fabricated narratives to answer the question.", "tokens": [50393, 814, 486, 10374, 8460, 20945, 11, 5405, 9942, 11, 293, 7696, 7253, 770, 28016, 281, 1867, 264, 1168, 13, 50715], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 334, "seek": 149270, "start": 1500.1200000000001, "end": 1502.94, "text": " And they absolutely believe their own fabrication.", "tokens": [50736, 400, 436, 3122, 1697, 641, 1065, 44820, 13, 50877], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 335, "seek": 149270, "start": 1503.3, "end": 1508.66, "text": " And neurological models have historically struggled to explain the precise mechanism of that generative fabrication.", "tokens": [50895, 400, 48185, 5245, 362, 16180, 19023, 281, 2903, 264, 13600, 7513, 295, 300, 1337, 1166, 44820, 13, 51163], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 336, "seek": 149270, "start": 1509.02, "end": 1512.66, "text": " Why do they invent fliction's geometry provides the answer.", "tokens": [51181, 1545, 360, 436, 7962, 932, 4105, 311, 18426, 6417, 264, 1867, 13, 51363], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 337, "seek": 149270, "start": 1512.8600000000001, "end": 1517.74, "text": " The confabulation is the topological signature of a vector field flowing around a singularity.", "tokens": [51373, 440, 1497, 455, 2776, 307, 264, 1192, 4383, 13397, 295, 257, 8062, 2519, 13974, 926, 257, 20010, 507, 13, 51617], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11192621503557477, "compression_ratio": 1.6830188679245284, "no_speech_prob": 1.988805387737047e-12}, {"id": 338, "seek": 151774, "start": 1517.74, "end": 1518.22, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50365, 7587, 13, 50389], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12367679133559718, "compression_ratio": 1.540983606557377, "no_speech_prob": 1.6039872338322048e-12}, {"id": 339, "seek": 151774, "start": 1518.36, "end": 1527.28, "text": " The brain is attempting to maintain a continuous logical path through the manifold, but it is forced to navigate around a non-contractable one-dimensional hole.", "tokens": [50396, 440, 3567, 307, 22001, 281, 6909, 257, 10957, 14978, 3100, 807, 264, 47138, 11, 457, 309, 307, 7579, 281, 12350, 926, 257, 2107, 12, 9000, 1897, 712, 472, 12, 18759, 5458, 13, 50842], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12367679133559718, "compression_ratio": 1.540983606557377, "no_speech_prob": 1.6039872338322048e-12}, {"id": 340, "seek": 151774, "start": 1527.56, "end": 1528.68, "text": " It is circling the void.", "tokens": [50856, 467, 307, 3510, 1688, 264, 22009, 13, 50912], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12367679133559718, "compression_ratio": 1.540983606557377, "no_speech_prob": 1.6039872338322048e-12}, {"id": 341, "seek": 151774, "start": 1529.1200000000001, "end": 1533.48, "text": " The system is navigating around invisible topological constraints it can no longer see.", "tokens": [50934, 440, 1185, 307, 32054, 926, 14603, 1192, 4383, 18491, 309, 393, 572, 2854, 536, 13, 51152], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12367679133559718, "compression_ratio": 1.540983606557377, "no_speech_prob": 1.6039872338322048e-12}, {"id": 342, "seek": 153348, "start": 1533.48, "end": 1540.18, "text": " So the complexity of the false narrative is directly proportional to the size of the topological hole it is trying to bypass.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 264, 14024, 295, 264, 7908, 9977, 307, 3838, 24969, 281, 264, 2744, 295, 264, 1192, 4383, 5458, 309, 307, 1382, 281, 24996, 13, 50700], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.11071158306939262, "compression_ratio": 1.2626262626262625, "no_speech_prob": 1.7077939539963949e-12}, {"id": 343, "seek": 154018, "start": 1540.18, "end": 1546.3, "text": " It is a devastatingly elegant mathematical explanation for a tragic biological reality.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 307, 257, 21280, 356, 21117, 18894, 10835, 337, 257, 20385, 13910, 4103, 13, 50671], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 344, "seek": 154018, "start": 1546.8600000000001, "end": 1550.1000000000001, "text": " The system is operating perfectly within the constraints of its new geometry.", "tokens": [50699, 440, 1185, 307, 7447, 6239, 1951, 264, 18491, 295, 1080, 777, 18426, 13, 50861], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 345, "seek": 154018, "start": 1550.78, "end": 1555.04, "text": " It is simply that the geometry now contains invisible topological barriers.", "tokens": [50895, 467, 307, 2935, 300, 264, 18426, 586, 8306, 14603, 1192, 4383, 13565, 13, 51108], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 346, "seek": 154018, "start": 1555.28, "end": 1557.54, "text": " Which brings us to the real world scale of this.", "tokens": [51120, 3013, 5607, 505, 281, 264, 957, 1002, 4373, 295, 341, 13, 51233], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 347, "seek": 154018, "start": 1558.02, "end": 1560.9, "text": " Because these aren't just abstract mathematical proofs.", "tokens": [51257, 1436, 613, 3212, 380, 445, 12649, 18894, 8177, 82, 13, 51401], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 348, "seek": 154018, "start": 1561.24, "end": 1567.04, "text": " Fliction applies these exact geometric laws to real world biological and societal structures.", "tokens": [51418, 3235, 4105, 13165, 613, 1900, 33246, 6064, 281, 957, 1002, 13910, 293, 33472, 9227, 13, 51708], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1689592785305447, "compression_ratio": 1.7054263565891472, "no_speech_prob": 1.8040630838170313e-12}, {"id": 349, "seek": 156704, "start": 1567.04, "end": 1569.62, "text": " Right, because the calculus is scale invariant.", "tokens": [50365, 1779, 11, 570, 264, 33400, 307, 4373, 33270, 394, 13, 50494], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1045138180910886, "compression_ratio": 1.52863436123348, "no_speech_prob": 1.5796975273013603e-12}, {"id": 350, "seek": 156704, "start": 1570.04, "end": 1575.3, "text": " An observer, defined by a repair repertoire, doesn't have to be a single human brain.", "tokens": [50515, 1107, 27878, 11, 7642, 538, 257, 10535, 49604, 11, 1177, 380, 362, 281, 312, 257, 2167, 1952, 3567, 13, 50778], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1045138180910886, "compression_ratio": 1.52863436123348, "no_speech_prob": 1.5796975273013603e-12}, {"id": 351, "seek": 156704, "start": 1575.46, "end": 1576.18, "text": " What else could it be?", "tokens": [50786, 708, 1646, 727, 309, 312, 30, 50822], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1045138180910886, "compression_ratio": 1.52863436123348, "no_speech_prob": 1.5796975273013603e-12}, {"id": 352, "seek": 156704, "start": 1576.6, "end": 1587.1599999999999, "text": " Well, if an operator is a neural pathway, then the penumbra of an ischemic stroke, the tissue surrounding the core infarct, is a literal manifestation of the erasure deformation tensor.", "tokens": [50843, 1042, 11, 498, 364, 12973, 307, 257, 18161, 18590, 11, 550, 264, 3435, 2860, 424, 295, 364, 307, 339, 3438, 12403, 11, 264, 12404, 11498, 264, 4965, 1536, 289, 349, 11, 307, 257, 20411, 29550, 295, 264, 1189, 2508, 34364, 40863, 13, 51371], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1045138180910886, "compression_ratio": 1.52863436123348, "no_speech_prob": 1.5796975273013603e-12}, {"id": 353, "seek": 156704, "start": 1587.3, "end": 1587.68, "text": " Wow.", "tokens": [51378, 3153, 13, 51397], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1045138180910886, "compression_ratio": 1.52863436123348, "no_speech_prob": 1.5796975273013603e-12}, {"id": 354, "seek": 158768, "start": 1587.68, "end": 1597.4, "text": " It is a biological region where repair costs are actively stretching toward infinity, and clinical intervention is a race to prevent the manifold from topologically fragmenting.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 307, 257, 13910, 4458, 689, 10535, 5497, 366, 13022, 19632, 7361, 13202, 11, 293, 9115, 13176, 307, 257, 4569, 281, 4871, 264, 47138, 490, 1192, 17157, 26424, 278, 13, 50851], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 355, "seek": 158768, "start": 1597.48, "end": 1600.38, "text": " But we can scale the observer up even further, right?", "tokens": [50855, 583, 321, 393, 4373, 264, 27878, 493, 754, 3052, 11, 558, 30, 51000], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 356, "seek": 158768, "start": 1600.48, "end": 1605.0800000000002, "text": " An entire culture or institution operates under the exact same geometric constraints.", "tokens": [51005, 1107, 2302, 3713, 420, 7818, 22577, 833, 264, 1900, 912, 33246, 18491, 13, 51235], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 357, "seek": 158768, "start": 1605.38, "end": 1605.74, "text": " Absolutely.", "tokens": [51250, 7021, 13, 51268], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 358, "seek": 158768, "start": 1606.02, "end": 1607.68, "text": " Consider the phenomenon of language death.", "tokens": [51282, 17416, 264, 14029, 295, 2856, 2966, 13, 51365], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 359, "seek": 158768, "start": 1607.96, "end": 1614.68, "text": " A language is basically a distributed repair repertoire for specific semantic and cultural distinctions.", "tokens": [51379, 316, 2856, 307, 1936, 257, 12631, 10535, 49604, 337, 2685, 47982, 293, 6988, 1483, 49798, 13, 51715], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.1392001395529889, "compression_ratio": 1.667832167832168, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054640677806933e-12}, {"id": 360, "seek": 161468, "start": 1614.68, "end": 1617.6200000000001, "text": " The speakers themselves are the operators.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 9518, 2969, 366, 264, 19077, 13, 50512], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 361, "seek": 161468, "start": 1617.9, "end": 1618.0800000000002, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50526, 1779, 13, 50535], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 362, "seek": 161468, "start": 1618.3400000000001, "end": 1620.18, "text": " The people keep the distinctions alive.", "tokens": [50548, 440, 561, 1066, 264, 1483, 49798, 5465, 13, 50640], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 363, "seek": 161468, "start": 1620.98, "end": 1627.42, "text": " So as the speaker population undergoes attrition, the operators are removed from the global manifold.", "tokens": [50680, 407, 382, 264, 8145, 4415, 26426, 279, 951, 32938, 11, 264, 19077, 366, 7261, 490, 264, 4338, 47138, 13, 51002], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 364, "seek": 161468, "start": 1627.8400000000001, "end": 1633.3400000000001, "text": " The cost to maintain those specific cultural distinctions begins to stretch toward infinity.", "tokens": [51023, 440, 2063, 281, 6909, 729, 2685, 6988, 1483, 49798, 7338, 281, 5985, 7361, 13202, 13, 51298], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 365, "seek": 161468, "start": 1633.9, "end": 1642.54, "text": " The world of that language geometrically contracts, it fragments into disconnected dialects, and eventually it crosses the irrestorability boundary.", "tokens": [51326, 440, 1002, 295, 300, 2856, 12956, 81, 984, 13952, 11, 309, 29197, 666, 29426, 24652, 82, 11, 293, 4728, 309, 28467, 264, 3418, 4149, 284, 2310, 12866, 13, 51758], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 366, "seek": 161468, "start": 1642.74, "end": 1643.92, "text": " It becomes a dead language.", "tokens": [51768, 467, 3643, 257, 3116, 2856, 13, 51827], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.16313482983277575, "compression_ratio": 1.6948529411764706, "no_speech_prob": 1.708054379358226e-12}, {"id": 367, "seek": 164392, "start": 1643.92, "end": 1647.5600000000002, "text": " And the exact same principle applies to archive destruction.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 264, 1900, 912, 8665, 13165, 281, 23507, 13563, 13, 50547], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 368, "seek": 164392, "start": 1647.78, "end": 1648.68, "text": " Like burning books.", "tokens": [50558, 1743, 9488, 3642, 13, 50603], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 369, "seek": 164392, "start": 1648.92, "end": 1649.16, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50615, 1779, 13, 50627], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 370, "seek": 164392, "start": 1649.54, "end": 1658.16, "text": " When a society intentionally burns physical records or deletes institutional databases, they are intentionally inducing infinite historiesis.", "tokens": [50646, 1133, 257, 4086, 22062, 22684, 4001, 7724, 420, 1103, 37996, 18391, 22380, 11, 436, 366, 22062, 13716, 2175, 13785, 30631, 271, 13, 51077], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 371, "seek": 164392, "start": 1658.68, "end": 1661.76, "text": " The historical facts and legal precedents don't just disappear.", "tokens": [51103, 440, 8584, 9130, 293, 5089, 16969, 791, 500, 380, 445, 11596, 13, 51257], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 372, "seek": 164392, "start": 1662.2, "end": 1665.8400000000001, "text": " The societal manifold deforms such that those facts become permanently invisible.", "tokens": [51279, 440, 33472, 47138, 36094, 82, 1270, 300, 729, 9130, 1813, 24042, 14603, 13, 51461], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 373, "seek": 164392, "start": 1666.22, "end": 1671.5600000000002, "text": " The society structurally loses the capacity to even formulate the questions required to restore that knowledge.", "tokens": [51480, 440, 4086, 6594, 6512, 18293, 264, 6042, 281, 754, 47881, 264, 1651, 4739, 281, 15227, 300, 3601, 13, 51747], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 374, "seek": 164392, "start": 1671.8600000000001, "end": 1673.22, "text": " This raises an important question.", "tokens": [51762, 639, 19658, 364, 1021, 1168, 13, 51830], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15300603594098772, "compression_ratio": 1.6948051948051948, "no_speech_prob": 2.01256437730446e-12}, {"id": 375, "seek": 167322, "start": 1673.22, "end": 1678.8600000000001, "text": " How does this apply to systems that actively attempt to preserve knowledge, like the global scientific community?", "tokens": [50365, 1012, 775, 341, 3079, 281, 3652, 300, 13022, 5217, 281, 15665, 3601, 11, 411, 264, 4338, 8134, 1768, 30, 50647], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13278017873349396, "compression_ratio": 1.1770833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 2.4853992561940652e-12}, {"id": 376, "seek": 167886, "start": 1678.86, "end": 1680.24, "text": " Ah, yes.", "tokens": [50365, 2438, 11, 2086, 13, 50434], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.5163628033229283, "compression_ratio": 0.8, "no_speech_prob": 2.254231740508872e-12}, {"id": 377, "seek": 167886, "start": 1680.24, "end": 1682.1, "text": " The replication crisis.", "tokens": [50434, 440, 39911, 5869, 13, 50527], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.5163628033229283, "compression_ratio": 0.8, "no_speech_prob": 2.254231740508872e-12}, {"id": 378, "seek": 168210, "start": 1682.1, "end": 1692.28, "text": " Fliction dedicates a massive portion of the text to framing the replication crisis as a collective topological collapse, which is explosive.", "tokens": [50365, 3235, 4105, 37071, 1024, 257, 5994, 8044, 295, 264, 2487, 281, 28971, 264, 39911, 5869, 382, 257, 12590, 1192, 4383, 15584, 11, 597, 307, 24630, 13, 50874], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13874258313860213, "compression_ratio": 1.7129186602870814, "no_speech_prob": 2.219293108660092e-12}, {"id": 379, "seek": 168210, "start": 1692.56, "end": 1694.6599999999999, "text": " It is his most aggressive application of the theory.", "tokens": [50888, 467, 307, 702, 881, 10762, 3861, 295, 264, 5261, 13, 50993], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13874258313860213, "compression_ratio": 1.7129186602870814, "no_speech_prob": 2.219293108660092e-12}, {"id": 380, "seek": 168210, "start": 1695.52, "end": 1705.76, "text": " The replication crisis in the psychological and biomedical sciences is traditionally attributed to malicious pastman care, statistical anomalies, or outright fraud.", "tokens": [51036, 440, 39911, 5869, 294, 264, 14346, 293, 49775, 17677, 307, 19067, 30976, 281, 33496, 1791, 1601, 1127, 11, 22820, 24769, 48872, 11, 420, 35189, 14560, 13, 51548], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13874258313860213, "compression_ratio": 1.7129186602870814, "no_speech_prob": 2.219293108660092e-12}, {"id": 381, "seek": 170576, "start": 1705.76, "end": 1710.68, "text": " We assume the original researchers lied, or the current researchers are just incompetent.", "tokens": [50365, 492, 6552, 264, 3380, 10309, 20101, 11, 420, 264, 2190, 10309, 366, 445, 41602, 317, 13, 50611], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21306969137752757, "compression_ratio": 1.566326530612245, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054675372276453e-12}, {"id": 382, "seek": 170576, "start": 1710.82, "end": 1714.3799999999999, "text": " But Fliction models it as a failure of the admissibility boundary.", "tokens": [50618, 583, 3235, 4105, 5245, 309, 382, 257, 7763, 295, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 12866, 13, 50796], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21306969137752757, "compression_ratio": 1.566326530612245, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054675372276453e-12}, {"id": 383, "seek": 170576, "start": 1714.72, "end": 1716.22, "text": " A collective repair failure.", "tokens": [50813, 316, 12590, 10535, 7763, 13, 50888], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21306969137752757, "compression_ratio": 1.566326530612245, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054675372276453e-12}, {"id": 384, "seek": 170576, "start": 1716.28, "end": 1716.6, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50891, 7587, 13, 50907], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21306969137752757, "compression_ratio": 1.566326530612245, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054675372276453e-12}, {"id": 385, "seek": 170576, "start": 1717.12, "end": 1722.3, "text": " He argues that the scientific community fundamentally misunderstood the shape of its own admissibility manifold.", "tokens": [50933, 634, 38218, 300, 264, 8134, 1768, 17879, 33870, 264, 3909, 295, 1080, 1065, 5910, 891, 2841, 47138, 13, 51192], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.21306969137752757, "compression_ratio": 1.566326530612245, "no_speech_prob": 1.9054675372276453e-12}, {"id": 386, "seek": 172230, "start": 1722.3, "end": 1731.44, "text": " So when a pivotal study was published in, say, 1998, the community assumed that finding was now safely deposited in the storage box of human knowledge.", "tokens": [50365, 407, 562, 257, 39078, 2979, 390, 6572, 294, 11, 584, 11, 21404, 11, 264, 1768, 15895, 300, 5006, 390, 586, 11750, 42002, 294, 264, 6725, 2424, 295, 1952, 3601, 13, 50822], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13424419289204612, "compression_ratio": 1.5154639175257731, "no_speech_prob": 1.96595365854757e-12}, {"id": 387, "seek": 172230, "start": 1731.44, "end": 1733.02, "text": " They assumed the state was permanent.", "tokens": [50822, 814, 15895, 264, 1785, 390, 10996, 13, 50901], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13424419289204612, "compression_ratio": 1.5154639175257731, "no_speech_prob": 1.96595365854757e-12}, {"id": 388, "seek": 172230, "start": 1733.34, "end": 1735.1, "text": " Once it's in a journal, it's a permanent fact.", "tokens": [50917, 3443, 309, 311, 294, 257, 6708, 11, 309, 311, 257, 10996, 1186, 13, 51005], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13424419289204612, "compression_ratio": 1.5154639175257731, "no_speech_prob": 1.96595365854757e-12}, {"id": 389, "seek": 172230, "start": 1735.26, "end": 1737.84, "text": " But scientific knowledge requires continuous restoration.", "tokens": [51013, 583, 8134, 3601, 7029, 10957, 23722, 13, 51142], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13424419289204612, "compression_ratio": 1.5154639175257731, "no_speech_prob": 1.96595365854757e-12}, {"id": 390, "seek": 173784, "start": 1737.84, "end": 1754.08, "text": " The original result was dependent on highly specific, tacit, experimental operators, like the unique calibration of analog equipment, the localized environmental conditions of that specific lab, the undocumented physical techniques of the graduate students running the assays.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 3380, 1874, 390, 12334, 322, 5405, 2685, 11, 25018, 270, 11, 17069, 19077, 11, 411, 264, 3845, 38732, 295, 16660, 5927, 11, 264, 44574, 8303, 4487, 295, 300, 2685, 2715, 11, 264, 40472, 4001, 7512, 295, 264, 8080, 1731, 2614, 264, 1256, 3772, 13, 51177], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13479765723733342, "compression_ratio": 1.7315175097276265, "no_speech_prob": 1.4272686765098852e-12}, {"id": 391, "seek": 173784, "start": 1754.58, "end": 1757.3, "text": " Over 20 years, those graduate students retire.", "tokens": [51202, 4886, 945, 924, 11, 729, 8080, 1731, 10731, 13, 51338], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13479765723733342, "compression_ratio": 1.7315175097276265, "no_speech_prob": 1.4272686765098852e-12}, {"id": 392, "seek": 173784, "start": 1758.12, "end": 1762.6599999999999, "text": " The analog equipment is replaced by digital sensors with completely different noise floors.", "tokens": [51379, 440, 16660, 5927, 307, 10772, 538, 4562, 14840, 365, 2584, 819, 5658, 21008, 13, 51606], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13479765723733342, "compression_ratio": 1.7315175097276265, "no_speech_prob": 1.4272686765098852e-12}, {"id": 393, "seek": 173784, "start": 1763.32, "end": 1765.08, "text": " The tacit operators are lost.", "tokens": [51639, 440, 25018, 270, 19077, 366, 2731, 13, 51727], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.13479765723733342, "compression_ratio": 1.7315175097276265, "no_speech_prob": 1.4272686765098852e-12}, {"id": 394, "seek": 176508, "start": 1765.08, "end": 1769.0, "text": " And the admissibility boundary of the scientific community silently contracts.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 264, 5910, 891, 2841, 12866, 295, 264, 8134, 1768, 40087, 13952, 13, 50561], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 395, "seek": 176508, "start": 1769.62, "end": 1773.1399999999999, "text": " When modern researchers attempt to replicate the finding, they fail.", "tokens": [50592, 1133, 4363, 10309, 5217, 281, 25356, 264, 5006, 11, 436, 3061, 13, 50768], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 396, "seek": 176508, "start": 1773.52, "end": 1777.4199999999998, "text": " Not necessarily because the 1998 finding was fraudulent.", "tokens": [50787, 1726, 4725, 570, 264, 21404, 5006, 390, 14560, 23405, 13, 50982], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 397, "seek": 176508, "start": 1777.56, "end": 1783.8, "text": " But because that specific scientific distinction now lies outside the restorable boundary of the current manifold.", "tokens": [50989, 583, 570, 300, 2685, 8134, 16844, 586, 9134, 2380, 264, 1472, 15249, 12866, 295, 264, 2190, 47138, 13, 51301], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 398, "seek": 176508, "start": 1784.6, "end": 1790.62, "text": " Results that scientists thought were safely inside the restorable interior of knowledge were actually outside the boundary.", "tokens": [51341, 5015, 33361, 300, 7708, 1194, 645, 11750, 1854, 264, 1472, 15249, 10636, 295, 3601, 645, 767, 2380, 264, 12866, 13, 51642], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 399, "seek": 176508, "start": 1790.8799999999999, "end": 1792.48, "text": " The boundary was mislocated.", "tokens": [51655, 440, 12866, 390, 3346, 5842, 770, 13, 51735], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12384322349061357, "compression_ratio": 1.7878787878787878, "no_speech_prob": 1.7831991308905892e-12}, {"id": 400, "seek": 179248, "start": 1792.48, "end": 1794.98, "text": " The collective repair repertoire degraded.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 12590, 10535, 49604, 24740, 292, 13, 50490], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 401, "seek": 179248, "start": 1794.98, "end": 1801.74, "text": " And the hysteresis cost of perfectly recreating the 1998 experimental conditions just reached infinity.", "tokens": [50490, 400, 264, 35915, 9374, 2063, 295, 6239, 850, 44613, 264, 21404, 17069, 4487, 445, 6488, 13202, 13, 50828], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 402, "seek": 179248, "start": 1802.26, "end": 1802.72, "text": " Exactly.", "tokens": [50854, 7587, 13, 50877], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 403, "seek": 179248, "start": 1803.3, "end": 1807.96, "text": " When original techniques are lost, the scientific distinctions become permanently invisible.", "tokens": [50906, 1133, 3380, 7512, 366, 2731, 11, 264, 8134, 1483, 49798, 1813, 24042, 14603, 13, 51139], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 404, "seek": 179248, "start": 1808.54, "end": 1810.18, "text": " The knowledge hasn't been disproven.", "tokens": [51168, 440, 3601, 6132, 380, 668, 717, 4318, 553, 13, 51250], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 405, "seek": 179248, "start": 1810.58, "end": 1812.66, "text": " It has become topologically inaccessible.", "tokens": [51270, 467, 575, 1813, 1192, 17157, 33230, 780, 964, 13, 51374], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 406, "seek": 179248, "start": 1812.92, "end": 1821.38, "text": " The scientific community is navigating a space filled with topological holes, completely unaware that their geometric reality has shrunk.", "tokens": [51387, 440, 8134, 1768, 307, 32054, 257, 1901, 6412, 365, 1192, 4383, 8118, 11, 2584, 32065, 300, 641, 33246, 4103, 575, 9884, 3197, 13, 51810], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.17383498752240054, "compression_ratio": 1.6145833333333333, "no_speech_prob": 1.6751697685252198e-12}, {"id": 407, "seek": 182138, "start": 1821.38, "end": 1824.1000000000001, "text": " It's a sobering way to look at human progress.", "tokens": [50365, 467, 311, 257, 26212, 278, 636, 281, 574, 412, 1952, 4205, 13, 50501], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 408, "seek": 182138, "start": 1824.3000000000002, "end": 1825.2, "text": " So what does this all mean?", "tokens": [50511, 407, 437, 775, 341, 439, 914, 30, 50556], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 409, "seek": 182138, "start": 1825.7, "end": 1837.38, "text": " We have traversed from the fundamental flaws of the von Neumann architecture to the universal operator machine, all the way to the topological collapse of biological memory and scientific institutions.", "tokens": [50581, 492, 362, 23149, 292, 490, 264, 8088, 27108, 295, 264, 2957, 1734, 449, 969, 9482, 281, 264, 11455, 12973, 3479, 11, 439, 264, 636, 281, 264, 1192, 4383, 15584, 295, 13910, 4675, 293, 8134, 8142, 13, 51165], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 410, "seek": 182138, "start": 1838.2800000000002, "end": 1840.48, "text": " It means we must fundamentally abandon the chalkboard.", "tokens": [51210, 467, 1355, 321, 1633, 17879, 9072, 264, 28660, 3787, 13, 51320], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 411, "seek": 182138, "start": 1840.7800000000002, "end": 1841.7800000000002, "text": " The storage box.", "tokens": [51335, 440, 6725, 2424, 13, 51385], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 412, "seek": 182138, "start": 1841.94, "end": 1842.1200000000001, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [51393, 1779, 13, 51402], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.14618621152990005, "compression_ratio": 1.5301724137931034, "no_speech_prob": 2.0122601501748605e-12}, {"id": 413, "seek": 184212, "start": 1842.12, "end": 1850.3, "text": " The illusion of mutable state, of information as something you can simply store and erase without consequence, is a dangerous ontological error.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 18854, 295, 5839, 712, 1785, 11, 295, 1589, 382, 746, 291, 393, 2935, 3531, 293, 23525, 1553, 18326, 11, 307, 257, 5795, 6592, 4383, 6713, 13, 50774], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09145487952478153, "compression_ratio": 1.6872727272727273, "no_speech_prob": 2.210023180085341e-12}, {"id": 414, "seek": 184212, "start": 1850.3, "end": 1865.8999999999999, "text": " Whether we are architecting next-generation compilers inside a computer chip or analyzing the decay of human institutions, we must recognize that information is a living, irreversible, geometric landscape of historical construction and repair capacity.", "tokens": [50774, 8503, 321, 366, 6331, 278, 958, 12, 30372, 715, 388, 433, 1854, 257, 3820, 11409, 420, 23663, 264, 21039, 295, 1952, 8142, 11, 321, 1633, 5521, 300, 1589, 307, 257, 2647, 11, 16014, 840, 964, 11, 33246, 9661, 295, 8584, 6435, 293, 10535, 6042, 13, 51554], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09145487952478153, "compression_ratio": 1.6872727272727273, "no_speech_prob": 2.210023180085341e-12}, {"id": 415, "seek": 184212, "start": 1866.02, "end": 1867.06, "text": " You don't own information.", "tokens": [51560, 509, 500, 380, 1065, 1589, 13, 51612], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09145487952478153, "compression_ratio": 1.6872727272727273, "no_speech_prob": 2.210023180085341e-12}, {"id": 416, "seek": 184212, "start": 1867.2199999999998, "end": 1868.9599999999998, "text": " You only own the capacity to repair it.", "tokens": [51620, 509, 787, 1065, 264, 6042, 281, 10535, 309, 13, 51707], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.09145487952478153, "compression_ratio": 1.6872727272727273, "no_speech_prob": 2.210023180085341e-12}, {"id": 417, "seek": 186896, "start": 1868.96, "end": 1874.28, "text": " And that capacity dictates the boundaries of your reality, which leads me to a final provocative thought.", "tokens": [50365, 400, 300, 6042, 12569, 1024, 264, 13180, 295, 428, 4103, 11, 597, 6689, 385, 281, 257, 2572, 47663, 1194, 13, 50631], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15177786977667557, "compression_ratio": 1.4753086419753085, "no_speech_prob": 1.981363640865541e-12}, {"id": 418, "seek": 186896, "start": 1874.3600000000001, "end": 1879.48, "text": " Drawn from the very end of the source material, it deals with the concept of observer identity.", "tokens": [50635, 15971, 895, 490, 264, 588, 917, 295, 264, 4009, 2527, 11, 309, 11215, 365, 264, 3410, 295, 27878, 6575, 13, 50891], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15177786977667557, "compression_ratio": 1.4753086419753085, "no_speech_prob": 1.981363640865541e-12}, {"id": 419, "seek": 186896, "start": 1879.76, "end": 1879.98, "text": " Right.", "tokens": [50905, 1779, 13, 50916], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15177786977667557, "compression_ratio": 1.4753086419753085, "no_speech_prob": 1.981363640865541e-12}, {"id": 420, "seek": 186896, "start": 1880.22, "end": 1881.3600000000001, "text": " Observer identity deformation.", "tokens": [50928, 20707, 38241, 6575, 34364, 13, 50985], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.15177786977667557, "compression_ratio": 1.4753086419753085, "no_speech_prob": 1.981363640865541e-12}, {"id": 421, "seek": 188136, "start": 1881.36, "end": 1894.08, "text": " If an observer, whether that's an AI, runtime, a human being, or a civilization, is strictly defined by its repair repertoire, then its identity is mathematically equivalent to the shape of its admissibility manifold.", "tokens": [50365, 759, 364, 27878, 11, 1968, 300, 311, 364, 7318, 11, 34474, 11, 257, 1952, 885, 11, 420, 257, 18036, 11, 307, 20792, 7642, 538, 1080, 10535, 49604, 11, 550, 1080, 6575, 307, 44003, 10344, 281, 264, 3909, 295, 1080, 5910, 891, 2841, 47138, 13, 51001], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.060671254208213406, "compression_ratio": 1.6423076923076922, "no_speech_prob": 1.9204091442071025e-12}, {"id": 422, "seek": 188136, "start": 1894.32, "end": 1894.6399999999999, "text": " Yes.", "tokens": [51013, 1079, 13, 51029], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.060671254208213406, "compression_ratio": 1.6423076923076922, "no_speech_prob": 1.9204091442071025e-12}, {"id": 423, "seek": 188136, "start": 1894.82, "end": 1908.4399999999998, "text": " If you undergo a severe erasure event, if your repair repertoire contracts, if your manifold fragments and develops non-contractable topological holes, you do not merely become an observer who knows less.", "tokens": [51038, 759, 291, 26426, 257, 8922, 1189, 2508, 2280, 11, 498, 428, 10535, 49604, 13952, 11, 498, 428, 47138, 29197, 293, 25453, 2107, 12, 9000, 1897, 712, 1192, 4383, 8118, 11, 291, 360, 406, 17003, 1813, 364, 27878, 567, 3255, 1570, 13, 51719], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.060671254208213406, "compression_ratio": 1.6423076923076922, "no_speech_prob": 1.9204091442071025e-12}, {"id": 424, "seek": 190844, "start": 1908.44, "end": 1910.54, "text": " The mathematics are unforgiving on this point.", "tokens": [50365, 440, 18666, 366, 31411, 15441, 322, 341, 935, 13, 50470], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12205292628361629, "compression_ratio": 1.7525083612040133, "no_speech_prob": 1.6684808916422877e-12}, {"id": 425, "seek": 190844, "start": 1910.76, "end": 1913.94, "text": " In this framework, the original geometry has been destroyed.", "tokens": [50481, 682, 341, 8388, 11, 264, 3380, 18426, 575, 668, 8937, 13, 50640], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12205292628361629, "compression_ratio": 1.7525083612040133, "no_speech_prob": 1.6684808916422877e-12}, {"id": 426, "seek": 190844, "start": 1914.54, "end": 1916.98, "text": " Therefore, the original observer has ceased to exist.", "tokens": [50670, 7504, 11, 264, 3380, 27878, 575, 49917, 281, 2514, 13, 50792], "temperature": 0.0, "avg_logprob": -0.12205292628361629, "compression_ratio": 1.7525083612040133, "no_speech_prob": 1.6684808916422877e-12}, {"id": 427, "seek": 190844, "start": 1917.3, "end": 1922.48, "text": " Extreme memory loss, or the total collapse of an institutional archive, 